<FILEID>AP-NR-03-24-89 2359EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-Steinberg 4thLd-Writethru a0718 03-24 0980</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Steinberg, 4th Ld - Writethru, a0718,1005</SECOND>
<HEAD>Steinberg Sentenced To Maximum</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS 2 grafs after 9th graf, ``I feel ..., to UPDATE with
Nussbaum reax; SUBS 25th graf, `Steinberg would ..., with 2 grafs to clarify
that Steinberg would get time off only for good behavior, eligible for
parole in 7 years.</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY31, NY39, NY42</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SAMUEL MAULL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Joel Steinberg was sentenced Friday to the
maximum 8 1-3 to 25 years in prison for killing his illegally
adopted daughter in a case that riveted national attention on the
problems of domestic violence.
   Steinberg, a disbarred attorney, spoke about the charges for the
first time just before he was sentenced by state Supreme Court
Justice Harold Rothwax in Manhattan on his manslaughter conviction
for the 1987 death of 6-year-old Lisa Steinberg. Rothwax
recommended against parole.
   ``His extraordinary narcissism and self-involvement, his extreme
need to control everyone ... led him to become the instrument of
Lisa's death,'' Rothwax said before passing sentence. ``There is
nothing in the record to mitigate the extreme callousness and
harshness of his conduct.''
   Steinberg denied hitting the girl and said she received
``constant love.''
   ``Those children were not locked in a house of horror,''
Steinberg said of Lisa and the infant boy he also adopted illegally.
   But Assistant District Attorney John McCusker told the court
Lisa's death resulted from Steinberg's ``life of violence,
selfishness and self-gratification at the expense of other people.''
   ``Mr. Steinberg has shown not one ounce of remorse for killing
Elizabeth,'' McCusker said.
   ``I understand the meaning of remorse,'' said Steinberg, 47, who
did not testify at his trial. ``I have remorse about losing my
life.''
   ``I feel that pain every day,'' Steinberg told the judge, adding
that the loss belongs to all those ``whose life Lisa touched (and
received) the love that she gave.''
   Hedda Nussbaum, Steinberg's battered companion, watched the
sentencing on television at the Manhattan office of her attorney,
Betty Levinson, who quoted her as saying, ``How can he stand there
and lie with such a straight face?''
   ``He just got up there and lied and she's furious,'' Ms.
Levinson said of Ms. Nussbaum's reaction to Steinberg's statements.
``He was weaving together this totally untrue and fantastic
rendition of what happened.''
   Steinberg was convicted Jan. 30 of first-degree manslaughter in
Lisa's death but was acquitted of the more serious charge of
second-degree murder. He had received the child at birth from an
unmarried teen-ager and raised her as his own rather than
fulfilling his promise to arrange for the baby's adoption.
   On Nov. 2, 1987, Lisa was taken unconscious from the Greenwich
Village apartment Steinberg shared with Hedda Nussbaum. A
16-month-old boy also was found and eventually returned to his
natural mother.
   Lisa died three days later; murder charges were filed against
Steinberg and Ms. Nussbaum. Charges against Ms. Nussbaum were
dropped when prosecutors said she was ``so physically and mentally
incapacitated on the night of the murder that she was not
criminally responsible for Lisa's death.''
   In testimony against Steinberg, Ms. Nussbaum described an
11-year relationship with him that included beatings, brainwashing,
food deprivation, bizarre punishments and drug use.
   Steinberg told the judge Lisa received ``constant nurturing,
constant caring, constant love'' and desribed their relationship as
``joyous, superb, delightful.''
   Steinberg said he regretted a delay in medical attention that
may have contributed to Lisa's death.
   ``I feel I should have sensed when I came home a need for
medical attention,'' he said. ``If there was anything wrong with
Lisa when I left, I would not have left.''
   He denied hitting the child, but said, ``I don't deny that
during the course of administering CPR, OK, I could have caused
some'' injury. He dispassionately discussed the technical aspects
of Lisa's bruises.
   ``The testimony established Joel was basically a fine human
being,'' defense attorney Perry Reich said.
   Steinberg had a ``happy and cheerful nature'' and never hit
Lisa, Reich said.
   Steinberg smiled, chuckled and fidgeted while his lawyers
offered lengthy presentencing motions.
   Behind them sat Michele Launders, Lisa's biological mother, and
Grace Ann Smiegel, the grandmother of Travis, Steinberg's other
illegally adopted child. Both women cried when the sentence was
delivered and Mrs. Smiegel nodded in approval.
   ``It's a lie,'' Ms. Launders said after Steinberg's declaration
of mourning. ``I don't believe he feels anything. I don't think he
has the capability to feel for anybody but himself.''
   Four jurors and an alternate from the trial also attended the
sentencing. ``I think he deserved the maximum,'' said juror Allen
Jared.
   ``Society should be protected from him,'' said juror Helena
Barthell. ``I think he's a very violent person who committed a
terrible, heinous crime.''
   Under the general practice in New York, Steinberg would serve a
maximum of 16 years and eight months _ two-third of the legal
maximum _ if he earns time off for good behavior.
   Technically, Steinberg will be eligible for parole in seven
years because he has served 16 months of the 8 1-3-year minimum
term since he has been held without bail from the time of his
arrest on Nov. 2, 1987.
   Reich said a notice of appeal was filed Friday, adding, ``We're
very optimistic. It is fair to say this was just round one.''
   Rothwax received hundreds of letters _ from adoptive parents,
childless couples and people abused as children _ urging him to
give Steinberg the maximum term in Lisa's beating death.
   ``We had recommended that he get the maximum. Few defendants
have so richly deserved that recommendation,'' District Attorney
Robert Morgenthau said later. ``We hope the case serves as a
catalyst to stem child and drug abuse.''
   Court sources said the letters came from around the country and
as far away as Alaska and Florida. None of the letters recommended
leniency for Steinberg, the sources said; some demanded the death
penalty, which New York does not have.
</TEXT>
