<DOCNO> AP890324-0009 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-24-89 0215EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-FarmScene     03-24 0886</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Farm Scene,880</SECOND>
<HEAD>Winter Winds Skim Tons of Soil from Great Plains</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DON KENDALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Farm Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fierce winds have eroded nearly 4.7 million
acres of land in the Great Plains this winter, one of the most
extensive losses on record, according to an Agriculture Department
survey.
   ``Much of this damage is due to the drought,'' Wilson Scaling,
chief of the department's Soil Conservation Service, said Thursday.
``We went into the wind erosion season with poor cover in much of
the Great Plains because of the drought. Then this winter, we've had
a combination of no snow cover and high-velocity winds in many
areas.''
   Scaling said 88 percent of the acreage damaged was cropland, with
rangeland accounting for most of the remainder.
   The SCS surveys Great Plains damage annually from Nov. 1 through
the following May 31, a seven-month period when winds are highest
and soils are driest. The damage to 4.7 million acres was through
February.
   Scaling said the northern plains were hard hit, with Montana
showing damage to nearly 1.4 million acres, about 30 percent of the
10-state total. Losses in Montana and Wyoming have been greater than
at any time since SCS began the regular surveys in 1955.
   Agency records go back to the mid-1930s, but figures for some of
those years were obtained from other sources.
   The worst damage was done to about 16 million acres in 1954-55,
although the old Dust Bowl probably exceeded that in the early 1930s
before annual figures were compiled.
   But the 1987-88 season was bad, too, with more than 13 million
acres damaged in the region. Another was in 1980-81 when the agency
reported 12.5 million acres.
   Land is considered wind-damaged when the effects of wind are
apparent to the eye. By that time, according to conservationists,
the erosion rate has reached about 15 tons per acre a year, usually
at least three times faster than is ``tolerable,'' or naturally
replaceable.
   A loss of five tons per acre translates into a layer of soil
about the thickness of a dime spread over one acre.
   Scaling said farmers used emergency tillage on more than a
million acres to help reduce the blowing by roughing the surface
exposed to wind. Texas accounted for 80 percent of the emergency
tillage, about 880,000 acres.
   In addition to the land damaged during the four-month period,
Scaling said more than 22.5 million acres were ``in condition to
blow'' as of March 1, the most in 32 years. Highest on the list are
Kansas, North Dakota and Texas, he said.
   According to the survey, which was made in 541 counties of the
region's 10 states, here is the state-by-state breakdown comparing
damaged acres in November, December, January and February with the
same four months of 1987-88:
</TEXT>
<NOTE>Northern Plains</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   _Montana, 1,393,625 acres this season and 793,181 in 1987-88.
   _Nebraska, 81,180 and 68,485.
   _North Dakota, 474,200 and 813,680.
   _South Dakota, 407,980 and 360,520.
   _Wyoming, 474,863 and 223,966.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>Southern Plains</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Colorado, 154,550 and 119,400.
   Kansas, 520,905 and 82,600.
   New Mexico, 54,600 and 11,150.
   Oklahoma, 85,565 and 48,708.
   Texas, 1,047,791 and 893,865.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A new 55-page handbook has been designed by the
Agriculture Department to help farmers, shippers and local
communities cope with the loss of railroad service.
   Martin ``Buzz'' Fitzpatrick Jr., head of the department's Office
of Transportation, said Thursday the handbook contains information
on rural rail assistance from a number of sources and summarizes
regulations as these apply to rail abandonments.
   ``Many of the light-density branch lines being cast off are
located in agricultural regions,'' he said. ``Without rail
transportation, the marketing options of local producers are
limited.''
   The topics include abandonments, alternatives to abandonment, and
guidelines for evaluating the possibility of small railroad
operations. Information is included for potential buyers who have
little or no railroad experience.
   Fitzpatrick said many, if not all, of the major railroad
companies have programs or plans for assisting in line sales. And
many of those have worked with rural communities and shippers to
explore ways of retaining rail service. This information is also in
the handbook, he said.
   Copies of the booklet are being sent to federal, state and local
organizations involved in rural railroad service assistance, he
said. A limited supply is available free of charge for general
distribution.
   For more information, contact: John Batson, USDA-OT, P.O. Box
96575, Washington, D.C., 20090-6575. Or call 202 653-6108.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Agriculture Department says egg production
is down about 6 percent from a year ago, mostly reflecting a sharp
cutback by producers because of low prices last year.
   Total production during the first three months of the marketing
year that began Dec. 1 was estimated at 16.7 billion eggs, down from
17.7 billion a year earlier, the department said Thursday in a
report.
   As of March 1, laying hens totaled 271 million, down from 282
million a year ago. The March 1 flock included about 232 million
hens producing eggs for consumer use, and 38.9 million producers of
hatching-type eggs.
   The department's Economic Research Service says 1989 egg
production is expected to be down around 2 percent from last year
because of the reduction in laying hens.
   Producers cut back flocks in response to the lowest net returns
since USDA began estimating those figures in 1972, the agency said.
</TEXT>
