<FIRST>r w PM-NewLook     03-24 0633</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-New Look,630</SECOND>
<HEAD>WASHINGTON TODAY: Soviet Ambassador Exudes Glasnost</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Over spicy Thai shrimp and piquant vegetables
in a Washington restaurant jam-packed with reporters, Soviet
Ambassador Yuri V. Dubinin exuded glasnost and good cheer.
   Superpower relations are on the upswing, and Dubinin was all
smiles _ except on NATO's plan to extend the range of short-range
nuclear missiles.
   ``It's unacceptable, at any rate not for the Soviet Union but for
the process we are talking about,'' Dubinin said. ``It's just
something which is going against the mainstream of peaceable
development of the world. It's something which goes against the
process of disarmament.''
   His tone of voice serious, Dubinin added: ``There's absolutely no
need to do it, because we have begun in Europe a historic process of
reducing forces, unilaterally by the Soviet Union and multilaterally
in negotiations.''
   In any event, Dubinin said, the Soviet Union will not modernize
its own battlefield nuclear weapons. ``We are strongly in favor of
beginning negotiations to eliminate this class of weapons, too,'' he
said.
   Indeed, Soviet President Mikhail S. Gorbachev is on a disarmament
offensive, and the United States and its allies are caught up in the
process.
   A treaty in 1987 banned all U.S. and Soviet intermediate-range
nuclear missiles. Negotiations have begun in Vienna between NATO and
the Warsaw Pact to reduce tanks, antiaircraft artillery and possibly
other conventional armor in Europe.
   And Gorbachev is unilaterally cutting Soviet defense spending,
withdrawing six tank divisions from Eastern Europe, and has
announced a projected reduction of 500,000 troops overall.
   Dubinin fielded questions with ease after reading a prepared,
boilerplate speech. English is his fourth or fifth language, but
Dubinin needed only occasional help from an interpreter. And when he
was done, he gave an interview in Spanish to a journalist from
Madrid for good measure.
   Soviet news conferences, here and in Moscow, have become a
frequent occurrence. A few weeks ago, Dubinin called in American
reporters at the Soviet embassy and answered their questions for
nearly two hours.
   At the session Thursday at the Thai restaurant, Dubinin said the
Soviets would be willing to reduce their military aid to Nicaragua _
a bone in the U.S. throat _ as part of a peaceful settlement in
Central America.
   He said Jews were free to leave the Soviet Union, or to return,
if they wished, and even leave again. Perhaps, he suggested with a
smile, they were coming and going ``for the love of travel.''
   Dubinin said Moscow accepts as a ``reality'' the growing union in
Western Europe and said his government wants to develop ``a normal
relationship'' with the 12-country community.
   And he declined to criticize the Bush administration for delaying
a resumption of negotiations to reduce long-range nuclear missiles.
   ``The delay is a delay,'' he said. ``It's absolutely clear. But
we understand the new administration needs some time to get things
together. It's understandable.''
   The NATO plan to make U.S. Lance missiles more powerful also is
running into obstacles within the Western alliance. West German
Chancellor Helmut Kohl, with support from some other allied leaders,
is seeking a delay.
   The United States is determined to go ahead, but still has to
convince Kohl, whose chance for re-election next year may hinge on
the missile issue in a country where disarmament forces are strong.
   Congress, meanwhile, is unlikely to fund the modernization with
West Germany on the fence.
   Soviet criticism of the NATO plan could deepen the division
within the alliance. Whatever the outcome, Dubinin said the Soviets
would not modernize their own battlefield nuclear weapons.
   The ambassador spoke with the confidence of a government that
seems to believe momentum is on its side.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Barry Schweid has covered U.S.-Soviet diplomacy
for The Associated Press since 1973.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
