<FIRST>r w PM-DyingBrothers     03-24 0572</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Dying Brothers,570</SECOND>
<HEAD>Brothers with Terminal Disease See Bush, Tour Capitol</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JENNIFER DIXON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Showing Aaron and Nick Gerstler pictures of his
five children, Rep. Dick Armey explained how each has a different
personality. One son, Armey said, is a worrier.
   ``Does he worry about dying?'' asked one of the Gerstler brothers
in a quiet, small voice.
   Armey deftly changed the subject, and to the amazement of the
brothers from DeSoto, Texas, presented them with a flag that had
flown over the Capitol a day earlier.
   ``Is it ours?'' asked Aaron, 10.
   ``Where'd you get it?'' asked Nick, 9. ``Do we get to keep it?''
   And so began, Armey promised, a great adventure for two children
with Duchenne's muscular dystrophy, a rare form of the disease that
usually takes the life of its victims by the age of 15.
   With their parents, Harold W. and Penny, pushing their
wheelchairs, Armey in the lead, and Nick's twin sister, Angelee
scampering ahead of everyone, the little convoy set out to explore
the Capitol in the dim light of evening, when the click of heels on
the tiled floors resonates through the empty corridors.
   The brothers rubbed the feet of Will Rogers' statue for good
luck, saw where machine gun bullets grazed across a table in the
House chamber three decades ago, and blood stains that had seeped
into a marble staircase during a shootout involving a Kentucky
congressman and newspaper reporter in the early days of 1890.
   While on the floor of the House chamber, Aaron asked Armey if the
lawmakers leave a lot of trash littered about at the end of the day.
   ``They talk a lot of trash,'' said Armey, a Republican from
Texas. ``But they don't mess the place up.''
   ``You can't call anybody a bad name,'' Armey said, explaining how
congressmen ask each other ``Will the gentleman yield?'' when they
want to talk.
   ``We don't say shut up,'' said Armey, whose office arranged for
special tours for the boys during their week in Washington,
including visits to the FBI and a visit Thursday with President Bush
in the Oval Office.
   The boys said Bush showed them pictures of his new puppies, and
each child received an autographed picture of the president.
   Angelee was given a stick pin with the presidential crest. The
boys got tie clips.
   They gave the president a picture taken from above, of children
in one of their schools lined up to spell ``Drug Free,'' and stories
from Nick and Angelee's fellow third graders.
   Bush asked them about their tour of Washington, sponsored by the
non-profit ``A Wish for Wings'' in Arlington, Texas, which helps
children with life-threatening illness live out a wish that would
otherwise have been financially impossible.
   ``Meeting the president was an extra bonus,'' said the boys'
mother as the family shivered outside the White House in chilly
weather and no coats. ``We were really thrilled,''
   Mrs. Gerstler said the family had expected warmer weather, and
the jackets they had brought weren't dressy enough for the White
House.
   She said the trip to Washington was the boys' first choice for
their Wish with Wings, ahead of Hawaii and all the Nintendo games
ever made. The boys are A students with a big interest in social
studies, she said..
   ``I like the building,'' Aaron said of the Capitol. ``It's big. I
like the statues, all of the detail.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
