<FILEID>AP-NR-03-24-89 0023EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-HostageShot 4thLd-Writethru a0774 03-24 0891</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hostage Shot, 4th Ld-Writethru, a0774,0914</SECOND>
<HEAD>Suspect Shots Self, Captured In Abduction, Murder Of Two Women</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS grafs 19-21, `Shortly after ..., with 3 grafs to give identities
of murdered women.</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos DXA2,3</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVEN K. PAULSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LITTLETON, Colo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man on a rampage with a submachine gun
Thursday abducted a woman, killed her and her mother-in-law, then
raped another woman, was cornered by police and shot two officers
before fatally shooting himself, police said.
   The gunman, identified as Eugene Frank Thompson Jr., was taken
into custody with a head wound around 3 p.m. from a duplex in this
suburb south of Denver where he shot the officers who entered the
building on a house-to-house search.
   The suspect, armed with a MAC-11 submachine pistol, opened fire
on the two officers, hitting one in the chest and neck and wounding
the other with flying glass, as they entered a townhouse in the
Arapahoe Ridge subdivision.
   The gunman then shot a 18-year-old hostage in the back, and went
upstairs and shot himself in the head, police said.
   ``All he said was, `Jesus Christ, Jesus Christ, he shot me and
then went upstairs and shot himself,'' Arapahoe County Sheriff Pat
Sullivan quoted the hostage, Jake Carper, as saying.
   A police SWAT team rescued the wounded officers, lobbed flash
grenades into the house and found the hostage and Thompson, Sullivan
said.
   The gunman was taken with the wounded officers to Swedish Medical
Center, where he died at 5:56 p.m., said hospital spokeswoman
Beverly Jacobsen.
   Carper was in critical condition with multiple gunshot wounds;
Deputy Arthur L. Hilton, 37, was in serious condition with a chest
wound; and Deputy Daniel Thomas, 36, was in good condition with a
leg wound and face cuts, hospital officials said.
   Sullivan, a critic of assault rifle sales, said the gunman used
the semiautomatic MAC-11, which is sold over-the-counter, and that
said there was evidence the weapon had been modified to fire fully
automatic.
   When the weapon was recovered there were only five rounds left of
its 32-round magazine, he said.
   Authorities were at a loss to explain a motive for the one-man
crime wave.
   ``This man is ... extremely dangerous,'' said Douglas County
Sheriff's Lt. Bill Walker. ``We have four or five crime scenes and a
lot of people hurt and injured.''
   The state Department of Corrections said its only record of
Thompson was that he had been charged for second-degree burglary.
But he never served time in state prison, apparently having been
granted probation, officials said.
   Eugene Strauber, regional vice president of the Cenikor
Foundation cocaine residence treatment program in suburban Lakewood,
said Thompson had been enrolled in the program as part of his
probation and eventually was kicked out for stealing, but never
hinted at violence.
   ``He left about three months ago. We ask people how severe their
addictions are and he reported he had a $30-a-day cocaine habit. He
was a very average person. ... Not the type who stands out. He came
in at age 20 and had a long history of substance abuse,'' Strauber
said.
   ``He never exhibited mood swings here. If he had shown violent
behavior, we would not have allowed him to stay here,'' Strauber
said.
   More than 100 officers from three counties and the State Patrol
joined a manhunt in southern metropolitan Denver, where creeks with
grassy floodplains run amid housing subdivisions.
   Authorities said the man broke into a house in Jefferson County,
southwest of Denver, about 3 a.m., and a woman there called a police
emergency number. She hung up before she could give her address, but
authorities traced the call and found her garage door open, and the
woman and a car missing.
   Authorities said Thompson kidnapped Beverly J. Swartz, 47, from
her home in a burglary gone sour, and forced her to drive to the
home of her mother-in-law, Janice Irene Swartz, 68, in rural
Littleton.
   Shortly after 6 a.m., the Louviers Fire Department got a report
of shootings in a subdivision in Douglas County. Authorities found
the two women dead, and two men in shock.
   Douglas County Sheriff Steve Zotos said the women were tied up
and shot with a semiautomatic weapon. The two men were tied up but
not harmed and were able to untie themselves and telephone
authorities. Their names were not disclosed.
   The gunman then stole a car, and drove about 10 miles to a
southern Denver subdivision and pulled in behind a limousine that
had arrived to pick up residents.
   ``He pulled in behind the limousine, apparently assaulted the
limousine driver, and apparently the victim was either outside or
came outside and he forced her back into the house,'' Zotos said.
The woman's husband and an infant were also in the house.
   The gunman sexually assaulted the woman, then fled in the
limousine and wrecked it a short time later when he crashed into a
fence, authorities said. He fled on foot to the Arapahoe Ridge
house, about three blocks distant, and holed up with Carper. It was
not immediately clear whether Carper was living at the townhouse.
   Based on the damage to the car, authorities believed the man was
injured in the accident. The man was acting erratically, and may
have been taking drugs, Walker said.
   ``He's high on something, high and desperate for some reason.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890324-0021 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-24-89 0249EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Mexico-Subway     03-24 0541</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Mexico-Subway,0562</SECOND>
<HEAD>Subway Mashers Lead To Segregation By Sex</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Also in Friday AMs report.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANITA SNOW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It's 6 a.m. in the Pino Suarez subway station
and the transit police are dividing the river of morning commuters
rushing toward the trains: women on the right, men on the left.
   Any man found on the wrong side is apt to be publicly humiliated.
   ``Excuse me, sir,'' a uniformed official said to a young man
joining his female companion in the women's line.
   ``Over there,'' the officer ordered, pointing. Morning commuters
silently stared as the couple moved over.
   Mexico City has the only subway system that segregates its
passengers by sex during rush hour, said Miguel Gerardo Requis
Bustos, manager of stations and transportation.
   Women who use the Metro on weekdays between 5 a.m. to 9 a.m. and
4 p.m. to 9 p.m. say there's only one reason.
   ``They separate us because the men are abusive, they like to grab
the women,'' said seamstress Modesta Baez, 50, who rides the women's
cars daily. ``Women don't try to grab other women.''
   Itziar Lozano, a feminist counselor who has been sexually
harassed on the Metro, agreed.
   ``Although the women's cars are just as crowded, and you can't
move or breathe, you don't have to worry about sexual aggression,''
Lozano said.
   Requis said the segregated cars, which began 10 years ago, are
necessary for ``maintaining order'' on the subway. The modern system
daily moves an estimated 5 million people over almost 90 miles of
track.
   ``It is the only Metro in the world that gives additional
attention to women and children by separating them,'' Requis said.
``This way they can travel more comfortably.''
   Women can ride in the men's cars during rush hour, but men are
prohibited from the women's cars.
   Mexico City doesn't have a corner on Metro mashing, said Antonio
Santamaria, a psychoanalyst who has written extensively on Mexican
male aggression, known as machismo.
   He said such harassment occurs elsewhere, but the fact that
segregated subway cars exist only in Mexico says a lot about Mexican
culture.
   Santamaria believes the cars exist because Mexican men want to
protect their women from other men like themselves.
   ``You have to understand that this is a society in which the
woman is an object, something that can be carried away, taken,'' he
said.
   Ever since the Spanish conquistadores ran off with the Aztecs'
wives, the Mexican male has worried other males will try to
``steal'' his women, Santamaria said.
   That insecurity, says Santamaria, also leads the Mexican male to
try to conquer women who ``belong'' to others.
   Mexican writer Octavio Paz has said that to the Mexican, there
are only two possibilites: being the sexual aggressor or the one who
is violated.
   In his collection of essays, ``The Labyrinth of Solitude,'' Paz
writes, ``One word sums up the (male) aggressiveness, insensitivity,
invulnerability and other attributes of the macho: power.''
   Few men interviewed agreed with Santamaria's theory.
   ``It isn't machismo or a way to protect women from the damned
Mexicans,'' said Hector Castillo, an urban sociologist from the
National University of Mexico. ``It's just a space of greater
comfort for the women and children because the men are stronger.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
