<FIRST>r i PM-China-Journalists     03-24 0237</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-China-Journalists,0245</SECOND>
<HEAD>Chinese Suspend Canadian Journalist, Warn Two Others</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Western journalist has been prohibited from
working for one month in China after he broke Chinese regulations
and went to Tibet following the declaration of martial law.
   Two other reporters were given warnings by the Ministry of
Foreign Affairs.
   The ministry revoked the press credentials of Robert MacPherson,
a Canadian working for Agence France-Presse, for one month as of
Wednesday, MacPherson said today.
   He said the ministry accused him of violating a rule under which
all foreign journalists wishing to travel in China must inform
provincial authorities of their plans 10 days in advance.
   MacPherson admitted breaking the regulations, but those rules
often are relaxed by Chinese authorities in the interests of news
reporting.
   The Canadian went to Lhasa, Tibet's capital, on March 8, the day
martial law began. Chinese authorities imposed the crackdown after
three days' violence between Tibetan activists and Chinese security
forces left up to 30 people dead.
   The ministry also warned Guy Dinmore of Reuters and Jasper Becker
of the British newspaper the Guardian, according to the Reuters'
Beijing bureau.
   Both men had applied to go to Tibet 10 days before they arrived
there but the ministry said they did not receive permission.
   While in Lhasa, Dinmore was fined by police for allegedly
breaking Lhasa city regulations after he took photographs of
demonstrations. Becker also was questioned by police.
</TEXT>
