<HEAD>U.S. Orders Soviet Trade Official Home</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States has ordered a New York-based
Soviet trade official to leave the country in the latest round of
tit for tat diplomacy between Washington and Moscow.
   The ouster of Sergei Malinin, an employee of the Soviet trade
organization Amtorg, was in retaliation for Moscow's expulsion of a
U.S. Army attache from the Soviet Union last week.
   With two Soviets expelled from the United States and one American
from Moscow thus far this month, State Department spokesman Charles
Redman said Thursday that the U.S. government hopes there will be no
further expulsions.
   Redman, asked whether Malinin had engaged in wrongdoing, said
simply he was being declared persona non grata. ``We expect that Mr.
Malinin's departure will put an end to this matter,'' Redman said.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>___</NOTE>
<NOTE>Congress Urged to Narrow Insurance Industry's Exemptions</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bankers and consumer-advocacy groups say price
collusion has resulted from the insurance industry's exemptions from
antitrust laws.
   ``Consumers suspect they're not getting their money's worth from
insurers,'' said Philip S. Corwin of the American Bankers
Association, one of several witnesses who called on Congress
Thursday to narrow the antitrust exemptions.
   In testimony to the commerce, consumer protection and
competitiveness subcommittee of the House Energy and Commerce
Committee, Corwin endorsed in general terms a bill by the
subcommittee chairman, Rep. James J. Florio, D-N.J., to forbid some
collective activities that insurance companies may engage in under
their antitrust exemptions.
   Several insurance companies and trade groups argued against
Florio's bill, contending it would lead to a reduction in the number
of companies offering property and casualty insurance.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>___</NOTE>
<NOTE>FDA: Yellow Light on AIDS Home Tests</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Food and Drug Administration has lingering
concerns about the safety, accuracy and privacy of home AIDS-test
kits as currently proposed.
   FDA Commissioner Frank Young told the House subcommittee on
regulation, business opportunities and energy on Thursday that
``caution at this time is prudent'' because of concerns about
technical feasibility as well as privacy and counseling.
   ``In this disease ... there is a death sentence given with a
positive test and without the appropriate interpretation and
counseling, the Food and Drug Administration is apprehensive that
some individuals might not only have major psychological concerns
but might do themselves harm,'' Young said.
   More than a dozen companies indicated interest to the FDA last
year in developing home AIDS-testing kits, all requiring users to
collect blood samples at home and send them to laboratories for
testing. The results would be supplied by mail or telephone.
</TEXT>
