<FIRST>r a PM-TeenMurder     03-24 0386</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Teen Murder,0394</SECOND>
<HEAD>Neighbor Arrested, Held Without Bail in Teen's Murder</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAT MILTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MINEOLA, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Residents hope normalcy will return to their
street now that a neighbor has been charged in the killing of a
13-year-old girl whose beaten body was found in his basement.
   Robert Golub, 21, pleaded innocent to second-degree murder in the
death of Kelly Tinyes at his arraignment Thursday before Nassau
County Court Judge Marvin Goodman. He was ordered held without bail
pending a March 29 court appearance.
   ``I hope it will be all over now, and the neighborhood can go
back to normal,'' said George Milano, who lives across the street
from the Golubs. ``I just hope they got the right guy.''
   The Golub family has been staying with friends since a few days
after the slaying when authorities asked them to vacate their home
in the quiet suburb of Valley Stream so police could search for
evidence.
   The Golubs tried to return to their house on New York's Long
Island over the weekend, but angry neighbors and relatives of the
dead girl taunted and chased them, forcing them to pack up and leave
again.
   The slain girl's parents, Richard and Victoria Tinyes, stood
quietly in a courtroom hallway as Golub was arraigned. The two
families live on the same street in the suburb.
   ``We have forensic evidence at the scene that points to Robert
Golub. ... All of the evidence we do have points to him,'' said
Nassau County Chief of Detectives Wayne Seay after the arrest.
   A palm print _ in the slain girl's blood _ found on the basement
doorway was identified as Golub's, a source who spoke on condition
of anonymity told The Associated Press.
   ``There are still a lot of unanswered questions ... there's too
many missing pieces that are not adding up,'' said Robert Player,
Kelly's uncle and spokesman for the family. ``However, there is a
fraction of relief that someone is finally behind bars.''
   Kelly was stabbed with a World War I bayonet, strangled, slashed,
kicked and punched by her killer, authorities said. The bayonet was
also recovered, said Seay. He said the investigation was continuing.
   Kelly was last seen entering the Golub house March 3. Her body
was found in the basement there a day later.
</TEXT>
