<DOCNO> AP890324-0032 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-24-89 0236EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Japan-Markets     03-24 0351</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-Markets,0360</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Slightly Higher, Share Prices Off Marginally</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar closed higher against the Japanese
yen Friday, while share prices fell slightly on the Tokyo Stock
Exchange.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues, which gained
145.42 points Thursday, shed 20.14 points, or 0.06 percent, to
finish the week at 31,568.52.
   The dollar closed at 131.27 yen, up 0.39 yen from the previous
day's 130.88-yen finish. The currency started trading at 131.35 yen
and moved in a narrow range of 131.27-131.43 yen.
   The market's key index started falling shortly after the start of
morning trading as market investors began reacting to an overnight
drop in the Dow Jones industrial average in New York, said Tatsuo
Kurokawa with Nomura Securities in Tokyo.
   ``Because the Tokyo market, which has been adjusting its price
levels recently, was not in an uptrend with stock-buying incentives,
the drop in New York stocks directly affected the market,'' he said.
   The dollar's firmness in foreign exchange dealings also
discouraged participants, Kurokawa added.
   In currency dealings, the dollar's higher opening in Tokyo
followed an increase overnight in New York, where investors bought
the currency after U.S. Federal Reserve Board Governor H. Robert
Heller indicated he backed a stronger dollar, dealers said.
   Heller, in a speech Thursday before the Richmond, Virginia,
Society of Financial Analysts, said using a weaker dollar to improve
the U.S. trade balance would result in rising import prices,
aggravating U.S. inflation problems.
   Allowing that ``much work remains to be done'' on improving trade
imbalances, Heller said that ``under the present circumstances, a
dollar depreciation is unwarranted and uncalled for.''
   After opening higher, the dollar remained almost unchanged in
Tokyo Friday as Japanese investors stepped to the sidelines prior to
the start of the Easter holidays overseas, said one dealer with a
commercial bank in Tokyo, speaking on condition of anonymity.
   The New York currency market will be open Friday, but most U.S.
banks and other financial institutions will observe a three-day
Easter holiday weekend beginning the same day, while European
markets will be closed for four days until Tuesday.
</TEXT>
