<FIRST>r a PM-BombFound     03-24 0277</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bomb Found,0284</SECOND>
<HEAD>Police Detonate Letter Bomb Sent to Highway Patrol Chief</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LEN IWANSKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HELENA, Mont. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police removed and detonated a small bomb
that arrived in the mail at Montana Highway Patrol headquarters
after they were alerted by a secretary's suspicions.
   ``The bomb wasn't powerful enough to blow up a building, but it
could have seriously injured someone,'' Capt. George Olsen of the
Helena Police Department said Thursday evening.
   Col. Robert Griffith, the Highway Patrol's administrator, said
his secretary became suspicious of a parcel about the size of a box
of kitchen matches and addressed to ``Police Force, Capitol.''
   It arrived at his office Thursday afternoon.
   ``It was delivered to the mail room in the basement,'' Griffith
said. ``When the mail was brought up to us, my secretary looked at
it and felt it was a very suspicious-looking package. She said her
intuition or her instinct told her she'd better not open it.''
   The secretary, who was unidentified, took the parcel to state
Justice Department criminal investigators in the same building, a
block north of the Montana Capitol, and the investigators agreed the
package was suspect and notified Helena police, Griffith said.
   ``They came over and looked at it and they called the bomb
squad,'' he said.
   Police wrapped the parcel in a specially designed ``bomb
blanket,'' put it in a city dump truck filled with sand and took it
to a city-run auto salvage yard north of town, said Griffith. There,
police fired a shotgun into the parcel and it exploded, he said.
   Griffith said authorities had no idea who might have sent the
package, or about any motive.
</TEXT>
