<FIRST>r i PM-Nicaragua-Cardinal     03-24 0315</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Nicaragua-Cardinal,0326</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cardinal Says Sandinistas Should Have Declared Full Amnesty</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-US-Nicaragua, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RODOLFO GARCIA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Roman Catholic Cardinal Miguel Obando y
Bravo said the leftist government should have declared a general
amnesty for political prisoners rather than just releasing 1,894
former national guardsmen.
   Meanwhile in Washington, congressional and administration sources
said Thursday that President Bush and lawmakers had agreed on a plan
to extend aid to the Nicaraguan rebels, known as Contras, through
February 1990. The aid was to expire this month.
   Critics have said extending aid would violate a regional peace
plan that calls for democratic reforms in Nicaragua in exchange for
the dismantling of Contra forces that have fled to Honduras.
   However, the U.S. plan includes a pledge to back the February
peace accord and eventual reintegration of the rebels into
Nicaraguan political life, the sources in Washington said.
   Through most of the Reagan administration, the United States gave
arms to the rebels. In February 1988, Congress stopped military aid
but continued sending humanitarian assistance.
   About 11,000 Contras now live in camps in neighboring Honduras.
   In remarks during a homily for Holy Thursday services in Managua,
the cardinal said the Contras should release any political prisoners
they hold now that the Sandinista government has freed the guardsmen.
   He also said it would have been best if the government ``had
decreed a general amnesty, bringing joy to the prisoners and their
families and thereby contributing to national reconciliation.''
   On March 17, the Sandinistas freed 1,894 former National Guard
members who had been jailed since the July 1979 Sandinista
revolution.
   The guard members served under former President Anastasio Somoza,
who fled Nicaragua two days before the Sandinistas marched into the
capital.
   However, the government denied freedom to 39 other former
guardsmen who served under Somoza, saying they were guilty of
heinous crimes against the Nicaraguan people.
</TEXT>
