<DOCNO> AP890324-0044 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-24-89 0648EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Bhutto     03-24 0443</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bhutto,0462</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pakistan's Bhutto Thanks Military</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHY GANNON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Benazir Bhutto, Pakistan's first
elected leader in more than a decade and the Moslem world's only
female leader, has presented the military with a ``medal of
democracy.''
   She said Thursday that the award recognizes the military's
decision to step out of politics after 11 years of direct
involvement.
   ``We are proud of our armed forces who gave national interests
precedence over personal considerations,'' the prime minister said.
   A plane crash killed military strongman Mohammad Zia-ul Haq last
August, paving the way for the first free elections since 1977. That
year, a coup engineered by Zia ousted Bhutto's father, Zulfikar Ali
Bhutto, who was tried for state crimes and hanged in 1979.
   Several top generals and the U.S. ambassador died when Zia's
Hercules aircraft went down outside the city of Bahawalpur.
   Investigators say it was probably sabotage, but no definite cause
or suspect has ever been found.
   In a nationally televised speech, Ms. Bhutto also promised not to
break faith with the expectations of the people who propelled her to
power. ``We are determined to face every challenge with courage,
bravery and determination,'' she said.
   In 1940, seven years before Pakistan was carved from the western
edge of India, the nation's founding father Mohammad Ali Jinnah
promised his followers that the days of the British Raj were
numbered and formally declared independence. Pakistanis celebrated
that promise Thursday in what is called Pakistan Day, a national
holiday.
   Pakistan was created to give Moslems who felt maltreated by
India's majority Hindu population their own state.
   Reminiscent of colonial pomp, Pakistan's President Ghulam Ishaq
Khan arrived at Thursday's ceremonies in a gilded carriage.
   It passed in front of tanks, armored personnel carriers,
anti-aircraft weapons, long-range missiles and heavy artillery _ all
on display for the ceremonies.
   In her speech, Bhutto referred to the years of military rule
before her rise to power as an era of ``darkness everywhere.''
   ``There was a sense of want everywhere, clouds of pessimism and
helplessness were in all directions and there was tension on our
eastern and western frontiers.''
   Bhutto's left-of-center Pakistan People's Party won the largest
bloc of votes in general elections last November.
   The task before her government is formidable with a bankrupt
economy, ethnic unrest and an Afghan civil war that has sent more
than 3 million refugees fleeing to Pakistan.
   On Wednesday, Ms. Bhutto expanded her 23-member Cabinet to 41,
including her mother, Nusrat Bhutto.
   The elder Bhutto, co-chairman of the People's Party, won her
first election last November. She was named minister without
portfolio, several English-language daily newspapers reported
Thursday.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
