<SECOND>PM-Weatherpage Weather,0524</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rain Falls Along Atlantic and Pacific Coasts</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Rain drenched parts of the Atlantic and Pacific coasts today,
including areas in North Carolina that received over 2 inches from
an overnight storm.
   Since the rain began in the middle Atlantic states Thursday
night, about 2\ inches had fallen in Charlotte, N.C. Record
rainfalls for the date were set Thursday at Charlotte and
Wilmington, N.C.
   Freezing rain fell over portions of the central Appalachians.
Some power outages were reported south of Wilkesboro, N.C., as ice
accumulated on trees and power lines.
   In the West, rain was widespread over the central Pacific Coast
and snow was falling over the Sierra Nevada mountains. As of late
Thursday night, several inches of snow had fallen at Donner Pass,
Calif. Six to 8 inches of snow was expected to fall over higher
elevations near Lake Tahoe. Winds accompanying the snow have been
brisk, with a gust of 55 mph reported on a mountain peak northwest
of Reno, Nev.
   Rain showers also were widely scattered across the northern
Plains and upper Mississippi Valley.
   Heavier rainfall during the six hours ending at 1 a.m. EST
included over 1\ inch at Hampton, Va., and a little more than 1 inch
in Norfolk, Va.
   Friday's forecast: rain extending across much of the Atlantic
Coast region as well as across the central and northern
Appalachians, except Georgia and Florida, and from the northern and
central Pacific Coast across to southern and central Idaho;
scattered rain over northern Wisconsin and Minnesota; and sunny
skies over much of the remainder of the nation.
   High temperatures were to be in the 40s from northeast Montana
across much of the northern Plains and the upper Mississippi Valley
to Upper Michigan, as well as across much of the northern and middle
Atlantic Coast states; in the 70s and 80s from southern Georgia and
Florida across the eastern Gulf of Mexico Coast, the lower half of
the Mississippi Valley, the southern half of the Plains, the
southern Rockies and the southern Plateau to interior southern
California; and generally in the 50s and 60s over the remainder of
the Lower 48 states.
   Temperatures around the nation at 2 a.m. EST ranged from 7
degrees at Houlton, Maine, to 76 degrees at Key West, Fla.
   Other reports:
   _East: Atlanta 41 foggy; Boston 34 cloudy; Buffalo 34 cloudy;
Charleston, S.C., 46 foggy; Cincinnati 45 cloudy; Cleveland 40
cloudy; Detroit 32 fair; Miami 72 fair; New York 38 cloudy;
Philadelphia 38 rain; Pittsburgh 37 rain; Portland, Maine, 27
cloudy; Washington 40 rain.
   _Central: Bismarck 31 cloudy; Chicago 40 fair; Dallas-Fort Worth
52 partly cloudy; Denver 40 fair; Des Moines 40 fair; Indianapolis
38 fair; Kansas City 46 fair; Minneapolis-St. Paul 38 foggy;
Nashville 44 foggy; New Orleans 55 cloudy; St. Louis 43 fair.
   _West: Albuquerque 46 fair; Anchorage 33 cloudy; Las Vegas 64
windy; Los Angeles 57 cloudy; Phoenix 64 fair; Salt Lake City 43
partly cloudy; San Diego 57 cloudy; San Francisco 57 rain; Seattle
38 fair.
   _Canada: Montreal 19 fair; Toronto 34 cloudy.
</TEXT>
