<FIRST>r a PM-LASchools     03-24 0359</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-LA Schools,0372</SECOND>
<HEAD>Teachers' Union Threatens To Withhold Midterm Grades</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Teachers won't file midterm grades with the
nation's second-largest school district unless their contract
demands are met and will strike May 1 if threatened with loss of
paychecks, a union leader said.
   ``Withholding grades from the district puts the pressure on,''
United Teachers-Los Angeles President Wayne Johnson said Thursday.
``It means if we do want to take action at the end of the year, it
will be very effective.''
   If teachers keep their grade reports from the school district,
students would be given their grades on union-supplied report cards,
Johnson said.
   Associate Superintendent Gabriel Cortina said Thursday the
district doesn't plan to withhold paychecks, which it threatened to
do last month when teachers attempted to withhold final grades for
the fall semester.
   But he said some pay will be deducted from paychecks of teachers
who don't turn in the midterm grades, which are due April 7.
   ``We have maintained that if teachers do not perform the
assignment of preparing the report cards, they will be docked,'' he
said.
   Teachers on Feb. 7 voted almost 9-to-1 to authorize preparations
for a strike. A second strike vote is scheduled April 19.
   Los Angeles' last teachers strike was in 1970.
   Union leaders said they decided to urge teachers to withhold
midterm grades because they believe the district is planning to
close the schools for the summer two weeks early in order to foil a
union threat to strike in June. The midterm grades would then be
used as final grades for students, Johnson said.
   Both Cortina and Bill Honig, state superintendent of public
instruction, denied there is such a plan.
   ``Nobody's talked to me about it,'' Honig said. ``And there's no
way they (district officials) could do that. It would cost them a
fortune.''
   The teachers and administrators have been bargaining for more
than a year over a new contract for the district's 32,000 teachers
and have deadlocked over the issue of pay.
   The teachers want a 21 percent pay increase over two years, while
the district has offered a 20 percent pay hike over three years.
</TEXT>
