<FIRST>r i PM-Lebanon-Violence 1stLd-Writethru a0489 03-24 0538</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lebanon-Violence, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0489,0554</SECOND>
<HEAD>Arab League Tries to Stop Lebanese Bloodshed</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto BEI1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>Eds: Leads with 10 grafs to UPDATE with Aoun comments, Syrian envoy
meeting Hoss, U.S. withdrawing military team. Pickup 6th pvs, ``When Jassem...''
^By MOHAMMED SALAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Peace talks arranged by the Arab League
failed to halt fighting between Christian and Moslem troops today,
and the United States announced it is withdrawing a military
training team from Lebanon.
   Fighting between Christian army units and Druse militiamen and
their Syrian backers killed 81 people this month. Police said 15
died in the past 24 hours.
   The Arab League sent Kuwait's ambassador to Syria, Ahmed Jassem,
to meet today with Gen. Michel Aoun, commander of the 20,000-member
Christian force and leader of the Christian Cabinet in Lebanon's
splintered government.
   Jassem later met with acting Prime Minister Salim Hoss, chief of
the rival Moslem Cabinet battling for control of Lebanon.
   At a news conference after meeting Jassem, Aoun accused Syria of
seeking to ``reduce Lebanon to ashes.''
   The Syrian envoy said, ``Such a solution cannot be achieved in
one hour of talks.' Later, he refused to comment on a meeting with
Hoss in West Beirut.
   With no sign of an early breakthrough, the U.S. Embassy announced
it is pulling out three American officers sent in 1983 to train
Lebanese officers to use U.S. equipment bought earlier that year.
   ``We are withdrawing the technical assistance team at the Defense
Ministry as part the embassy's policy of reducing American personnel
due to the current situation,'' said a spokesman who declined to be
named.
   The spokesman denied Arab news reports that two of the Americans
were wounded in random artillery and rocket fire earlier this week.
   The embassy suspended consular services to non-Americans on
Wednesday.
   When Jassem was in Beirut on Tuesday, radio stations said Aoun
gave him a letter asking Syrian President Hafez Assad to withdraw
his 40,000 troops from Lebanon. Aoun and other Christian leaders say
the Syrians have failed in the peacekeeping task with which the Arab
League entrusted them in 1976.
   The Christians also bitterly criticize Syrian support for
Lebanese Moslems and leftists.
   Voice of the Nation, a radio station based in Moslem west Beirut,
said Aoun also sent a letter to President Bush requesting ``American
pressure on Israel to withdraw from south Lebanon.''
   Israel and allied Christian militiamen control a self-proclaimed
6-to-10-mile ``security zone'' in south Lebanon, to guard against
cross-border guerrilla raids on Israel.
   The day after Aoun sent his letters, Syrian army gunners joined
militiamen of Druse warlord Walid Jumblatt in shelling the country's
main Christian communities. About 1 million Christians live in a
crescent-shaped, 310-square-mile enclave that includes Christian
east Beirut.
   The prestigious daily newspaper An-Nahar said today the United
States, the Soviet Union, Britain, France and China were considering
making a joint demand for withdrawal of all non-Lebanese troops from
Lebanon. It did not elaborate.
   Charles Redman, U.S. State department spokesman, says all foreign
troops should be withdrawn, except United Nations peacekeepers in
south Lebanon.
   The lastest round of fighting in Lebanon began after Aoun's
forces blockaded illegal ports used by Moslem militias to import
military equipment and supplies sold in regions they control.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
