<FIRST>u i PM-Japan-Rescue 1stLd-Writethru a0501 03-24 0461</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan-Rescue, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0501,0469</SECOND>
<HEAD>Captain Says Ships Ignored Mayday Calls During Rescue Of Boat People</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs one graf for 9th graf, ``Survivors said ...'' to CORRECT
length of boat to 32 feet sted 320. Pickup 10th graf, ``They said ...''</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The captain of a Japanese tanker that helped rescue
Vietnamese refugees from a sinking boat said he radioed three nearby
ships for help but that they ignored his request, according to a
document obtained today.
   Survivors of the accident on March 8 say that 130 of the refugees
died when the boat sank after colliding with the tanker in the South
China Sea.
   But the tanker's log said that waves created by its propeller
capsized the boat which was in distress before the tanker arrived on
the scene.
   The accident went unreported in Japan until the 35 survivors of
the accident arrived in Yokohama on Monday.
   ``We radioed a mayday call to three large vessels between three
and five nautical miles from our ship, but there was no response,''
Yasuo Kawamura, captain of the Nissei-Maru tanker, wrote in his log.
A copy of the log was made available to The Associated Press today.
   The Maritime Safety Agency said it is investigating the accident,
the latest in a series involving the growing number of Vietnamese
fleeing political repression and economic hardship in their homeland.
   The refugees, known as boat people, risk piracy and disaster in
hopes of achieving asylum in other countries.
   Survivors and the captain have given different accounts of the
accident, which occurred between Malaysia and Vietnam.
   Survivors said 165 Vietnamese left Long An in southern Vietnam
aboard the 32-foot-long wooden boat on March 4, bound for Malaysia.
   They said their boat capsized and sank after colliding with the
propeller of the Nissei-Maru while seeking assistance from the
tanker.
   ``The tanker came very close to our boat, and the waves pushed us
into the ship,'' survivor Chan Kin Kan told the Japan Broadcasting
Corp. ``Our boat capsized. The children and others trapped in the
boat were drowned.''
   Kawamura's log, however, says that about 40 people were first
sighted on the fishing vessel, which appeared to be in distress. In
the process of rescuing the Vietnamese, their small wooden boat
drifted behind the 239,000-ton tanker and was capsized by strong
waves, he wrote.
   Hampered in its rescue effort by strong winds and ocean currents,
the Nissei-Maru asked for help at least four times from three nearby
vessels, including a tanker and a container ship, but they didn't
reply, Kawamura wrote.
   The Nissei-Maru conducted a seven-hour search, he said, and then
proceeded to Singapore, where the refugees were refused entry. They
were brought to Yokohama on another Japanese vessel after Japan
granted them entry.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
