<FILEID>AP-NR-03-24-89 1018EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-SouthAfrica     03-24 0351</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-South Africa,0359</SECOND>
<HEAD>Marchers Support South African Hunger Strikers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DURBAN, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hoisting crosses to symbolize the
plight of political detainees, protesters marched through Durban on
Good Friday. Some visited a sick prisoner who has not eaten for 35
days to protest his detention.
   The protesters visited Sandil Thusi at a hospital, where doctors
said his hunger strike could leave him blind and brain damaged.
Thusi has conducted the longest fast of 600 black detainees who
stopped eating for varying periods since January, demanding they be
freed or allowed to stand trial.
   Hunger strikers ``are being crucified for the truth,'' the Rev.
Wilfred Napier, president of the Southern African Catholic Bishops'
Conference, told an ecumenical church service held on Good Friday in
solidarity with the detainees. ``They are suffering for their
God-given rights,'' Napier told 1,000 people at the service,
including anti-apartheid leaders and U.S. and West German diplomats.
   South Africa's white-led government says it has authorized the
release of 580 detainees, but human rights groups say several
hundred activists remain held without charge.
   After the service, the crowd marched through the port city's
business district to an Anglican church. Two men hauled a large
wooden cross at the head of the procession. About 70 others carried
small crosses in their hands.
   Some of the protesters then delivered flowers to St. Aidan's
Hospital for Thusi, and about 10 of the marchers walked past police
guards into his room and sang an anti-apartheid anthem until they
were evicted.
   Seven journalists at the hospital, including television crews
from CBS and WTN, were taken to a police station for questioning.
Their video tapes were confiscated, one of the reporters said.
   The Law and Order Ministry said on Friday that Thusi's status
would not be reconsidered until he starts eating.
   Thusi, a 26-year-old university researcher, reportedly has lost
57 pounds, about one-third of his weight, during the fast to protest
his nine-month detention without trial. He underwent surgery
Thursday for an ear infection.
   Doctors have attached an intravenous drip to his arm, which
supplies some nutrition. They say his condition is critical.
</TEXT>
