<FIRST>r a PM-ZoningRuling     03-24 0322</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Zoning Ruling,0333</SECOND>
<HEAD>Towns Can't Restrict Number of People in Single-Family House: State
Court</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BAUDER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A couple who take in former psychiatric
patients as boarders successfully challenged a town zoning rule
limiting the number of unrelated people living in the same house.
   The New York state Court of Appeals, the state's top court, on
Thursday threw out a Long Island town's zoning law that restricted
the number of unrelated people living together, because the town did
not also restrict the number of related people who could live
together.
   ``I'm glad it's all over. It's been a long, drawn-out thing,''
said Rose Ann Baer of Brookhaven, who challenged the zoning ruling
along with her husband, Steve.
   The Baers, who have a Suffolk County license to run a rooming
house, were told in 1984 that they were in violation of town rules
nonetheless, because four women lived in the home along with the
couple's two children.
   The town's zoning law said no more than four unrelated people
could live under the same roof in a single-family district.
   Two women currently live in the home with the Baers, Ms. Baer
said.
   Her lawyer, Jane Reinhardt, said she was pleased with the
four-paragraph decision but disappointed with its brevity.
   ``I wish they had said some kind of socially conscious thing
about the need to help the elderly and disabled,'' Reinhardt said.
   Edwin Crawford, counsel for the state Association of Towns, said
the decision should make communities look more carefully at their
zoning laws. He predicted the decision wouldn't lead to a large
number of group or student homes opening in residential areas.
   ``This does not totally abrogate the ability of local governments
to use their zoning regulations to preserve the character of
single-family neighborhoods,'' Crawford said. ``It will just take
some careful draftsmanship.''
   Brookhaven's town attorney, David Fishbein, did not return a
telephone call seeking comment.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
