<FILEID>AP-NR-03-24-89 1037EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Laos     03-24 0328</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Laos,0338</SECOND>
<HEAD>Campaigning Ends In Unprecedented Laos Election</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MOLLY YONG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VIENTIANE, Laos (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A government official said Sunday's
parliamentary election will be another step toward ``socialist
democracy'' in the communist-ruled Southeast Asian nation.
   The 121 candidates contesting the 79 seats of the Supreme
People's Council, the highest state body, ended campaigning today.
   About 1.8 million of Laos' 3.8 million people are eligible to
vote, Somsavath Lengsavad, the secretary of the national election
committee, said on Friday. All those 18 years old or older can vote,
he said at a briefing.
   The council comprised 45 appointed officials when it was
established Dec. 2, 1975, when the Communist Party seized power
after a struggle over the U.S.-backed government in Vientiane.
   Somsavath said the candidates included seven women and averaged
40 years of age. Six candidates are from the Communist Party Central
Committee and 60 percent to 70 percent are party members, he said.
   He said results from the country's 4,153 polling stations would
be counted by hand, and the final tally would not be known for a
week to 10 days.
   He called the election ``another step toward socialist
democracy.''
   Official media has said it will draft communist Laos' first
constitution.
   Thailand's ambassador to Laos, Niran Panupong, has cited
unconfirmed reports that some senior officials may retire after the
election, including Prime Minister Kaysone Phomvihane, who is in his
late 60s, and acting President Phoumi Vongvichit, 80. Kaysone has
led the party since he co-founded it in 1955.
   Laos is one of the world's poorest nations, with an estimated per
capita income of $135 in 1985. In late 1986, the party endorsed
Western-style reforms to try to reverse a decade of socialist
policies.
   The first nationwide district and provincial elections were held
last year.
   But a Thai political scientist, Sirichai Sirikai, said the
election Sunday is designed only to endorse the legitimacy of those
in power and convince the world of Laos' political stability.
</TEXT>
