<FIRST>r i PM-Pope     03-24 0167</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Pope,0172</SECOND>
<HEAD>John Paul Hears Confessions of Seven on Good Friday</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VATICAN CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pope John Paul II heard the confessions of
six Italians and a West German religion teacher in St. Peter's
Basilica in keeping with a Good Friday tradition he began 10 years
ago.
   In the evening, the Roman Catholic leader was to carry a wooden
cross in a procession at the Colosseum symbolizing Christ's walk to
his crucifixion on Calvary Hill in Jerusalem.
   John Paul, carrying a black overcoat, appeared shortly after noon
in St. Peter's Basilica and stepped into one of the hand-carved
mahogany confessional booths.
   During the next 70 minutes, he heard confessions from a Frankfurt
religion teacher and two Italian military students, a laborer, a
transport worker, a 40-year-old woman and her 12-year-old son.
   As he left the confessional, the pope greeted several thousand
people who had gathered nearby to watch.
   John Paul began hearing confessions in the basilica on Good
Friday to emphasize the importance of the sacrament.
