<FIRST>r w PM-GingrichInvestor     03-24 0443</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Gingrich Investor,430</SECOND>
<HEAD>Georgia Democratic Official Involved in Gingrich Book Deal</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID PACE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A close adviser to Georgia's Democratic
governor said today he was one of the 21 investors who put up $5,000
each to promote a 1984 book by Rep. Newt Gingrich, the newly elected
House Republican whip.
   Joel Cowan, a Peachtree City, Ga., real estate developer who is
treasurer of the Georgia Democratic Party and the honorary chief of
staff to Gov. Joe Frank Harris, said in a telephone interview that
he invested in the book promotion deal because he thought Gingrich
had a message for the public.
   Cowan's participation in the book promotion deal was first
disclosed in today's Wall Street Journal. Gingrich earlier this week
promised to list all 21 investors once he has contacted them
personally.
   The Journal said Cowan's company, Cowan and Associates, received
a $204,480 grant from the Department of Housing and Urban
Development last year, but Cowan denied today that his company ever
received such a grant.
   ``Unless there is just a total lapse of memory and organization
on my part, I didn't get it,'' Cowan said. ``And if I'm right,
clearly somebody used my name to get a grant ... I'm going to get to
the bottom of it.''
   Cowan said he has never supported Gingrich politically and and
has never contributed to any of his congressional campaigns. He said
he made a $500 contribution last year to Gingrich's Democratic
opponent, David Worley.
   Cowan said he has had very little contact with Gingrich over the
years. He said he once wrote him recommending an appointment to the
Air Force Academy and once visited him in Washington when he was
making calls on all members of the Georgia delegation for Harris
shortly after his election in 1982.
   Cowan said he became interested in Gingrich's book, ``Window of
Opportunity,'' in 1983 when the congressman mentioned the project
during a speech to the Aspen Group, a mostly Republican group of
people involved in real estate.
   Cowan said he invited Gingrich to speak at that meeting because
``I thought he had a message. At the time he was speaking out on
supply-side economics and he was an outspoken conservative voice.''
   Cowan said the members of the group who attended the Aspen
meeting split the cost of Gingrich's travel and lodging expenses.
   The partnership created to promote Gingrich's book was to have
received half of the publisher's profits in exchange for their
investment. But there were not enough sales to produce profits and
Cowan said all he got for his $5,000 was six copies of the book and
a tax writeoff.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
