<FIRST>r i AM-Soviet-Awards     03-24 0227</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Awards,0234</SECOND>
<HEAD>Gorbachev Awards Air Hijack Hostage Team</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Mikhail S. Gorbachev on Friday honored
the task force that won the release of 30 young hostages in the
December hijacking of a Soviet jet to Israel.
   The task force, code-named ``Grom'' or ``thunder,'' was organized
quickly on Dec. 1 when an armed gang seized a busload of
fourth-graders and their teacher in the Caucasus town of
Ordzhonikidze.
   Gorbachev presented awards to the team, made up of
representatives from the Foreign Ministry, the KGB and the Civil
Aviation Ministry, at a ceremony in the Kremlin, Tass said.
   The four hijackers had demanded cash, weapons and a plane to fly
them to Israel. The Tass news agency said the captors didn't want to
leave the Soviet Union for any political or religious reasons, but
solely ``to enrich themselves.''
   The task force acceded to the hijackers' demands Dec. 2 after
they released the children unharmed.
   ``The Soviet leadership decided to do everything to save the
children,'' Tass said. ``The participants in the operation,
code-named `Grom,' had been told from the start not to take any
steps that might have endangered the kids' lives.''
   Israel sent the hijackers back to the Soviet Union, and on March
17, they were convicted. Ringleader Pavel Yakshiyants was sentenced
to 15 years in prison and three others received 14 years each.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
