<FIRST>u i PM-Dollar-Gold     03-24 0264</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Dollar-Gold,0276</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Steady in Quiet Good Friday Trading</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar was steady in very quiet trading in
Europe today, with most markets closed for the long Easter holiday
weekend.
   Gold and silver bullion markets in London, Zurich and Hong Kong
were closed.
   Market players said that with most European financial centers
closed for Good Friday, trading fizzled out with the winding down of
the Tokyo day. The European markets reopen on Tuesday.
   ``The last, shall we say operative, quotes were in Tokyo,'' said
a trader with a large Italian bank in Rome. He and others commented
that short of major new factors emerging to affect currencies during
the morning, it wasn't likely that any notable exchange rate moves
would take place.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day begins,
the dollar rose 0.39 yen to a closing 131.27 yen. Later in Europe it
was quoted at 131.30 yen.
   ``Nothing was happening in Tokyo trading today. Hardly anyone was
participating from the beginning, mainly because of long weekends on
overseas markets for the Easter holidays,'' said a dealer with Daiwa
Bank in Tokyo.
   In Europe, the British pound fell to $1.7185, compared with
$1.7205 Thursday.
   Other dollar rates at late morning in Europe, compared with late
Thursday:
   _1.8718 West German marks, down from 1.8720
   _1.6250 Swiss francs, down from 1.6260
   _6.3355 French francs, up from 6.3315
   _2.1138 Dutch guilders, up from 2.1025
   _1,376.10 Italian lire, up from 1,370.12
   A rate was not available for the dollars against the Canadian
dollar. The rate was 1.1894 Canadian dollars on Thursday.
</TEXT>
