<FILEID>AP-NR-03-24-89 1311EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-NRC-WitnessPaid     03-24 0610</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-NRC-Witness Paid,600</SECOND>
<HEAD>NRC Lawyer Warned Officials Against Paying Informants</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CALLAHAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Nuclear Regulatory Commission lawyer in 1986
warned officials against paying informants without congressional
approval, according to an internal document, but two years later the
agency paid a witness $4,000 for information against the NRC's No. 2
investigator.
   In a six-page memo dated Sept. 2, 1986, Assistant General Counsel
Hudson B. Ragan told NRC Investigations Director Ben B. Hayes that
informant payments ``would not be on sound legal ground,'' noting
that federal law and legislative history ``are all silent on the use
of such an investigative technique by the commission.''
   Ragan recommended that the commission either write such a
provision into the next year's NRC budget or seek informal approval
from Congress.
   But in an interview Thursday, Ragan said he believes such
payments can be made without congressional approval in special
circumstances where officials can prove the information is essential
to health and safety.
   Lawmakers and congressional aides who watch the NRC say they have
never heard of the commission paying informants and were shocked
earlier this week when Rep. Sam Gejdenson, D-Conn., obtained an NRC
contract detailing a $4,000 payment to Douglas S. Ellison, a former
technician at the Nine Mile Point plant in upstate New York.
   Gejdenson accused the commission of trying to undermine the
Office of Investigations by paying Ellison, who had accused the
office's deputy director, Roger A. Fortuna, of misconduct.
   In the 1986 memo, Ragan gave commission officials a detailed
analysis of administrative precedent in other agencies showing that
in all but one other case the U.S. comptroller general ``strongly
admonished'' agencies either to seek specific legislative authority
or to make sure Congress did not object.
   He also pointed to specific congressional authorizations of
informant payments in other agencies as a precedent.
   ``These enactments create the implication that such expenditures
should not be incurred except by express authority or by expressly
informing Congress that such expenditures will be incurred,'' Ragan
wrote.
   But in a telephone interview from the NRC's Rockville, Md.,
headquarters, Ragan said such congressional approval would be
necessary only if the commission wanted to create a regular program
to pay informants.
   ``The main thrust of the memorandum is `you just don't go
engaging in this kind of activity without advising Congress or
getting special authority unless you have special circumstances,'''
Ragan said.
   ``Generally speaking, any agency that can show a substantial need
for obtaining information that is not otherwise available to them
can use their appropriations to obtain that information,'' he said.
   ``Our type of cases have been based upon a specific need of
health and safety,'' he added. ``The instances that we have (paid
informants), to the best of my knowledge, are very few and far
between and we don't think we have to establish such a program.''
   Ragan said he believes there have been only two or three
instances of NRC payments to informants in the past 10 years.
   Ellison contends that Fortuna passed along confidential
information provided by Ellison to Stephen Comley, a Massachusetts
anti-nuclear activist.
   NRC officials, who are trying to fire Fortuna for his refusal to
testify on the Ellison allegations, say they will not discuss the
case because it is still pending.
   One NRC official close to the Fortuna investigation, who spoke on
the condition of anonymity, said Ellison was not an informer but a
consultant.
   But Ellison said in an interview earlier this week that he was
paid to testify and provide the commission with tapes of
conservations he secretly recorded.
   The NRC official argued that Ellison's explanation and
interpretations of the tapes constituted consulting work.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890324-0086 </DOCNO>
