<FIRST>u a PM-AbortionProtests 2ndLd-Writethru a0542 03-24 0664</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Abortion Protests, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0542,0678</SECOND>
<HEAD>Good Friday Anti-Abortion Protests Reported In Several Cities</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto AB1</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 11 grafs to UPDATE with new California demonstrations,
protests in Syracuse, Philadelphia, Detroit. Pickup 9th graf, `Leaders
of...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JUDY FARAH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Chanting anti-abortion protesters gathered at
a health clinic today and pro-choice demonstrators followed as a
group called Operation Rescue went into the second day of its Holy
Week crusade against abortion.
   Police said about 150 abortion foes showed up at a clinic in Long
Beach early this morning, a day after 373 Operation Rescue members
were arrested while defying a court order and blockading a clinic in
suburban Cypress.
   There were no immediate arrests in Long Beach, said Lt. Columbus
Lowe.
   A caravan of Operation Rescue members earlier passed by a clinic
on Long Beach Boulevard where pro-choice demonstrators were already
waiting.
   Pro-choice forces have been stationed at mobilization centers
from which they can be dispatched to counter Operation Rescue
protests.
   Operation Rescue opened its Southern California campaign of civil
disobedience on Thursday in Orange County. About 500 protesters sang
hymns and prayed at the Family Planning Associates Medical Clinic in
Cypress, about 20 miles southeast of Los Angeles.
   Elsewhere today, more than 200 anti-abortion protesters in
Albany, N.Y., staged a Good Friday demonstration at a Planned
Parenthood clinic, with police reporting 80 to 100 arrests by
midmorning. Fifty protesters were charged with trespassing in
Syracuse for entering a Planned Parenthood center, while another 100
protested outside.
   Police arrested 124 protesters _ four busloads _ who gathered in
rain and gusting winds outside a downtown Philadelphia clinic, three
days after a federal judge barred such protests in the area. At a
second downtown site, 500 demonstrators assembled but left when they
learned patients had entered through a back door. Abortion rights
advocates staged a counterdemonstration.
   Some 100 demonstrators in the Detroit suburb of Farmington Hills
similarly dispersed when they found a clinic closed, said police
Inspector Richard Niemisto. In Cincinnati, 30 to 35 demonstrators in
front of two women's clinics were orderly and there were no arrests.
   Southern California was targeted as the center of most pre-Easter
National Week of Rescue because of its high abortion rate and many
clinics, organizers said.
   Operation Rescue has staged many similar protests throughout the
country, most notably during the Democratic National Convention in
Atlanta last summer.
   Leaders of the group had vowed to risk arrest by defying a
federal court order obtained by the American Civil Liberties Union
that prohibited protesters from blocking entrances or gathering
within 15 feet of certain clinics.
   Among those arrested was Randall Terry, the zealous 29-year-old
leader of Operation Rescue. Terry and many of his followers refused
to talk to reporters.
   Led by feminist attorney Gloria Allred shouting in a bullhorn,
advocates of a woman's right to an abortion applauded and gleefully
chanted ``Read him his rights, take him away,'' every time a
protester was arrested.
   Those arrested were booked for investigation of failing to
disperse, a misdemeanor. Under Terry's order, they fell limp during
arrests, forcing four police officers to drag each one off to a bus
that took them to City Hall.
   Los Angeles officials, who had expected protests by as many 2,500
people, followed developments during the day from a City Hall
command center. But Los Angeles clinics were spared.
   Police in suburban Inglewood had set up a temporary jail site at
the Hollywood Park race track, but it was unneeded.
   Operation Rescue began its blockades outside women's clinics in
1987 and since then, more than 21,000 of its anti-abortion
protesters have been arrested nationwide.
   In the most recent figures available, California recorded 304,130
abortions in 1985 with some 100,360 performed at about 75 clinics in
the Los Angeles area.
   Some 1.5 million abortions have been performed annually in the
United States since the U.S. Supreme Court decision of 1973 that
made abortion legal for women in all states.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
