<HEAD>Spokesman: Bakker-Nautilus Studio Deal Off</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LAKE HELEN, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An attorney for Jim Bakker says the
evangelist and former PTL owner won't be buying the former Nautilus
property as a broadcasting headquarters.
   Reports earlier this week that Bakker wouldn't be buying the
Nautilus sports medicine facility led opponents of the possible sale
to call off a meeting to protest Bakker's presence in the small
community.
   The 158,000-square-foot Nautilus facility reportedly carried a
price tag of $5.5 million.
   The two sides failed to reach agreement on the terms, said
Bakker's attorney George Davis. Negotiations with the current
Nautilus owner, Travis Ward, broke down after five minutes, he said.
   Davis said Ward wanted $2 million up front and a definite
commitment, conditions Bakker and his business backers from
Charlotte, N.C., said they couldn't provide.
   Nautilus founder Arthur Jones sold his Nautilus exercise
equipment company to Ward in 1986. Ward then moved the company to
Dallas after the purchase.
   Officials at Studio Six Productions in Orlando, part of the WCPX
television station, said Wednesday they had put in a bid to serve as
a temporary broadcast facility for Bakker's ministry, a WCPX news
report said.
   Bakker's lawyers said no decision has been made either on a site
or on any broadcast arrangement. They also refused to comment on
that report of the Studio Six Productions offer.
   Bakker, who has pleaded not guilty to charges that he and another
PTL leader took $4 million from the PTL ministry, has been searching
for a new site for his TV pulpit.
</TEXT>
