<FIRST>r i AM-Britain-Somalia     03-24 0576</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Britain-Somalia,0593</SECOND>
<HEAD>Anti-Government Rebels in Somalia Claim They Hold Most of North</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rebels fighting Somalia's governmment claimed
Friday they hold almost a third of the strategically important
country on the Horn of Africa and are closing on two major northern
cities.
   Abdirahman Ahmed Ali, the rebel Somali National Movement's
executive committee member responsible for foreign relations, also
claimed Libya has provided nerve gas to the Somali government and
trained soldiers to use it. Ali said the gas was now in the port of
Berbera.
   The reports could not be independently confirmed.
   ``For some time we have been controlling 85 percent of the
northern region, which is about one-third of Somalia, and in the
past four weeks we have been closing on the main cities in the
north,'' Ali said in London, where he is based.
   Rebels were fighting government troops on the outskirts of
Hargeisa and Burao in northwest Somalia and expect to take control
of both cities ``very soon,'' he said.
   Last week, he said, rebels captured the town of Erigazo, near the
Red Sea, and the town of Odweine, between Hargeisa and Burao.
   ``We have also cleared a large costal area between Hargeisa and
the Red Sea,'' Ali said.
   The movement is fighting to oust army Gen. Mohamed Siad Barre,
who has ruled Somalia since a 1969 coup, and reestablish democracy.
The East African country of 5.3 million was once allied with the
Soviet Union, but switched allegiance to the West in 1977.
   Ali quoted Arab newspapers in Abu Dhabi as saying Barre had
called in Arab ambassadors in Mogadishu this week and appealed for
militry support. He said Libya was the only Arab country that had
provided the Somali government with some arms, tanks, ammunition and
nerve gas.
   ``We know the nerve gas is now in Berbera,'' the main port on the
Gulf of Aden, he said. ``It arrived there four weeks ago,
transported from Mogadishu, and 18 Somalis who have been trained in
Libya for use of nerve gas have now come back to Berbera. We know
because we have our own people there.''
   Ali said that on Wednesday, government soldiers in Kismaayo,
about 300 miles south of Mogadishu, broke into an army and police
armory, took all the ammunition and rifles, and went into the bush,
apparently defecting. ``So another front is going to start there
soon,'' he said.
   The rebel successes, he said, were the result of demoralization
in the army and an economic crisis.
   Somalia has accused neighboring Ethiopia of arming the rebels in
violation of a 1987 pact between the two countries that ended their
11-year war and stipulated they would not arm each others'
insurgents.
   In September, Amnesty International said the Barre government had
executed up to 1,000 civilians while trying to end the insurgency in
the north. In response, the U.S. Congress froze $55 million in aid
to the impoverished nation.
   Ali said the rebels were ``very concerned'' that two U.S.
military cargo planes were transporting arms and personnel for the
government from Mogadishu to Berbera and that the Americans also
were helping the Somali army with communications equipment and
training.
   ``We don't want the United States to be caught in civil war ...
and we hope they keep out of this conflict,'' he said.
   The rebels have been fighting Barre for seven years.
   Northern Somalia is a former British protectorate that merged
with the south, a former Italian colony, in 1960.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
