<HEAD>LifeSavers Turns Nostalgic, Brings Back 1920's Flavors</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HOLLAND, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Planters LifeSavers Co. hopes customers
hungry for nostalgia will savor the return of some old-fashioned
flavors it hasn't sold in decades.
   The company's Holland plant recently began producing the
``Limited Edition Nostalgia Flavors'' _ ``Lic-O-Rice,''
``Choc-O-Late'' and ``Pepsin.'' Stores began carrying them a week
ago.
   The three flavors were developed in the 1920s. Lic-O-Rice and
Pepsin were discontinued in 1938 and Choc-O-Late was produced until
1968.
   ``Our society's general interest in nostalgia is booming these
days, and many Americans associate LifeSavers candy with warm
memories of their childhood and quieter, simpler lifestyles,'' said
Jeff Walters, associate product manager for the Winston-Salem,
N.C.-based company.
   When LifeSavers candies were introduced in 1912, Pep-O-Mint was
the only flavor available. Over the years, 45 flavors have been sold
at various times and 34 billion rolls have been purchased.
Currently, 17 flavors are on the market.
