<FIRST>u a PM-MissingBoat 2ndLd-Writethru a0512 03-24 0429</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Missing Boat, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0512,0433</SECOND>
<HEAD>Coast Guard Says Boat with 10 Aboard Not Found; Hoax Not Ruled Out</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: UPDATES throughout with officials saying call may have been
hoax but are still looking; other detail; CORRECTS in penultimate graf
number of boats called Blue Goose in computer records to 37 sted 20. No
pickup.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PORTSMOUTH, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Coast Guard said today it has found no
sign of a sport fishing boat that radioed a distress call off the
Virginia coast and indicated 10 people aboard were abandoning ship.
Officials said they feared the boat had sunk but they couldn't rule
out a hoax.
   ``The helicopter is having a tough time due to the fog,'' said
Petty Officer 1st Class Rick Woods. ``Visibility was almost zero
last night, and it's real low this morning.''
   Petty Officer 1st Class Rick Barrett said today that an
84-square-mile area was being searched by the Coast Guard cutters
Point Huron, Point Highland and Point Arena, two Navy ships and a
Coast Guard helicopter.
   He said winds were blowing at 15 mph and seas were running 4 to 6
feet.
   Coast Guard officials have been unable to find any registration
records for a 52-foot vessel called the Blue Goose and were
considering the possibility that the distress call was a hoax.
   ``We don't know that this is a hoax, but there have been hoaxes
before,'' Petty Officer 2nd Class Steve Blando said late this
morning.
   The boat radioed late Thursday that it was taking on water and
that the passengers had donned life jackets and were abandoning the
vessel, said Coast Guard Petty Officer 1st Class Vernon Covington.
He said officials told them to try to stay together but did not
receive acknowledgement of that transmission.
   The helicopter from Elizabeth City, N.C., arrived to help in the
search but returned to its base shortly afterward because of 60 mph
winds and zero visibility, officials said.
   Seas were running 6 to 8 feet and the water temperature was 42
degrees, raising concerns that anyone overboard might suffer
hypothermia, Covington said.
   He said a computer check found 37 boats on the East Coast with
the name Blue Goose but that none fit the description of the missing
vessel. He speculated that the boat may be one of the many pleasure
craft that travel to and from Florida this time of year.
   The Blue Goose was described as a Hatteras-type fishing vessel,
which has a large deck area to the rear, a high cabin and sleeping
accommodations for six to eight people.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
