<SECOND>PM-Space Shuttle, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0531,0268</SECOND>
<HEAD>Shuttle Arrives Back In Florida After Overnight In Texas</HEAD>
<HEAD>Precede SAN ANTONIO</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 5 grafs to UPDATE with shuttle arriving in Florida,
add background on next shuttle flights. Picks up penultimate graf, `Discovery
blasted...'.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A jumbo jet carrying the space
shuttle Discovery landed here today, concluding a cross-country
journey home after an overnight stop in Texas.
   The Boeing 747 transport took off from Kelly Air Force Base near
San Antonio shortly before 10 a.m. EST and arrived at the Kennedy
Space Center here three hours later, touching down on a runway just
three miles from the launch pad where Discovery started a space
journey more than a week ago.
   After removing the shuttle from the transport, NASA will begin
grooming it for a classifed Defense Department mission in August.
One of the craft's three main engines will have to be replaced
because of a small combustion chamber leak discovered during
post-flight inspection.
   Space shuttle Atlantis is scheduled to make the next shuttle
flight, with launch set for April 28. Its crew will dispatch the
Magellan payload to orbit the planet Venus.
   The transport with Discovery aboard left Edwards Air Force Base
in California on Thursday and flew to Kelly, where it was refueled
and spent the night before departing this morning.
   Discovery blasted off March 13 on a five-day mission that
deployed the last of three Tracking and Data Relay Satellites to
complete the National Aeronautics and Space Administraion's shuttle
communications system.
   The orbiter landed at dawn Saturday in the California desert.
</TEXT>
