<FIRST>r i AM-BRF--Italy-Arms     03-24 0174</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Italy-Arms,0180</SECOND>
<HEAD>Five Convicted of Arms Smuggling</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAVONA, Italy (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two Belgians, two Danes and an Italian were
convicted Friday of smuggling into Italy an estimated $8.5 million
in weapons destined for Latin American guerrillas.
   The court acquitted an officer and three crewmen on the Danish
freighter that carried the Czechoslovak-made arms from the West
German port of Hamburg to Savona on the Italian Riviera.
   Belgians Patrice Raulier and Andre Fredrics, considered the
ringleaders of the group sending arms to rebels in Bolivia and
Colombia, received sentences of 12 years and four and a third years
respectively.
   Marc Luick, a Danish shipping agent who rented the freighter
Jenstar, received three years in jail, and the Danish captain of the
ship, Joseph Andersen, received four years.
   All were fined between $1,500 and $3,000.
   The shortest jail term of two years and eight months went to
Italian Vito Manfredini, who cooperated with police following his
arrest.
   The shipload of pistols, guns and ammunition was seized when the
Jenstar docked in Savona on Feb. 8.
</TEXT>
