<FIRST>r i AM-Turkey     03-24 0452</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Turkey,0465</SECOND>
<HEAD>Turkish Premier Says He May Quit</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EMEL ANIL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ANKARA, Turkey (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Premier Turgut Ozal said he may quit if
opposition parties make strong gains in Sunday's nationwide local
elections.
   ``If many want to see Suleyman Bey back in power, or Erdal Bey in
power, we will say, `OK, come take over,''' Ozal said Friday,
referring to former Premier Suleyman Demirel and opposition leader
Erdal Inonu.
   ``I am not glued to the (premier's) chair, let whoever wants come
run the country,'' he said at a news conference.
   Turks on Sunday will elect mayors, provincial assembly members,
city councilors, neighborhood representatives and village headmen.
   Voting does not directly affect the national government, and
Ozal's mandate extends to 1992. But opposition parties say Ozal
should call early elections if the governing Motherland Party
receives less than one-third of votes nationwide.
   ``This is not a general election and I would like to continue
until 1992,'' Ozal said. ``But if matters come to a point where we
cannot rule comfortably, I will say, `do whatever you like.'''
   Ozal's record is a major election issue. During his five years in
power, the nation of 52 million people has enjoyed economic growth
and built power plants, roads and an improved communications
network. Trade has been liberalized and it has applied for
membership in the European Economic Community.
   But inflation, which reached 75 percent last year, has hurt many
wage earners and prompted a drop in support for Ozal.
   Public opinion polls indicate the main opposition Social Democrat
Populist Party will win mayoral posts in the capital, Ankara, and
Turkey's third largest city, Izmir. The Motherland Party is expected
to maintain control in Istanbul, the second city where popular Mayor
Bedrettin Dalan is seeking a second five-year term.
   Ozal said he doubted the accuracy of the polls and doubted his
party would lose. He declined to say exactly what vote result would
make him consider quitting.
   Respected columnist Guneri Civaoglu of the daily Sabah said Ozal
may call general elections in six months if his party suffers a
crushing defeat Sunday.
   The popularity of the center-right Motherland Party has declined
steadily since it won 1983 general elections that restored civilian
rule. The party at that time garnered 45 percent of the vote.
   In general elections in November 1987, the party won 36 percent
of the vote but 65 percent of seats in the 450-member legislature,
through electoral laws that favor the largest party.
   Ozal threatened to quit before a national referendum in November
on advancing the date of local polls. Although he lost the
referendum, he stayed on, saying the 35 percent of votes he won
indicated he still had wide support.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890324-0103 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-24-89 1412EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Israel-Daredevils     03-24 0432</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Israel-Daredevils,0446</SECOND>
<HEAD>Safety Program Ordered After Youth Dies in Highway Game</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The education minister ordered a traffic safety
program in schools Friday after an 11-year-old boy died playing a
daredevil ``game'' in highway traffic, Israel radio reported.
   Baruch Oren died last week after jumping in front of a speeding
car along the busy Tel Aviv-Haifa highway and trying to force it to
stop at the last moment, the radio said.
   The ``game'' is a new fad among elementary and high school
students, who also have been known to throw balls and school bags on
roads, and try to snatch them from in front of speeding cars. High
school students feel such reckless deeds toughen them before army
service, the radio said.
   ``It's a thrill,'' said one of Oren's classmates who was
interviewed on the radio. ``It makes kids feel strong and the girls
think they're heroes.''
   On Friday, Education Minister Yitzhak Navon met school principals
across the country after an investigation revealed Oren died while
playing the game.
   He ordered each school to open a road safety seminar Monday for
parents and children to stress dangers of the game.
   ``I don't know of a school in the country where the game is not
played,'' said Yaffa Saguy, principal of Ein Hayam school where Oren
was a student in northern Haifa city.
   ``Children stand by the road and when they see a car or bus
coming they throw a package and rush into the road,'' Ms. Saguy told
the radio.
   After Oren's death, she had the school psychiatrist hold a
seminar for students on the effects of the game.
   Shai Gadish, head of the Education Ministry's Road Safety Unit,
said children play the game to show their bravery and try to share
the dangers faced by older brothers or friends serving in the army.
   All Israelis are drafted into the army at age 18. Men serve for
three years, women for two.
   ``We are not talking about kids who don't know the dangers,''
Gadish said. ``They know the dangers and they do it.''
   Oren's classmates said it was the fourth time he had played the
game.
   One of his friends told the radio that Oren said ``Look, I can
stop cars,'' and walked into the middle of the road.
   ``He stood there and ... I heard a real loud sound from the
wheels and I saw Baruch fly into the air,'' said the friend, who was
not identified. He said he didn't want to play the game, but ``some
of the kids laughed at me so I did it.''
</TEXT>
