<FIRST>r i AM-Britain-SAfrica 1stLd-Writethru a0575 03-24 0502</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Britain-SAfrica, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0575,0513</SECOND>
<HEAD>Thatcher Says She'll Visit South Africa After Mandela is Freed</HEAD>
<HEAD>Embargoed For Release 8 p.m. EST _ Time Set By Source</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: ADDS 2 grafs with aide saying stance not new, background on
sanctions.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher says she believes
there are ``chances of things improving enormously'' in South Africa
if the government releases jailed nationalist leader Nelson Mandela.
   Until that happens, there is little hope for fruitful
negotiations on the nation's future, Mrs. Thatcher said in an
interview with the BBC's Africa service to be broadcast Saturday.
   She is visiting Africa next week, but South Africa is not on the
itinerary that includes Morocco, Nigeria, Malawi, and Zimbabwe.
   ``I have made it quite clear that I could not go until something
quite positive happens and Mr. Mandela is released,'' Mrs. Thatcher
said.
   ``I think that there are chances of things improving enormously
in South Africa once Mr. Mandela is released. It opens the way for
negotiations to start. But I could not go just at the moment until
there are more signs of that happening.''
   Asked what was the next likely stage of developments in South
Africa, she replied: ``I have indicated that if Mr. Mandela is
released I think that negotiations would become possible with some
of the other many leaders of black South Africans. Obviously they
are not a homogenous people any more than we are in Europe.''
   She doubted it would be possible for tribal leaders to negotiate
until Mandela was released.
   At the same time, she said she could not consider meeting with
the African National Congress that Mandela leads until the guerrilla
organization renounced violence.
   ``I think the government of South Africa would like a
renunciation of violence. We did not quite get that, and I do not
talk to those who in fact pursue their ends by violent means.''
   She continued: ``Look, we are trying to get a way through by
saying that Mr. Mandela should be released and should be free. This
is part of the bargain, he should be free in fact to put his own
view but not ... free to exercise violence.
   ``One tries to get a law-abiding country. Violence is anarchy.
The rule of the gun and rule by force is not something I've had any
sympathy with at all.''
   Asked if she believed in one man, one vote in South Africa, Mrs.
Thatcher said: ``I think you will have to have one person, one vote.
That does not necessarily mean a unitary state.
   ``They will have to work it out.''
   Mrs. Thatcher's comments do not represent a new approach. ``She's
said this for a long time now,'' an aide said.
   Mrs. Thatcher argues a moderate stance toward South Africa can
achieve more than advocating sanctions, which she argues would hurt
the country's black majority more than the white-run government, and
would devastate economies of nearby black-ruled states that depend
on South Africa's transport network to import and export goods.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890324-0105 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-24-89 1421EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-Kidnap-Lecture     03-24 0424</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Kidnap-Lecture,0436</SECOND>
<HEAD>Kidnap Suspect Once Lectured At Purdue</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WEST LAFAYETTE, Ind. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Five weeks before his arrest on
charges of kidnapping a woman and demanding nearly $2 million
ransom, a businessman told a university business class his secrets
of success, but said he needed $500,000.
   Arthur J. Curry, 41, of West Lafayette, is accused of kidnapping
Gayle T. Cook on March 15 and demanding $1.7 million in gold bullion
and cash from her multimillionaire husband. He was arrested and Mrs.
Cook was freed the next day. He is charged with five felonies and is
jailed in Bloomington in lieu of $1 million bond.
   On Feb. 10, as a guest lecturer at Purdue University, he
expounded on his success on Wall Street and his willingness to risk
everything to succeed. He admonished students to never trust anyone
they were dealing with.
   Curry portrayed himself as a shrewd, methodical businessman who
scouted bankrupt properties for gold-mine opportunities.
   ``The first key to risk is that you have to be willing to lose
everything that you are doing,'' he said. ``You have to be willing
to say, `I've lost it all. It's all gone.' If you can't take that
risk, don't go in the business.
   He also said: ``In the next three weeks, I'm going to have to
scramble around and find a half-million dollars.''
   At the time of the lecture, a lien had been placed on the Coyote
Grill, a Lafayette restaurant Curry was developing. Another project,
a hotel in Michigan, was in bankruptcy, and Curry had just been
removed as a general partner in another Michigan hotel investment.
   He peppered his presentation with humorous remarks to make his
points about finding a risk and forming a business team to follow up.
   ``Who should be on your team? You need a lawyer. This is
absolutely fundamental,'' said Curry. ``My attitude toward a lawyer
is that I would never have a lawyer that I would invite to my home.''
   Mrs. Cook was abducted from in front of her home. A man
telephoned her husband and demanded $1.2 million in cash and
$500,000 in gold for her release.
   About 24 hours later, FBI agents and state police surrounded a
van Curry was driving behind a Bloomington shopping center,
officials said. Inside, they found Mrs. Cook, bound and gagged.
   Curry was charged with kidnapping, criminal confinement, battery,
criminal recklessness and auto theft.
   Mrs. Cook and her husband, William A. Cook, own and operate a
$250 million medical instruments firm they started 25 years ago with
a $1,500 investment.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
