<FIRST>d a AM-Shoreham     03-24 0226</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Shoreham,0234</SECOND>
<HEAD>NRC Ready to License Shoreham Nuclear Plant</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RIVERHEAD, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Nuclear Regulatory Commission said
Friday it was ready to license the operation of the $5.4 billion
Shoreham nuclear power plant, although the state already has agreed
to dismantle it.
   William Russell, regional administrator for the commission, said
a two-week plant inspection had turned up six items that needed to
be corrected before the license could be issued.
   Russell said at a news conference that 17 NRC officials who
inspected Shoreham gave the plant high marks in most areas, and said
it could be ready to operate as early as next month. The inspection
was a final step before a decision on whether to grant an operating
license to the Long Island Lighting Co.
   Gov. Mario M. Cuomo and William Catacosinos, the chairman of the
utility, signed an agreement last month under which the state would
buy the plant for $1 and dismantle it, and the utility would be
granted rate increases to make up some of its losses.
   But the utility has said it would continue to take steps to
obtain a full operating license until its full board approves the
agreement.
   Cuomo and other officials have argued that Shoreham should not be
allowed to open because the area around the plant could not be
safely evacuated during a nuclear emergency.
</TEXT>
