<FIRST>r w AM-Bush     03-24 0594</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush,560</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Offers Strong Support for Space Program</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush voiced strong support for
further U.S. space exploration on Friday as he praised the Discovery
astronauts for ``exploring the new horizons of this nation's
technological future.''
   ``Gentlemen, your mission is accomplished. Your nation says, well
done, thank you,'' he told the five astronauts in a White House
ceremony.
   ``You showed exactly where we are going and why,'' Bush said.
   Pictures taken by the astronauts with the sophisticated IMAX
camera will add to the ``knowledge base'' of the global environment,
Bush said. ``That, in turn, will lead to reducing the threat to our
Earth's environment,'' he said.
   Bush greeted the five astronauts, who were clad in blue flight
suits, in a ceremony in the Old Executive Office Building. ``This
voyage of the shuttle Discovery is over, but its spirit lives,
linking the majesty of outer space with the greatness of Ameria.''
   ``And we're going to forge even stronger links as we reaffirm our
commitment to the shuttle program, as our science missions open up
new horizons of knowledge and as Space Station Freedom symbolizes
the promise of man,'' the president said.
   In turn, mission commander Michael Coats presented Bush with an
American flag carried aboard the shuttle on ``the first flight of
this administration,'' and said a gold shuttle charm also carried
into space had been given to first lady Barbara Bush.
   ``We deeply appreciate your words of support for our country's
space program,'' Coats said. ``We represent thousands of people that
work very hard to get the shuttle of the ground each time, and the
encouragement you've shown is deeply appreciated.''
   Coats and four crewmates returned to Earth last Saturday after
spending five days in orbit aboard space shuttle Discovery.
   The mission, the third since flights resumed following the
Challenger disaster, was the first of Bush's administration. The
president talked to the astronauts while they were in space and
invited them to the White House.
   While in orbit, Coats and his crew used a powerful 70mm camera
called IMAX to photograph areas of the Earth damaged by manmade
pollution or by violent natural events such as volcanoes. Film from
the camera is to be edited into a movie to be shown by the
Smithsonian Institution's Air and Space Museum.
   The Discovery astronauts also launched a communications satellite
and conducted a series of experiments during the mission.
   The Bushes left the White House in early afternoon to spend the
weekend at the presidential retreat at Camp David, Md.
   Travelling by motorcade because rain forced the cancellation of a
planned helicopter trip, the president stopped on the way to visit
former Salvadoran President Jose Napoleon Duarte, who is at Walter
Reed Army Medical Center in Washington for tests and treatment.
Duarte is dying of liver cancer.
   The first family was to be joined by three Bush chlidren and six
grandchildren over the weekend, as well as the family dog, Millie,
and her six week-old pups.
   Country singer Lee Greenwood, who frequently appeared at Bush
campaign events last year, and his family were to join the Bushes on
Saturday.
   The first family was to attend private Easter services at Camp
David, have their traditional Easter turkey dinner, then return to
Washington for the chistening of Ashley Walker Bush, who was born
Feb. 7.
   The child of Neil and Sharon Bush is the president's 11th
grandchild.
   On Monday, the Bushes, their children and grandchilden will
participate in the annual Easter egg roll on the White House lawn.
</TEXT>
