<HEAD>Corsica Returns To Normal As Unions Agree To Talks</HEAD>
<DATELINE>AJACCIO, Corsica (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Striking public employees Friday lifted
blockades of ports and airports that have isolated this French
Mediterranean island for more than a week, and they accepted a
government proposal for talks.
   Airlines operated normally from the two main airports at Ajaccio
and Bastia, carrying away tourists trapped in Corsica since the air
and sea shutdown started 10 days ago.
   Two boats unloaded 1,700 tons of meat and chicken, allowing
stores to start replenishing dwindling supplies.
   The strike by Corsica's public sector began six weeks ago, with
workers demanding a special bonus because of the unusually high
prices in Corsica.
   The cost of living in Ajaccio and Bastia, the two main Corsican
cities, is estimated at 4.2 percent above the French national
average.
   Unions Friday agreed to send representatives to Paris this
weekend for talks with the ministries of Public Services and Social
Affairs, union officials said.
   Tension had been mounting the past week with sporadic clashes
between demonstrators and police.
