<FIRST>r a AM-Cartoon     03-24 0297</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Cartoon,0305</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dick Tracy Originals Missing From Museum</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RYE BROOK, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   No crook gets the better of Dick Tracy,
but someone has stolen valuable original panels of the famous
syndicated cartoon strip from the Museum of Cartoon Art.
   A number of Tracy panels were willed to the museum by the creator
of the jut-jawed champion of law and order, Chester Gould, who died
in 1985.
   Museum director Barbara Hammond said Friday that because of press
reports and rumors within the cartoon art community, she was
confirming that Gould strips are missing, but she declined to say
how many or what they depicted. Nor would she say how many panels
Gould had left the museum or how they had been displayed.
   ``To say more would jeopardize the investigation and the museum's
position in recovering any art work,'' Mrs. Hammond said.
   The Westchester County district attorney's office confirmed the
museum filed a complaint Tuesday but declined to give details.
   ``Those things go for a minimum of $1,200 to $1,500 apiece,''
said Dick Locher, who has been drawing the strip for Tribune Media
Services in Chicago for the past five years.
   His collaborator, Max Allen Collins of Muscatine, Iowa, who has
been writing the strip's story line since 1977, said that what Gould
left the museum ``were highly prized strips that obviously had been
set aside by the creator.''
   Collins was quoted in the Greenwich (Conn.) Time as saying he
believed some of the missing panels depicted important developments
in the history of the strip.
   Hallmarks of the strip, which originated in 1931, have been
Tracy's two-way wrist radio and its bizarrely named and drawn
characters, like the villains Pruneface, Flattop and Mumbles;
Tracy's girl friend, Tess Trueheart; and such friendlies as B.O.
Plenty and Gravel Gertie.
</TEXT>
