<FILEID>AP-NR-03-24-89 1521EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a PM-TankerSpill 3rdLd-Writethru a0603 03-24 0669</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Tanker Spill, 3rd Ld - Writethru, a0603,0687</SECOND>
<HEAD>Vessel Runs Aground Off Alaska, Spills 200,000 Barrels of Oil</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Rewrites throughout to UPDATE with official saying oil slick
is not approaching land; investigators board tanker to investigate accident;
attempt to get around icebergs cited as possible cause; detail on size
of ship, other detail. No pickup.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VALDEZ, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An oil tanker ran aground today about 25
miles outside this port, spilling an estimated 200,000 barrels of
crude oil into Prince William Sound, the Coast Guard said.
   Cmdr. Stephen McCall, commander of the port at the southern end
of the Alaska oil pipeline, said the Exxon Valdez was heading
outbound from the Alyeska marine terminal with 1.26 million barrels
of oil aboard when it ran hard aground at Bligh Reef.
   Petty Officer John Gonzales estimated that by midmorning, an oil
slick streched southward five miles into the sound from the site of
the tanker, toward an open body of water.
   ``At present, we don't see it approaching any land,'' he said.
   There were no reports of injuries, officials said. The crew
remained aboard the tanker.
   ``The ship is hard aground. It's not moving at this time,''
McCall said.
   ``There definitely are holes in the hull,'' he said. Three tanks
on the right side of the tanker have holes, he said, and ``we think
the centerline tanks also have holes.''
   Gonzales said estimates put the leak at 200,000 barrels, or 8.4
million gallons, and said the tanker continued to leak at about
20,000 gallons an hour.
   Employees of the Alyeska Pipeline Service Co., which runs the
800-mile trans-Alaska pipeline for a consortium of oil companies,
were on their way to try to contain the oil with booms, he said.
   Two Coast Guard investigators went aboard the tanker to begin
looking into the cause.
   Officials think the vessel may have gone aground as the captain
tried to maneuver around icebergs from the Columbia glacier,
Gonzales said. There is a hole or gash in the vessel below the water
line, he said, and divers planned to go down and assess the damage
in more detail.
   He said the new estimate of leakage came from looking at
videotapes taken of the scene by pilots flying over. Earlier, the
size of the spill was put at 150,000 barrels.
   The Coast Guard had no immediate detail on of damage to the
shoreline or marine environment.
   The 987-foot tanker, which has a capacity of 1.3 million barrel
in about 15 large tanks, left Valdez at 10 p.m. AST on Thursday and
ran ground about 12:30 a.m. today (4:30 a.m. EST), officials said.
The tanker is owned by Exxon Shipping Co., based in Houston.
   Valdez, the nation's northernmost ice-free port, is a town of
3,100 about 125 miles east of Anchorage. It looks out onto the
island-dotted Prince William Sound, which is near a number of
recreation areas. Fishing, as well as tourism, is an important
industry, but the main seasons for various types of fishing are
still weeks away.
   The Coast Guard was responding to two concerns _ pollution and
the safety of the ship, McCall said.
   ``It appears that the rate of release of the oil has been greatly
reduced. It probably lost the largest portion of that oil when it
ran aground. But it's still leaking.
   ``A concern we have, too, is the structural integrity of the
ship,'' McCall said. ``We're concerned about what further damage
would be done if attempts were made to remove it (the vessel) early.
   ``We've got the pollution to go after and the off-loading.''
   Another tanker, the Exxon Baton Rouge, is not far from the
stricken tanker and officials hoped oil could be transferred from
the Valdez to the Baton Rouge, McCall said.
   The worst oil spill in terms of financial loss claims was the 66
million-gallon spill from the tanker Amoco Cadiz off the coast of
Brittany in France in March 1978, according to the Guinness Book of
World Records. Losses were put at $1.7 billion.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890324-0124 </DOCNO>
