<FIRST>r w AM-Lucas 1stLd-Writethru a0630 03-24 0536</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lucas, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0630,490</SECOND>
<HEAD>Choice to Head Civil Rights Division Once Flunked Bar Exam</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs 3rd graf pvs, Burstion-Wade said, to clarify that spokewoman
didn't have records pertaining to whether Lucas was forced to leave; subs
5th graf pvs, Civil rights, to restore dropped material.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAROLYN SKORNECK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Attorney General Dick Thornburgh's choice to
head the civil rights division resigned from that division in the
early 1960s shortly after he flunked the District of Columbia bar
exam, a Justice Department spokeswoman said Friday.
   However, spokeswoman Deborah Burstion-Wade said she could not
confirm that William Lucas had been forced to resign because of the
failed bar exam, as Hearst News Service reported.
   Burstion-Wade said she did not have records from the personnel
office pertaining to whether Lucas was forced to leave the division
and had been unable to reach Lucas to ask him about it.
   He passed the Michigan bar exam in 1971, she said, adding that he
would not have to pass the District of Columbia bar if he became
assistant attorney general in charge of the civil rights division.
   Civil rights groups have expressed concern that Lucas, a black
Democrat-turned-Republican who ran unsuccessfully for governor of
Michigan in 1986, might be the wrong person to head the civil rights
division.
   Lucas was offered a job in the Justice Department's criminal
division in April 1962, and the former New York City police officer
took the position after he completed law school at Fordham
University. He was hired as an attorney contingent on his passing
the District of Columbia bar exam within nine months, Burstion-Wade
said.
   In August 1963, he became a legal assistant in the department's
civil rights division and, in November 1963, was given a one-month
extension to await the results of the bar exam, she said, adding
that such extensions are standard procedure.
   He did not pass the exam and, in December 1963, became an
investigator for the U.S. Commission on Civil Rights, she said.
   Lucas remained with the Commission on Civil Rights for six weeks,
leaving in January 1964 to join the FBI, Burstion-Wade said. He was
assigned first to the Cincinnati field office and, in 1965 to the
Detroit office, where he remained until June 1968, when he resigned.
   Although Thornburgh announced a month ago that Lucas was his
choice to head the division, the White House still has not nominated
him formally.
   Burstion-Wade said part of the reason for the delay was that
Lucas ``was just interviewed last week by the FBI.'' People who had
been interviewed by the FBI several weeks earlier also have not yet
been formally nominated by the White House, she said.
   Lucas, who is in private legal practice in Detroit, has said on
resumes that he served as an ``assistant U.S. attorney'' or as ``an
investigator and attorney in the U.S. Justice Department,'' despite
the fact that he did not actually serve as an attorney since he had
not passed the bar.
   Lucas said recently that he ``was classified as an attorney,''
and believed that he ``was an attorney with the Justice
Department.'' But he also has said that discrepancies on his resumes
were due to ``carelessness.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890324-0125 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-24-89 1551EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-SriLanka     03-24 0509</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sri Lanka,0526</SECOND>
<HEAD>Indian Army Accused of Killing Civilians in Sri Lanka</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEXTER CRUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Indian peacekeeping forces have killed
more than 300 Tamil civilians in a northern district, the most
powerful and biggest Tamil rebel group said Friday. India dismissed
the charge as propaganda.
   In New Delhi, the leader of the Tamils' semiautonomous government
warned there will be a blood bath unless authorities in Colombo give
his officials more power.
   An Indian High Commission official in Sri Lanka said the rebel
charges were their ``usual propaganda.'' He said 76 militants and 26
soldiers have been killed in operations this month in northern
Mullaitivu district.
   Sri Lankan officials said the dead include nine soldiers and six
militants who were killed in hand-to-hand fighting Thursday and two
soldiers killed when rebels blew up their jeep.
   ``The Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam today accused the Indian
army of committing the crime of genocide against the Tamil people in
its desperate drive to crush the armed resistance of the Tamil Tiger
guerrillas in the northeastern region of Sri Lanka,'' a rebel
statement said.
   It said Indian troops have killed more than 300 civilians in
Mullaitivu since March 2, when the soldiers started searching the
area for rebels.
   It was not possible to investigate the rebel charges
independently.
   Mullaitivu is 175 miles northeast of Colombo, and the Tamil
Tigers are believed to be based in the district's marshy jungles.
   At least 40,000 Indian soldiers are in Sri Lanka to put down the
Tamil insurrection. The troops initially were deployed to supervise
a rebel arms surrender agreed in an Indian-sponsored peace accord
July 1987.
   The rebels reneged two months later. Nevertheless, the government
set up a Northeastern Provincial government to give Tamils limited
autonomy.
   In New Delhi, the new government's chief minister Vardarajan
Perumal appealed to the Indian government to intercede to save the
accord, which he said is jeopardized by the Colombo government's
``intransigent and adamant attitude.''
   Perumal said his government has no control over education,
administrative services, law and order and allotment and
distribution of land.
   ``If there is no reasonable solution, everything will collapse,''
Perumal told a news conference.
   ``How far (the Sri Lankan government) will devolve power will
determine the unity and integrity of Sri Lanka,'' he said. ``We will
ask, then we will request and then we will appeal. If there is no
response, we will take.''
   Perumal said Indian leaders had made no commitments.
   ``The Indian government says it will do the maximum but they are
requesting us to be patient,'' he said. ``We feel that if the
provincial council fails there will be no solution except a blood
bath.''
   Tamils form 18 percent of Sri Lanka's 16 million people and say
the majority Sinhalese discriminate against them in and jobs and
education.
   At least 8,500 people, including 800 Indian soldiers, have been
killed since 1983, when Tamil militants started a campaign for a
separate state. India got involved because of the sympathies of its
own 60 million Tamils.
</TEXT>
