<FIRST>r a AM-ArtThefts     03-24 0338</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Art Thefts,0350</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pair Accused of Art Theft Spree</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN M. DOYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government has charged two men with stealing
a 14th-century Chinese vase and other works of art from six museums
in daylight heists, federal officials said Friday.
   The art works and antiques, ranging from the $2 million vase to
16 antique pocket watches, have a total value of $3.5 million,
according to the FBI.
   The works were taken from Jan. 12 to Feb. 25 from museums in
Boston, Baltimore, Detroit, Syracuse and Albany, N.Y., and Columbus,
Ohio.
   George A. Athanasatos, 34, and Ronald Corteselli, 28, both of New
York, pleaded innocent to theft charges and were ordered held
without bail.
   A total of 25 objects were stolen, officials said.
   The two men ``have been linked with some but not all of these
items,'' U.S. Attorney Benito Romano told a news conference where
most of the recovered objects were displayed.
   James Fox, head of the FBI's New York office, said most of the
objects were taken during normal working hours when the museums were
open to the public.
   They were removed from plexiglass-covered display cases which did
not have burglar alarms, he said.
   The five-count federal indictment charged the pair with
transporting across state lines and selling antique watches worth
$150,000, stolen from the Baltimore Museum of Art.
   Athanasatos also was charged with interstate transportation of a
$50,000 silver Tiffany pitcher stolen from the Detroit Institute of
Art on Jan. 12.
   The pitcher was recovered by the FBI on March 6 after it was sold
to an antiques dealer for $15,000.
   Both men were ordered detained without bail because of other
outstanding warrants, said defense lawyer Edward Rappaport.
   They were indicted last week by a federal grand jury in Boston on
stolen goods trafficking involving the 14th century, Yuan Dynasty
vase, worth $2 million, that was stolen from the Boston Museum of
Fine Arts.
   The blue and gray vase was among the recovered objects displayed
by the FBI.
</TEXT>
