<FIRST>r i AM-Bangladesh     03-24 0187</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bangladesh,0195</SECOND>
<HEAD>Protests Mark Seventh Anniversary of Ershad's Government</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DHAKA, Bangladesh (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 5,000 opposition activists
marched through Dhaka on Friday to protest the rule of President
Hussain Muhammad Ershad, who seized power in a bloodless coup seven
years ago.
   ``Gen. Ershad has killed democracy and his government is ruining
the country's economy,'' said Khaleda Zia, head of the Bangladesh
Nationalist Party, the major opposition alliance, in an address to
the rally.
   Two other protest rallies were held elsewhere in the capital as
police in riot gear watched. Ershad is away on a three-day official
tour of France.
   Mrs. Zia said opposition groups will have to unite to achieve
``democracy and impartial elections.''
   Ershad, 59, took power in a bloodless coup on March 24, 1982, and
imposed martial law after sacking the civilian government of
President Abdus Sattar.
   Sattar was head of the Bangladesh Nationalist Party, founded by
Mrs. Zia's husband, Ziaur Rahman.
   Ershad lifted martial law in November 1986 when he won the
presidential election. Opposition parties boycotted 1988 elections,
which were won by Ershad's Jatiya Party and were widely denounced as
fraudulent.
