<FIRST>r i AM-France-Collision     03-24 0275</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-France-Collision,0283</SECOND>
<HEAD>One Killed in Seine River Collision</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A glass-covered tour boat carrying 500 people on the
Seine River collided with a barge near Notre Dame Cathedral, killing
one person, officials said Friday.
   Police said the captains of the vessels blamed each other for the
crash Thursday night between the Notre Dame and Arcole bridges in
one of the most picturesque spots of central Paris.
   Firefighters treated 10 people for shock and took 10 others
suffering from sprains and bruises to hospitals, according to
police. Eleven Americans, two Spaniards and four Portuguese were
among those treated, police said. All those who were taken to
hospitals were released.
   Manuel Bessa, 28, a Portuguese student on the tour boat, was
killed when he was struck in the head by an open window that swung
shut in the impact of the collision, police said.
   Frogmen searched the river to make sure no one had been knocked
overboard.
   The accident occurred when the tour boat, known as the Bateau
Mouche, was hit head on by the 2,500-ton barge, part of a convoy of
five vessels.
   Sources close to the investigation quoted the tour boat captain
as saying the barge was poorly lighted. The barge captain said the
Bateau Mouche failed to respect the rules of navigation on the
Seine, ignoring a signal.
   The tourist boat is one of nine that ply the Seine daily,
lighting up historic buildings of old Paris with huge spotlights.
   The owner of Bateau Mouche boats said 1.75 million people went on
Seine cruises in 1988. Company officials said they could not recall
any comparable accident in the company's 40-year history.
</TEXT>
