<FIRST>r w AM-GingrichInvestor 500   03-24 0503</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Gingrich Investor, 500</SECOND>
<HEAD>Georgia Democratic Official Involved In Gingrich Book Promotion Deal</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID PACE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Georgia Democratic Party official said
Friday he invested $5,000 to help promote Rep. Newt Gingrich's book
in 1984 because he thought the newly elected House GOP whip had a
message that ``ought to get out.''
   But Joel Cowan, a Peachtree City, Ga., real estate developer who
serves as treasurer of the state Democratic Party and honorary
chief of staff to Democratic Gov. Joe Frank Harris, said he has
never supported Gingrich politically and has never contributed to
his congressional campaigns.
   In fact, Cowan said in a telephone interview, he contributed
$500 last year to Gingrich's Democratic opponent, David Worley.
   Cowan's investment in a partnership set up to promote Gingrich's
book, ``Window of Opportunity,'' was disclosed Friday by the Wall
Street Journal in a article that also said Cowan's company had
received a $204,480 grant in 1988 from the Department of Housing
and Urban Development.
   Cowan denied having received such a grant. And HUD officials,
after searching department records Friday, said they could find no
evidence of a grant award last year to Cowan's company, Cowan and
Associates.
   But Beth Almond in the economics and analysis branch of HUD's
Atlanta regional office said Cowan and Associates was given
preliminary approval by HUD in 1978 for a 60-unit low income
housing project for the elderly in Peachtree City.
   The letter of approval said HUD would pay rent subsidies to the
tenants once the project was completed and the Farmers Home
Administration would guarantee the financing for the units.
   Ms. Almond said a 1980 letter involving the same project listed
the total annual rent subsidy pledged by HUD for the 60 units at
$204,480. But she said that letter was addressed to someone other
than Cowan and Associates and would ``appear to indicate'' Cowan
had dropped out of the project.
   Cowan was one of 21 investors who put up $5,000 each to promote
Gingrich's book in exchange for a promise of half the publisher's
profits. But there were not enough sales to produce profits and
Cowan said all he got for his $5,000 was six copies of the book and
a tax writeoff.
   Gingrich has promised to disclose the names of all 21 once he
can contact them and obtain their permission. Thus far he has
identified only three, including James Tidwell of Douglasville,
Ga., James Richards of Carrollton and former Georgia Rep. Howard
``Bo'' Callaway.
   Cowan said he became interested in Gingrich's book in 1983 when
Gingrich mentioned the project during a speech to the Aspen Group,
a mostly Republican group of real estate professionals.
   Cowan said he invited Gingrich to speak at that meeting because
``I thought he had a message. At the time he was speaking out on
supply side economics and he was an outspoken conservative voice.''
   Cowan said the members of the group who attended the Aspen
meeting split the cost of Gingrich's travel and lodging expenses.
</TEXT>
