<FIRST>r i AM-Lebanon-Stinger     03-24 0315</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lebanon-Stinger,0325</SECOND>
<HEAD>Magazine Report: Islamic Group Has 2 Stinger Missiles</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A militant Moslem group has acquired two
U.S.-made Stinger surface-to-air missiles originally intended for
Afghan guerrillas, Ash-Shiraa magazine reported Friday.
   The weekly quoted an unidentified source close to the group as
saying the shoulder-held missiles ``have reached Lebanon through an
embassy that provided part of the large sum paid.''
   The magazine did not identify the group or the embassy.
   It also did not specify whether the fundamentalists were Shiite
or Sunni Moslem. Sunni factions have been inactive in Lebanon for
some time, however, and the magazine implied the militants belonged
to a pro-Iranian Shiite group.
   The missiles were shipped by the United States to seven Afghan
guerrilla factions based in Pakistan, the magazine said. The
phrasing of the report indicated the Moslem Afghan guerrillas sold
the Stingers to the Lebanese group.
   The Stinger is the U.S. Armed Forces' most potent anti-aircraft
weapon. The Afghan insurgents used the missiles to shoot down
Soviet fighter-bombers, helicopters and transport planes in the
nine-year war against Soviet intervention in Afghanistan.
   Ash-Shiraa said the Lebanese group was trying to smuggle the
Stingers out of the country, but did not elaborate.
   The report followed warnings of possible attacks on American
jetliners as part of Iran's confrontation with Western nations over
Salman Rushdie's book, ``The Satanic Verses.'' Many Moslems say the
novel defames Islam.
   Britain's domestic news agency, Press Association, quoted an
unidentified spokesman for the U.S. Federal Aviation Association as
saying U.S. airlines and airports around the world have been put on
alert for possible terrorist action.
   Ash-Shiraa gained international fame in November 1986 when it
broke the story of secret U.S. arms sales to Iran in return for
American hostages held in Lebanon by pro-Iranian Shiite factions.
   But the magazine's recent reports on the 15 foreign captives
held mainly by pro-Iranian factions have been inaccurate.
</TEXT>
