<FIRST>r i AM-Uganda-Rebels     03-24 0221</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Uganda-Rebels,0226</SECOND>
<HEAD>`Holy Spirit' Rebels Terrorize Villagers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KAMPALA, Uganda (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hundreds of civilians fled from two
village after rebels of the Holy Spirit Movement attacked and
looted their homes, the government-owned New Vision newspaper
reported Friday.
   It reported women, children and elderly people thronged the road
to nearby Lira after the attack Thursday on Alawo and Anyeke in the
northern district of Apac, 280 north of Kampala, Uganda's capital.
   New Vision quoted one witness, who was not identified, as
saying, ``The rebels surrounded the villages and shouted, `Don't
run!' Moments later they started unleashing terror on the
villagers.''
   The newspaper said witnesses did not know how many people were
killed and wounded.
   The rebels, led by Joseph Konyi, have been terrorizing northern
villages since early last year. They first used the name Lakwena 2
after the Holy Spirit Movement led by warrior-priestess Alice
Lakwena was crushed by army troops in late 1987. Ms. Lakwena fled
to Kenya and her follower returned to their home region in northern
Uganda and regrouped.
   Konyi subsequently became leader and adopted the Holy Spirit
Movement name. Army sources estimate that he has from 1,200 to
2,500 followers.
   The sources say his rebels follow some of the practices
encouraged by Ms. Lakwena, including smearing their bodies with oil
in the belief it will repel bullets.
