<FILEID>AP-NR-03-24-89 1714EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-NuclearCleanup     03-24 0355</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Nuclear Cleanup,340</SECOND>
<HEAD>Secretary Tells Scientists to Devise Cleanup Plan</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GUY DARST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Energy Secretary James D. Watkins said Friday
he is directing his department's scientists to devote more
attention to new methods of nuclear waste cleanup to support a plan
to establish cleanup priorities and schedules over the next five
years.
   Watkins wrote members of Congress that he hopes to have the
cleanup plan in place by August.
   During the next five years, ``immediate problems'' will be
``corrected'' and detailed long-term cleanup plans will be drawn up
for each site, said spokesman Phil Keif.
   The department produces nuclear weapons in at least 16
laboraties and factories in 12 states. Waste, both nuclear and
chemical, generated since the formation of the World War II
Manhattan Project in 1942 has resulted in massive contamination of
some areas around the facilities.
   The laboratories include some of the national laboratories run
by the department, where some of the nation's best scientists have
conducted basic research in a wide range of scientific disciplines.
It is these scientists that Watkins will call on for more
environmental work, possibly designating facilities to be in charge
of particular techniques or fields.
   Watkins told a Senate committee earlier this month that he
doubts the accuracy of common cleanup cost estimates of $60 billion
to $100 billion. ``I don't believe we need all those gold
watches,'' or frills, he said then.
   In his letter to Congress, Watkins said the five-year plan will
be composed of site plans that will ensure compliance with all
applicable state and federal requirements; ``will characterize and
assess the extent of contamination, where it exists, and assess
potential risk. The highest priorities will be placed on facilities
where contamination has occured that may potentially affect public
heatlh and the environment.''
   In addition, the department will ``assess current technology
development activities and provide a basis for future research,
development and demonstration of new and innovative environmental
technologies.''
   He said he intended to ``establish with Congress and the states
agreed-upon milestones to address the development of new
technologies as well as our environmental cleanup
responsibilities.''
</TEXT>
