<FIRST>u a PM-Steinberg 3rdLd-Writethru a0671 03-24 0592</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Steinberg, 3rd Ld - Writethru, a0671,0605</SECOND>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Steinberg Given Maximum Sentence of 8 to 25 Years</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 11 grafs to UPDATE with recommendation against parole,
more quotes. Picks up 10th graf, `The sources...' Will stand for PMs.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SAMUEL MAULL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Joel Steinberg today received a maximum sentence
of 8 to 25 years in prison for killing 6-year-old Lisa Steinberg,
his illegally adopted daughter.
   State Supreme Court Justice Harold Rothwax, saying Steinberg
showed ``extreme callousness'' and no remorse after the slaying,
also recommended against parole. Steinberg would normally be
eligible for parole in less than seven years because he has already
been jailed for nearly 17 months since his arrest.
   Steinberg, 47, was convicted of first-degree manslaughter Jan.
30 for the November 1987 beating death. Hundreds of letter writers
had urged that he get the maximum punishment.
   The death resulted from Steinberg's ``life of violence,
selfishness and self-gratification at the expense of other
people,'' Assistant District Attorney John McCusker told the court.
``Mr. Steinberg has shown not one ounce of remorse for killing
Elizabeth.''
   An emotional Steinberg, who did not testify at his trial,
addressed the court before his sentencing, saying, ``I understand
the meaning of remorse. I have remorse about losing my life.''
   He insisted he had not abused his daughter. ``At no point did I
ever ... neglect her, did I ever strike her in any way,'' he said.
   Steinberg _ who smiled, chuckled and fidgeted while his lawyers
offered lengthy presentencing motions _ wanted the judge to ``feel
he is worthy of redemption,'' defense attorney Perry Reich said
earlier.
   But Assistant District Attorney Peter Casolaro, in a presentence
report released this morning, called Steinberg an ``insensitive,
remorseless killer'' who should receive the maximum sentence
without chance of parole.
   ``In the year and half since (Lisa's) death, he has yet to
express any remorse for killing her,'' Casolaro wrote in an 18-page
presentencing memorandum.
   ``Society needs to be protected from such a self-centered,
insensitive, remorseless killer,'' the memo continued. ``The only
appropriate sentence is the maximum sentence ... with a
recommendation against any parole.''
   Sources who spoke on condition of anonymity said Rothwax had
gotten hundreds of letters from adoptive parents, childless couples
and people abused as children urging him to throw the book at
Steinberg.
   The sources said letters from Alaska to Florida also came from
child advocacy groups and domestic violence projects, including a
Georgia organization responsible for writing more than 100 letters.
   Not one of the letters recommended mercy for Steinberg, the
sources said, and some demanded the death penalty, which New York
lacks.
   Rothwax, asked to make the letters public, said he had destroyed
any letters involving the case.
   But a family advocacy group, Family Dynamics Inc., showed
reporters its letter to the judge, which said the maximum sentence
``will communicate that unspeakable crimes against children shall
not be condoned.''
   A disbarred lawyer, Steinberg had received the child shortly
after birth from an unwed teen-ager and raised her as his own
rather than arranging for the baby's adoption as he had promised.
   Charges against Hedda Nussbaum, Steinberg's long-time live-in
companion, were dropped when prosecutors determined she was too
physically and mentally incapacitated to be responsible for the
girl's death.
   Ms. Nussbaum, 46, testified under immunity as the star
prosecution witness in Steinberg's trial, during which defense
attorneys contended she was responsible for Lisa's fatal beating.
   The Steinberg case focused national attention on domestic
violence and the question of who should report cases of suspected
child abuse.
</TEXT>
