<FILEID>AP-NR-03-24-89 1715EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-ThinBlueLine-Jury     03-24 0359</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Thin Blue Line-Jury,0369</SECOND>
<HEAD>Jury Forewoman, Other Jurors Express Doubts About Their Verdict</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jurors who sentenced Randall Dale Adams to die 12
years ago say they are convinced they erred in declaring him
guilty, but blame a prosecutor for swaying their minds by
suppressing evidence.
   Adams, 40, was greeted by yellow ribbons and rousing cheers when
he returned Thursday to Columbus, Ohio, after the Dallas County
district attorney dropped the case against him.
   He was freed on bond Tuesday after the Texas Court of Criminal
Appeals ordered a new trial. His case garnered wide attention after
``The Thin Blue Line,'' a documentary film, raised doubts about his
guilt.
   ``If he had gone to the death chamber and all this had come out
later, that would have been a horrible thing to have on my
conscience,'' said Bette Jane Fain, jury forewoman at Adams' 1977
trial.
   Adams came within three days of execution in 1980 for the
shooting death of Dallas officer Robert Wood before his sentence
was commuted to life in prison.
   ``Based on everything that I have seen and read and on this
man's reactions, I just don't believe the man is guilty,'' Ms.
Fain, 66, told the Dallas Morning News.
   Dallas County District Attorney John Vance said Thursday he
would not seek a new trial and filed a motion to dismiss the
capital murder charge against Adams.
   The appeals court, in ordering a new trial for Adams, ruled
prosecutor Doug Mulder had allowed a key witness to commit perjury
and had suppressed evidence that the witness' original description
of the killer did not match Adams.
   ``It makes you wonder sometimes about the judicial system,''
said juror Elliott Rammey. ``If somebody as powerful as the DA's
office can manipulate witnesses, it seems to me there's something
wrong.
   ``Hopefully, we'll all learn something from it,'' Rammey, 47,
said.
   Mulder has denied any misconduct and said he believes Adams is
guilty. He did not immediately return a telephone call Friday by
The Associated Press.
   ``If anything was kept from us, I blame Doug Mulder,'' juror
Doris Hooper, 74, said. ``What happened is not the jury's fault.''
</TEXT>
