<FILEID>AP-NR-03-24-89 1724EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-China-Education     03-24 0533</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-China-Education,0552</SECOND>
<HEAD>China Says Its Education System Faces Crisis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN POMFRET</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   High school enrollment has fallen more than 25
percent since 1978, when China embarked on ambitious economic
development, and senior leader Deng Xiaoping says there is a crisis
in education.
   Elementary school enrollment has declined more than 14 percent
in the same period.
   Education Minister Li Tieying told a news conference Friday the
government cannot devote enough money to the problems and advocated
an education tax. He implied other funds should be raised through
tuition and schools starting their own businesses to make money.
   Deng was quoted in the People's Daily as saying: ``Our biggest
mistake over the last 10 years is that education has not developed
sufficiently.''
   He said the mistake surpassed errors that have created an
inflation rate of 36 percent, the highest since the Communist Party
gained power in 1949.
   China used to take pride in free education, but has begun
forcing schools to set up factories to pay expenses. Some now
charge tuition to pay for books and other materials.
   Li's news conference coincided with a session of the National
People's Congress, which is studying a proposal to raise the
education budget by 15 percent to $10 billion.
   Last year, China spent $11 a student, among the world's lowest.
   About one-third of all pupils now finish primary school and
fewer than 10 percent of those attend high school or college.
Despite a law requiring nine years of education, the average
Chinese spends five years in school.
   Several problems have combined to create the education crisis.
   Agriculture policies giving land back to the peasants caused
many to put their children to work. Li said 8.5 percent of
elementary pupils and 2.65 percent of high school students left
school last year and 220 million Chinese are illiterate, most of
them in rural areas.
   Educated Chinese are poorly paid. Starting salaries for Chinese
men and women with college diplomas are about $29 a month,
one-tenth of what a hairdresser can earn.
   ``This is not the kind of incentive that makes people want to
get an education,'' Li said.
   Statistics released Friday said 65.4 million youngsters were
attending high school in 1978, but the figure last year was 47.6
million.
   On the bright side, the number of students in college increased
from 856,000 to 2.7 million and the number of colleges doubled to
1,075, according to the statistics.
   An increasing number of graduate students are leaving school,
however, to seek higher wages outside teaching and research.
   The physical plant also has suffered. Li said more than 60
percent of the junior high schools and 90 percent of elementary
schools lacked sufficient facilities and supplies last year.
   Many teachers are not qualified, he said, but was not specific.
Li said teachers are paid less than the average worker in a
state-run factory.
   He said the responsibility rests with the State Council, or
Cabinet, and the Central Committee of the Communist Party.
   Li has led the State Education Commission for one year. Premier
Li Peng was education minister in 1985-88, when the commission was
given responsibility for elementary and secondary schools as well
as higher education.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
