<FIRST>r w AM-OffshoreDrilling     03-24 0217</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Offshore Drilling,200</SECOND>
<HEAD>Panetta Seeks to Halt Work on Three Offshore Oil and Gas Lease Sales</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rep. Leon Panetta, D-Calif., chairman of the
House Budget Committee, said Friday he is seeking legislation to
halt work on three offshore oil and gas lease sales in California.
   Panetta said work on the lease sales should stop until a
presidential task force finishes its analysis of the environmental
impact of outer continental shelf oil and gas leasing, and Congress
and the public have time to review it.
   The lease sales involve the area off the coast of Humboldt and
Mendocino counties, that portion stretching from San Luis Obispo
County to the U.S.-Mexico border and the area covering the central
coast area from Sonoma County to Monterey County.
   Panetta said he will request the legislation April 25 in
testimony before the House interior appropriations subcommittee.
   He said legislation is necessary because Bush administration
officials have said that before-lease steps for lease sales on two
sections of the coast will continue and that the central section is
not be to included in the task force's review.
   ``There is simply no point in continuing work on this sale until
we have more information on the environmental impacts of offshore
drilling in all critical areas of our coast,'' he said.
</TEXT>
