<FIRST>r i AM-Belgium-Kidnapping     03-24 0318</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Belgium-Kidnapping,0329</SECOND>
<HEAD>Lawyer Charged In Vanden Boeynants Kidnapping</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A neighbor of former Premier Paul
Vanden Boeynants was charged Friday in the January kidnapping of
the wealthy businessman, who was freed a month later after his
family paid an undisclosed ransom.
   Officials said Michel Vander Elst, 41, is the lawyer of Patrick
Haemers, an escaped convict considered the key suspect in the
kidnapping. Haemers escaped from a prison transport truck in August
1987, and remains at large.
   Vander Elst was taken in for questioning on Thursday. He was
charged Friday with kidnapping, extortion, forgery and conspiracy,
officials said.
   Haemers' father and brother were questioned Friday, officials
said.
   Vander Elst is the second person under arrest. Basri Bajrami was
arrested in Metz, France, last month and is to be extradited to
Belgium.
   On Thursday, police found Vander Elst at his home, which is in
the same Brussels apartment building where Vanden Boeynants lives.
Several men abducted the 69-year-old Christian Democrat from the
building's garage as he parked his car on the evening of Jan. 14.
   Vanden Boeynants was held in a dark room at a house in Le
Touquet, France, and released in Tournai, Belgium, on Feb. 13,
officials say.
   He said he was held by as many as five armed men whose faces he
never saw and with whom he communicated in writing.
   The kidnappers, in rambling notes to Belgian media, claimed
responsibility for the abduction on behalf of a non-existing
left-wing group.
   Vanden Boeynants' family paid an undisclosed ransom through a
Swiss bank. Belgian newspapers have put the amount at up to $1.6
million.
   Vanden Boeynants was prime minister from 1966-68 and again from
1978-79. He also was defense minister for seven years during the
1970s.
   He has long been a controversial politician. In 1988, he
received a three-year suspended sentence for tax fraud and forgery
as head of a Brussels meat-packing company.
</TEXT>
