<FILEID>AP-NR-03-24-89 1730EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-TestingSuit     03-24 0196</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Testing Suit,170</SECOND>
<HEAD>Union Challenges Education Department's Drug Test Plan</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A union representing 3,000 Education
Department workers has filed a court challenge to the department's
plans to begin a random drug-testing program next month.
   The suit, filed in U.S. District Court here Thursday, is the
latest of more than a half-dozen attempts by the American
Federation of Government Employees to block drug-testing programs
in federal departments and agencies. The cases filed previously are
pending at various levels of the federal court system.
   ``We are confident the courts will not sanction programs that
randomly select government workers and require them to submit to
humiliating urinalysis testing without any history or reasonable
suspicion of drug abuse problems,'' said AFGE President John N.
Sturdivant.
   A union spokeswoman said the Education Department on Feb. 21
distributed to employees a notice that the testing program would
begin on or after April 21. Federal agencies, as part of their
compliance with an executive order issued by then-President Reagan
requiring them to draft drug-testing programs, routinely give
employees 60 days' notice before begining testing.
   Education Department spokesman Jim Bradshaw said the department
had no comment on the union's suit.
</TEXT>
