<FILEID>AP-NR-03-24-89 1800EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-ManchinImpeachment     03-24 0432</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Manchin Impeachment,0443</SECOND>
<HEAD>West Virginia Senators Told to Expect Treasurer Impeachment Trial
in May</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By A.V. GALLAGHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHARLESTON, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   West Virginia's state senators were
notified Friday to be prepared to sit as a jury for an expected
impeachment trial against the state treasurer at the end of May.
   ``It would appear likely that the House of Delegates will next
week send us a message containing the articles of impeachment
against state Treasurer A. James Manchin,'' Senate President Larry
Tucker wrote in a memorandum to his 33 colleagues.
   ``I would anticipate a starting date for the impeachment trial
being toward the end of May, and I also anticipate it lasting three
to four weeks,'' Tucker wrote.
   Tucker said he believes two-thirds or more of the 100-member
House will vote to impeach Manchin, 61, a two-term treasurer
tangled in allegations that a fund under his supervision lost $279
million in 1987, and that he failed to perform the proper
supervisory functions over the fund.
   Manchin has distanced himself from the losses. He testified
before the House Judiciary Committee last week that he never
discussed specific investment practices with his staff, didn't
understand investment documents when they crossed his desk, and
didn't learn of the losses until late November or early December
1988.
   The judiciary committee voted 19-6 Wednesday to recommend that
Manchin be impeached for maladministration, incompetence, neglect
of duty and high crimes and misdemeanors for his role in the loss.
   House Judiciary Chairman John Hatcher said his committee on
Monday will take up the formal articles of impeachment _ drafted
along the lines suggested by Wednesday's vote _ and vote on the
final document. The resolution then goes to the House.
   Only a simple majority is needed to recommend impeachment, which
is, in effect, an indictment of the treasurer. That would go to the
Senate, which would sit as a jury. It would take a two-thirds vote
by the Senate _ 23 of 34 members _ to convict.
   If convicted, Manchin would be forced from office and would lose
his pension, estimated at the end of 1988 by the Public Employees
Retirement System to be at least $2,128 a month, the agency's
acting director George Crum said Friday.
   The timetable for when the resolution will be presented to the
House has not been resolved, Hatcher said, but the 60-day
legislative session ends April 8.
   The last time a West Virginia state treasurer was impeached was
1876.
   Manchin's attorney, Frank Cleckley, has hinted, without
elaboration, that he may file a lawsuit challenging the impeachment
proceedings against his client.
</TEXT>
