<FILEID>AP-NR-03-24-89 1729EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Peru-Guerrillas     03-24 0238</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Peru-Guerrillas,0246</SECOND>
<HEAD>Guerrillas Kill 5 in Mine Raids; Strike Declared Illegal</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LIMA, Peru (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Leftist guerrillas raided two government
copper mines in the Andes, killing five people and blowing up a
barracks and offices, police said Friday.
   Miners have announced plans for a three-day nationwide strike to
begin Monday, but the official gazette El Peruano said Friday it
was illegal.
   Unions want all contracts for Peru's 70,000 miners to be
negotiated jointly rather than with individual companies, as is the
practice now. Two strikes on the same issue failed last year.
   Guerrillas of Shining Path, a Maoist group that began fighting
nine years ago, attacked the Yauricocha and Chumpe mines near La
Oroya, 95 miles east of Lima, on Thursday, police reported.
   They said the worst raid was the first, on Yauricocha, where two
policemen, two watchmen and an office employee were killed.
   Members of the guerrilla band used dynamite to blow up a vacant
barracks used by administration workers and stole drugs and
medicine from the mine clinic, the report said.
   Guards at Chumpe, about five miles away, apparently did not
resist, and the raiders destroyed mine offices with dynamite, the
police said.
   Both mines are are operated by state-owned Centromin, Peru's
largest mining company.
   Shining Path guerrillas have increased attacks on the mining
industry, which produces more than half the nation's export
earnings. More than 14,000 people have been killed since the
insurgency began.
</TEXT>
