<FILEID>AP-NR-03-24-89 1807EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Nicaragua-Church     03-24 0393</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Nicaragua-Church,0406</SECOND>
<HEAD>Church Leaders Call For National Reconciliation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELOY O. AGUILAR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Roman Catholic church leaders marked
Good Friday by calling for reconciliation among Nicaraguans and
criticizing both the U.S.-backed rebels and the Sandinista
government.
   At a Good Friday procession attended by an estimated 30,000
people, Monsignor Bismarck Carballo, the church spokesman, told the
crowd: ``This is the year all Nicaraguans hope will bring national
reconciliation.''
   Cardinal Miguel Obando y Bravo, who led the procession
commemorating Christ's tortured journey to Cavalry, cried out,
``Long live Catholic Nicaragua, long live the pope!'' and people
cheered.
   They cheered again when he shouted, ``One church!'' referring to
the so-called Popular Church of dissident Catholics who support the
left-wing Sandinistas.
   Thursday night during a ceremony recalling Christ's washing the
feet of his disciples, Obando y Bravo said ``it would have been
beautiful'' if the rebel command ``had released all its prisoners
of war so they could reunite with their families.
   ``And it would have been a good thing if the government of
Nicaragua had declared a general amnesty to bring happiness to
prisoners and their families and to contribute to national
reconciliation.''
   Obando y Bravo urged faithful Catholics to take part in politics
to provide ``an example of responsibility and service for the
common good.''
   The cardinal has been a frequent critic of the Sandinistas,
accusing them of trying to impose a leftist government in
predominantly Catholic Nicaragua against the will of the people.
   Some former national guard members, who were among the 1,894
freed last week by the government, joined in the Good Friday
procession, and a few wore their old uniforms.
   Thousands of national guardsmen were imprisoned after the
Sandinistas gained power in 1979, ousting the right-wing regime of
President Anastasio Somoza.
   The government said only 39 ex-guardsmen remain in jail, and
they are ``very dangerous and undisciplined.''
   Last week's ceremonial release of nearly 1,900 guardsmen was
part of the revived Central American peace accord the presidents of
Nicaragua, El Salvador, Honduras, Costa Rica and Guatemala signed
in February. It includes plans to disband the Nicaraguan rebel
army, believed to have about 11,000 members.
   Government sources claim the rebels, known as Contras, are
holding at least 1,000 pro-Sandinistas prisoners, including
soldiers and civilians. The Contras acknowledged last year that
they held some prisoners but gave no figures.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
