<DOCNO> AP890324-0150 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-24-89 1808EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-ContraReaction     03-24 0376</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Contra Reaction,380</SECOND>
<HEAD>With AM-US-Nicaragua</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Contra spokesman lauded the Bush
administration's newly announced humanitarian aid plan Friday as a
``very significant step'' that will keep their fighters alive while
diplomatic peace efforts are pursued.
   The Contras had expected they would get some continued aid, said
Nicaraguan Resistance spokesman Bosco Matamoros.
   The most positive aspect of the $45 million aid plan announced
at the White House was that it represents for the first time '`a
national policy on a bipartisan consensus,'' said Matamoros.
   In addition, he said, ``We have resolved a fundamental problem
which is the integrity of our combatants,'' who are encamped on the
Honduran side of the Nicaraguan border. They have been existing on
$27 million worth of U.S. non-lethal aid which runs out March 31.
   Contra leader Adolfo Calero, perhaps the most well known
resistance figure in the United States because of his longtime U.S.
travels for his cause, was in Guatemala and could not be reached
Friday by phone, said a man who answered the phone at his Miami
home.
   Another top Contra leader, Alfredo Cesar, was in Miami but could
not be reached for comment at his home there.
   During the Reagan administration, the Contras were taken care of
through a covert White House plan even when Congress halted
military aid, but dissension on Capitol Hill and within the
administration weakened their cause, Contra leaders have said.
   ``It's a very significant step taken by the United States,''
Matamoros said. ``The United States now enters with the Central
American countries and other Latin American countries in this
concert which enhances the possibility ... of arriving to a process
of democratization in Nicaragua.''
   As to the plan's provision of money for voluntary repatriation
on the part of the 11,000-member Contra army, Matamoros said,
``It's very clear that if there is democracy we are willing return
to our country.''
   But he said most of the rebels will likely wait to see how
Nicaragua's ruling Sandinista government lives up to its pledge for
democratic reforms and free elections early next year.
   The Contras also want to participate in a reconciliation
dialogue with the Sandinistas and the internal political
opposition, Matamoros said. Previous efforts were fruitless.
 
</TEXT>
</DOC>
