<FILEID>AP-NR-03-24-89 1811EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-India-Punjab     03-24 0256</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-India-Punjab,0264</SECOND>
<HEAD>Militants Kill 14, Including Seven Family Members</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sikh militants in the northwestern state
of Punjab raided the house of a Sikh woman and killed her and six
members of her family, Press Trust of India said Friday.
   At least seven others were killed in other militant-related
violence in Punjab, said United News of India, another news agency.
   More than 455 people have been killed in such violence so far
this year, officials say.
   According to Press Trust, militants raided the house of Dhan
Kaur in Katran village near Amritsar, about 280 miles northwest of
New Delhi. The militants fired guns and killed Kaur, two of her
sons, three daughters and a daughter-in-law, the news agency said.
   It said police blamed members of the radical ``Bhindranwale
Tigers Force'' for the slayings. The group is one of about a dozen
underground militias based in Punjab fighting for a separate Sikh
state.
   Sikhs make up 2 percent of India's population but hold a slight
majority in Punjab, a prosperous farming state.
   Militants have killed thousands of Hindus and moderate Sikhs in
their insurgency for an independent Sikh nation since 1982. They
say they are discriminated against by the country's Hindu majority,
which makes up 82 percent of the population.
   The federal government, in an effort to curb the violence,
dissolved the state government in May 1987 and put Punjab under
federal rule.
   But authorities say Sikh militants killed at least 2,400 last
year, more than double the number killed in 1987.
</TEXT>
