<DOCNO> AP890324-0153 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-24-89 1747EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Nicaragua-US     03-24 0653</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Nicaragua-US,0672</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sandinistas Condemn US Contra Aid Renewal Plan</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-US-Central America, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DORALISA PILARTE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The leftist Sandinista government on
Friday condemned the bipartisan plan President Bush announced in
Washington to renew humanitarian aid to the Nicaraguan rebels.
   Foreign Ministry Secretary-General Alejandro Bendana called the
plan drafted by the Bush administration and congressional leaders
``confusing and unclear'' and said it goes against a regional pact
that calls for dismantling the rebel force by mid-May.
   ``Humanitarian aid to a standing military force is a
contradiction in terms,'' Bendana said at a news conference, where
journalists had been told President Daniel Ortega was to speak.
Ortega's absence was not explained.
   Bendana and Manuel Espinoza, presidential information minister,
read a communique from the Nicaraguan government which said in part
that the U.S. government drafted the plan ``in order to save face
while it proceeds to dismantle its failed policy against
Nicaragua's sovereignty and integrity.''
   Answering journalists' questions later, Bendana said of the plan:
   ``We want to believe this is indeed a positive step, because
there are other steps ahead'' where the United States can show its
support of the peace accord that Ortega and the presidents of El
Salvador, Honduras, Guatemala and Costa Rica reached in El Salvador
on Feb. 14.
   In the El Salvador accord the five presidents agreed to draft a
program by mid-May to dismantle the Contras, as the Nicaraguan
rebel force is known, and help them return to civilian life.
   Ortega also agreed to electoral and other reforms to guarantee
fair general elections, which he moved up by 10 months to Feb. 25,
1990.
   In speaking of ``other steps ahead,'' Bendana said he was
referring to support needed from the United States to have a U.N.
peacekeeping force sent to Central America and independent
observers to the Nicaraguan elections, both part of the El Salvador
pact.
   The United States, as one of the five permanent members of the
U.N. Security Council, can veto the measure.
   Bendana called the vote ``an acid test'' of U.S. intentions
toward Nicaragua.
   Congress voted in February 1988 to cut off military aid to the
Contras, which the United States began arming in 1981, and continue
only food, shelter, medical and other non-lethal assistance.
   The bipartisan agreement announced in Washington on Friday calls
for $45 million in new aid through February 1990 for the estimated
11,000 Contras living in Honduran jungle camps near the Nicaraguan
border with an equal number of relatives.
   The expressed intent of the aid renewal is to put pressure on
the Sandinistas to comply with the El Salvador pact. The current
$27.1 million aid package to the rebels runs out March 31.
   The new aid is expected to be approved by Congress soon after it
returns from its Easter break next month.
   ``There is an inconsistency in these two documents (the El
Salvador pact and the U.S. bilateral Contra aid plan),'' Bendana
said. ``Either you approve the dismantling of the Contras or you
don't.''
   He said that regardless of the U.S. Contra aid plan, the Central
American presidents will meet their mid-May deadline for the Contra
dismantling plan.
   Since the El Salvador accord, the Nicaraguan government has
released nearly 1,900 former members of the National Guard, most of
whom were jailed after a revolution that brought the Sandinistas to
power July 19, 1979.
   Nicaragua also sent to the National Assembly a list of reforms
on electoral and other laws, as part of the El Salvador accord.
Passage of the reforms is virtually assured because the
Sandinistas, with 61 deputies, control the unicameral 96-member
assembly.
   The Sandinistas and the Contras signed a temporary cease-fire in
March 1988 which has been broken by sporadic skirmishes. he plan
Bush announced Friday stipulates that aid can be suspended if the
Contras attack Nicaragua or if the presence of the Contras is
deemed detrimental to the Central American peace process.
</TEXT>
