<FIRST>r i AM-Gorbachev-Ireland 1stLdWritethru a0634 03-24 0274</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Gorbachev-Ireland, 1st Ld Writethru, a0634,0279</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviet, Irish Leaders to Meet April 2</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: ADDS 7 grafs with details, background.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DUBLIN, Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviet President Mikhail S. Gorbachev
will meet with Prime Minister Charles Haughey during an April 2
stopover at an Irish airport on his trip to Cuba, the Irish leader
said Friday.
   Their first-ever meeting, made at Gorbachev's request, is
expected to last several hours at a site near Shannon International
Airport in western Ireland, Haughey said.
   They plan to discuss international and bilateral issues
including the development of the ``excellent relationship between
Ireland and the Soviet Union,'' Haughey said.
   It will be the first official visit to Ireland by a Soviet
leader, according to the Department of Foreign Affairs.
   Gorbachev and his wife, Raisa, will visit Britain from April
5-7. Gorbachev had been scheduled to visit Britain in December
after his visit to the United States, but postponed the trip to
rush to earthquake-devastated Soviet Armenia.
   British officials say Gorbachev and Prime Minister Margaret
Thatcher will spend much of the time in talks dominated by
East-West relations, human rights and disarmament.
   Ireland and the Soviet Union exchanged ambassadors for the first
time in 1974.
   The overwhelmingly Roman Catholic country won partial
independence from Britain in 1921, and the Soviet Union was the
first country to recognize its republican government.
   The republicans negotiated with Soviet diplomats, but failed to
get an agreement on establishing diplomatic links.
   In September 1983, Ireland barred the Soviet state airline,
Aeroflot, from picking up or discharging passengers at Shannon for
60 days to protest the shooting down of a South Korean airliner
over Soviet airspace.
</TEXT>
