<FIRST>r w AM-Pentagon-McGovern 470   03-24 0462</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Pentagon-McGovern, 470</SECOND>
<HEAD>AF Head to Leave</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NORMAN BLACK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Military Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Acting Air Force Secretary James F. McGovern
announced late Friday he will step down later this spring to seek a
job in the private sector.
   McGovern has served as the under secretary, or No. 2, man, in
the Air Force's heirarchy since November 1986 and as the acting
secretary since last December.
   An associate of former Sen. John Tower, McGovern had been widely
expected to take on the Air Force post on a permanent basis had
Tower been confirmed as the secretary of defense.
   Tower's nomination was rejected two weeks ago by the Senate and
President Bush replaced him with former Wyoming congressman Dick
Cheney.
   ``In a meeting I had with Defense Secretary Cheney earlier this
week, I indicated that I was inclined to return to the private
sector so that I could finally give my two daughters the attention
they deserve and to pursue several other professional interests,''
McGovern said in a prepared statement.
   ``Without making any commitments, Secretary Cheney asked that we
both keep our options open. However, today I indicated to Secretary
Cheney my preference for leaving public service ...''
   An aide said McGovern is planning to leave in May.
   McGovern's announcement comes one day after administration
sources disclosed Navy Secretary William L. Ball is also unlikely
to keep his post in a new Cheney line-up.
   Ball, another associate of Tower, has said nothing about leaving
his job. But the sources said Thursday that Assistant Defense
Secretary Richard L. Armitage had been told by Cheney he was being
considered for the job of Navy secretary, among others.
   The secretary of the Army, John O. Marsh, long ago made it clear
he planned to retire as soon as the Bush administration selected a
successor and was not interested in remaining.
   McGovern's announcement Friday came as Cheney, during his first
press conference, publicly rebuked the Air Force's top general for
consulting privately with congressional leaders on how to modernize
the nuclear arsenal.
   The aide to McGovern, who asked not to be named, insisted that
controversy involving Gen. Larry D. Welch had played no role in
McGovern's decision.
   ``All this happened earlier in the week and there's no tie-in,''
said the aide. ``He's been thinking about it for a long time.''
   McGovern, a native of Dayton, Ohio, is a graduate of the U.S.
Naval Academy and Georgetown Law School. He has worked as a Navy
fighter pilot, a corporate attorney and as the staff director of
the Senate Armed Services Committee under Tower.
   In his statement, McGovern said it ``has been my great privilege
and honor to have served with the thousands of dedicated and
professional men and women of the United States Air Force.''
</TEXT>
