<FIRST>r i AM-Burma-Arrest     03-24 0275</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Burma-Arrest,0284</SECOND>
<HEAD>Prominent Student Activist Arrested</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RANGOON, Burma (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Authorities have arrested a prominent
student leader and will act against political parties involved in
any anti-government demonstrations, the government said Friday.
   The arrest Thursday of Min Ko Naing was the first of a well
known student activist since military commander Gen. Saw Maung
seized power in a coup in September.
   Government spokesman Kyaw Sann said that from March 15-21, Min
Ko Naing made seven anti-government speeches at offices of the
National League For Democracy, a major political party headed by
dissident leaders Tin Oo and Aung San Suu Kyi.
   The student also violated the ban on public gatherings, Kyaw
Sann said.
   ``Min Ko Naing and his groups have repeatedly violated the law,
inciting the people to disrupt the peace and tranquility in the
country,'' he said at a news conference. ``They were also planning
to disrupt the forthcoming Armed Forces Day celebrations on March
27.''
   ``Action will also be taken against political parties involved
in these anti-government activities,'' Kyaw Sann said.
   Students took a leading role in street demonstrations last year
aimed at ending a quarter century of authoritarian rule in Burma.
   Saw Maung's troops killed hundreds of people in suppressing
dissent. He later allowed the formation of alternative political
parties and promised a general election in 1990.
   Min Ko Naing was a leader of the student group most prominently
involved in the campaign for democracy, the All Burma Student
Federation.
   Most members of the federation went underground or fled to areas
along the Thailand border after the coup. Min Ko Naing and two
other leaders resurfaced in Rangoon late in the year.
