<FIRST>u a AM-Hijack-IBM 1stLd-Writethru a0666 03-24 0407</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hijack-IBM, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0666,0415</SECOND>
<HEAD>IBM Advises Employees To Avoid U.S. Airlines To Europe, Mideast</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS Lead to fix spelling of first word; SUBS 4th graf, `It
is ..., to CLARIFY that IBM employees not obliged to choose an alternate
airline. Picks up 5th graf pvs, `The FAA ...</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   International Business Machines Corp. has
advised its employees against flying U.S. carriers on some routes
until the end of next month because of the government warning about
a possible hijacking in Europe.
   ``On the basis of the FAA (Federal Aviation Administration)
alert, IBM notified its employees to avoid traveling on U.S. air
carriers from Europe and the Middle East until the end of April,''
IBM spokeswoman Colette Abissi said Friday.
   She said the notification was issued Thursday through the
company's internal security channels. IBM employs 163,904 people
outside the United States.
   It is strictly up to employees to decide what travel
arrangements to make, she said.
   The FAA confirmed Thursday it had issued a security bulletin to
airports and carriers March 16 about ``the possibility of a
hijacking of a U.S. airliner in Western Europe.''
   The warning did not mention any specific airline or airport that
might be threatened, nor did it cite any time for the warning, the
FAA said.
   The White House has sought to calm anxiety about the bulletin,
which leaked in a front-page newspaper story in London.
   Bush administration officials said the bulletin was similar to
many other terrorist alerts and travelers ``should be confident
that all reasonable precautions are being taken.''
   Security also was strengthened this week at Los Angeles
International Airport because of the warning, although it specified
Europe, airport officials said.
   ``We have the ability to react to any type of situation,'' said
airport manager Stephen Yee.
   Meanwhile, a spot check of travel agents did not find that
travelers were reacting by altering their reservations.
   H. Wayne Berens, president of Revere Travel Inc. in Trenton,
N.J., said he was unaware of any customers seeking to change their
travel plans.
   Herbert Teison, editor and publisher of two travel newsletters
including Travel Smart for Business, said ``My feeling is that the
majority of people will not pay attention to it'' if they already
are booked on a U.S. airline.
   ``If reservations are already made, they will let them sit,''
said Teison. ``But in making reservations they will lean toward
making them on a foreign carrier.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890324-0160 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-24-89 1824EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Europe-AirTravel     03-24 0590</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Europe-Air Travel,0611</SECOND>
<HEAD>Easter Travelers Fly Despite Warning; No Severe Delays</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   European airport officials indicated severe delays
were averted Friday because travelers, aware of reports that a
hijacking might be attempted, checked in early and faced extra
luggage searches calmly.
   The Federal Aviation Administration warned U.S. airlines of a
possible hijack by Palestinian terrorists in Europe this weekend. A
London newspaper disclosed the warning Thursday, angering the
American government, which feared its sources might be compromised.
   International Business Machines Corp., which employs 163,904
people outside the United States, advised them not to fly U.S.
airlines on European and Middle Eastern routes until the end of
April.
   Police at Leonardo da Vinci Airport in Rome said the FAA warning
prompted increased security and that more staff members were
checking bags and working in the metal-detecting section.
   No takeoff delays were reported, and reservations agents at U.S.
airline counters said the number of cancellations was not unusual.
   Security experts in Italy also were wary because of the
approaching anniversary of the U.S. bombing of Libya on April 15,
1986.
   On April 14 last year, a bomb exploded a USO in Naples, killing
an American woman and four other people. The Japanese Red Army was
blamed.
   ANSA, the Italian news agency, quoted Libyan Ambassador
Abdulrahman Shalgam as telling reporters Friday that allegations of
Libyan involvement in attacks allegedly planned were an
``absurdity.''
   At London's Heathrow airport, passengers found themselves in
long lines as bags were carefully searched and their owners
questioned.
   Some passengers traveling on American lines faced double checks,
by the airport staff and the airlines. Airlines tightened security
after the bombing Dec. 21 of Pan Am Flight 103, in which 270 people
were killed.
   Most travelers appeared to have arrived early, as suggested, and
delays generally were limited to a little more than an hour.
   ``I think most people have been well informed and are taking
advice about arriving early and not carrying electrical
equipment,'' said Bob Hearn, manager of customer services at
British Airways Terminal 4.
   Investigators say the Flight 103 bomb was in a radio-cassette
player. British airports now insist that small electronic and
electrical goods be inspected and carried in hand baggage.
   At Gatwick, the other London airport, officials reported delays
up to four hours but said most flights took off on time.
   One traveler said on British Broadcasting Corp television: ``We
just keep our fingers crossed. That's all you can do.''
   The situation was complicated by a 90-minute fault in an air
traffic control computer in the morning, which delayed flights at
airports in central England.
   In Frankfurt, West Germany, an airport spokeswoman said
increased security was in effect and some flights were held up, but
the delays were not ``of a substantial nature.''
   Athens airport officials said security always is tight, and a
spokeswoman said: ``we had normal delays which had nothing to do
with extra security.''
   A Lisbon airport official said security checks were slightly
more rigorous than normal, particularly on U.S. airlines, but
flights were not delayed.
   Airport authorities in Amsterdam said security measures had been
``quietly beefed up,'' but caused no delays or cancellations.
   French police in charge of air transport reported nothing
unusual at the Paris airports.
   In Spain, security officials said the warning had not affected
standing rules, which require teams of armed paramilitary Civil
Guards and police to be on duty at all times at major airports.
   Control tower spokesmen at Madrid's Barajas airport and El Prat
in Barcelona reported no delays Friday in international arrivals.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
