<FIRST>r w AM-BlackRepublicans     03-24 0570</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Black Republicans,570</SECOND>
<HEAD>Black GOP Group Says Won't Attend Meeting if Farrakhan Takes Part</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A black Republican group is refusing to attend
next month's ``African-American Summit'' led by a group of
prominent blacks because of the possible participation of Nation of
Islam leader Louis Farrakhan.
   In a letter Friday to former presidential candidate Jesse
Jackson, Fred Brown, chairman of the National Black Republican
Council, said he and the 150 members of his group would not take
part because the philosophies of Farrakhan and black militants
Angela Davis and Stokely Carmichael ``are offensive to us.''
   Brown's organization is an arm of the Republican National
Committee.
   Jackson is an honorary chairman of the African-American Summit
which is scheduled for April 21-23 in New Orleans. Other honorary
chairmen include Coretta Scott King, NAACP head Benjamin Hooks,
National Urban League president John Jacob, Dorothy Height of the
National Council of Negro Women and Joseph Lowery of the Southern
Christian Leadership Conference.
   Richard Hatcher, former mayor of Gary, Ind., is the general
chairman of the bi-partisan summit which has the stated purpose of
developing an ``African-American agenda'' for the next four years.
   The coordinator of the summit, Kay Hixson, confirmed that
Farrakhan had been asked to participate as a panelist on black
families, but said she did not know about any participation by
Davis or Carmichael. She said the summit organizers have not
received a response from Farrakhan.
   A spokesman for Jackson said he was on the board of the summit
but was not involved in organizing it or inviting people.
   ``He has nothing to do with the planning of it,'' said spokesman
Eric Easter, who added however that the idea for the summit was
raised at a black leadership meeting Jackson held in Chicago in
December.
   Fred Brown in the leter to Jackson, with a copy to Hatcher, said
that the GOP group ``cannot serve on, nor participate in, the
African-American summit as long as these individuals are associated
with the cause.''
   Brown's letter says that Jackson on Jan. 27 informed the summit
steering committee that he also ``could not be associated with this
undertaking if these same individuals were allowed to be official
summit speakers.''
   The committee voted to exclude Farrakhan and tabled the issue of
Davis and Carmichael, the letter said.
   Subsequently, according to Brown's letter, ``some individuals
have fought diligently to have them included in the summit.''
   ``I feel that the move to revisit the question of participation
of these three individuals has been a breach of faith - not on your
part, but on the part of others,'' Brown wrote Jackson.
   Jackson's relationship with Farrakhan became an issue in his
1984 campaign for the Democratic presidential nomination, because
Farrakhan referred to Judaism as a ``dirty religion.'' Jackson
dissociated himself from Farrakhan's remarks but did not rebuke
him. Farrakhan played no role in Jackson's 1988 campaign.
   Hixson said Farrakhan was selected as a panelist ``because he
does play a prominent role'' in black family issues.
   Angela Davis, a Communist Party black radical, and Stokely
Carmichael, former head of the Student Nonviolent Coordinating
Committee, were leaders in the militant black power movement on the
1960s.
   Republican National Committee Communications Director Mark
Goodin said RNC officials were unfamiliar with the summit or the
controversy, and had no comment on Brown's action except to say
that ``from all we've heard, his reasoning is sound.''
</TEXT>
