<FIRST>r i AM-SatanicVerses     03-24 0307</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Satanic Verses,0317</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pakistani In Hiding For Plans To Translate Rushdie's Book</HEAD>
<DATELINE>STOCKHOLM, Sweden (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Pakistani living in Sweden said
Friday he has gone into hiding after receiving death threats for
planning to translate Salman Rushdie's book ``The Satanic Verses.''
   Police speculated that a Malaysian slain in Stockholm early
Wednesday was mistaken for the Pakistani poet, Yousaf Jhelumi. The
Malaysian was knifed from behind for no apparent reason close to
Jhelumi's apartment in a northern Stockholm suburb.
   Jhelumi, 36, a Moslem, told Swedish television he received death
threats after announcing plans last month to translate ``The
Satanic Verses'' into his mother tongue, Urdu.
   Urdu is the chief language of Pakistan, where the book has been
banned and violently denounced.
   Jhelumi closed his small shop after receiving the threats and
has since moved from hotel to hotel, he said.
   ``I want to make it clear to Moslems in Pakistan and India that
nothing in the book goes against Islam,'' Jhelumi said. He was
interviewed in a hotel room at an unidentified location.
   He said he would only start translating the book if he got
police protection.
   Rushdie's book has been banned in many Moslem countries and the
Indian-born British author has been condemned to death by Iranian
leaders, who say ``The Satanic Verses'' blasphemes Islam.
   The book includes a brothel scene in which the prostitutes take
the names of Mohammed's wives, and it suggests Mohammed wrote the
holy Koran instead of receiving it from Allah.
   Jhelumi said he considered the book an attack ``against the
conservative mullahs who wanted to see the world as old-fashioned
as it was during the time of Mohammed.''
   ``The fanatics can wring my neck, but they can't wring
history,'' he said.
   Jhelumi said he has been denounced in Pakistan and his relatives
there have been threatened with being socially ostracized.
</TEXT>
