<FIRST>u w AM-Fruit-Cyanide     03-24 0440</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Fruit-Cyanide,440</SECOND>
<HEAD>More Fruit Cleared For Import</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH MESCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Food and Drug Administration on Friday
cleared the way for more Chilean fruit _ apples, peaches and plums
_ to be sold to U.S. markets after they are inspected for evidence
of cyanide poisoning.
   Import restrictions were lifted on pears and nectarines from
Chile on Tuesday, and on grapes and berries last Friday, allowing
the fruit to be released for sale after 5 percent of each shipment
is inspected and found free from cyanide.
   Grapes, which constitute 70 percent of the fruit Chile sends to
the United States, began appearing on produce shelves of U.S.
stores this week after a two-week absence due to the
cyanide-poisoning scare.
   More than 1 million cases of grapes and various types of berries
have been inspected at U.S. docks and airports and sent to
retailers since the hold on those fruits was lifted, the FDA said.
   Food graders should begin inspecting Chilean apples, peaches and
plums by the weekend, an FDA spokesman said.
   ``The public should be reassured that the government has kept
everyone informed and has moved promptly both to protect the public
health and to restore to the marketplace a healthy component of the
balanced diet that we recommend,'' said FDA Commissioner Frank
Young.
   Chile also exports melons to the United States at this time of
year, but FDA spokesman William Grigg said ``it is not clear
whether they will be returned to the (U.S.) market or not this
season.''
   Chilean fruit was removed from store shelves and unsold supplies
were held in warehouses, at ports, and on ships after the FDA found
traces of cyanide in two seedless red grapes. The FDA began looking
for evidence of cyanide tampering after two telephone calls to the
U.S. embassy in the Chilean capital of Santiago threatened to
inject the poison into fruit exports.
   An estimated $50 million to $75 million worth of Chilean fruit
that could not be readily inspected had to be destroyed. Meanwhile,
the FDA conducted tests on the different fruits to identify the
detectable damage caused by cyanide injections, so inspectors would
know what to look for.
   Evidence of cyanide poisoning includes discoloration and
deterioration of the fruit, the FDA said, and the agency advised
consumers to examine fruit as a precaution, including the area at
the stem, for discolorations and punctures.
   Inspectors have found no further cyanide contamination in any of
the fruit from Chile, despite a third telephone threat that was
received last Friday, shortly before the FDA announced its
stepped-up inspection plan to return Chilean fruit to U.S. stores.
</TEXT>
