<FIRST>r i AM-Soviet-Hungary 1stLd-Writethru   03-24 0487</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Hungary, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0556,0500</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hungarian Leader Says No Disagreements with Gorbachev</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 8th graf: `The Soviet...' and 11th graf: `Asked about...'
to fix typos.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARK J. PORUBCANSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hungarian Communist Party leader Karoly Grosz said
Friday he and President Mikhail S. Gorbachev reached complete
agreement in talks on Hungary's drive for a multiparty system and
increasing calls for neutrality.
   ``There were no issues in our three-hour discussion where we had
differences in our views,'' Grosz told a Moscow news conference.
   Reforms began earlier in Hungary than in the Soviet Union and
have progressed further, making it both a laboratory for economic
and social experiments in the East bloc and a source of worry for
Moscow over whether Budapest is going too far.
   Grosz arrived Thursday on his first visit to Moscow since
Hungarian party leaders last month declared their support for a
multiparty system.
   Grosz said he explained the decision to Gorbachev, and added,
``This is strictly up to the Hungarian people and the Hungarian
leadership.''
   ``It is natural that the political structure of a country
develop in its own particular way,'' he said.
   Grosz said that neither a one-party system, prevalent in Eastern
Europe, nor a multiparty system either ensures or precludes
democracy.
   The Soviet Union, where the Communist Party remains intolerant
of any challenge, is seeking to implement reforms based on its own
history, Grosz said.
   Hungarian Premier Miklos Nemeth said after visiting Moscow early
this month that Gorbachev approved Hungary's reforms and does not
oppose introduction of a multiparty system there.
   Despite sanctioning competition, Grosz said he does not
anticipate becoming leader of an opposition party. The Hungarian
Communist Party, he said, ``is sure to win a leading role. I'm not
thinking of being an opposition leader, I'm thinking of being the
leader of the winning party.''
   Asked about growing demands in Hungary for neutrality, Grosz
said, ``We are continually working for elimination of the two
military blocs on the European continent. If that happens, there
will be no question about the neutrality of Hungary.''
   ``We met complete unanimity of views'' with Gorbachev, he said.
   The Hungarian news agency MTI said Gorbachev told Grosz that
present world circumstances do not give any Warsaw Pact members a
chance to be neutral.
   The two leaders also expressed their support for a continuing
re-evaluation of the Soviet invasion that crushed the Hungarian
uprising of 1956, Grosz said.
   In order for the two sides to form an accurate record,
historians on both sides must gain access to documents of the
period, he said. ``Gorbachev's support is necessary to ensure that
the historians who are looking into this matter get a look at
authentic documents,'' Grosz said.
   The Tass new agency said the focus of the meeting was an
``exchange of expertise and information about pressing issues of
socialist construction in both countries and the development of
cooperation in all areas.''
</TEXT>
