<DOCNO> AP890324-0172 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-24-89 2012EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-NOW-Abortion     03-24 0378</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-NOW-Abortion,0389</SECOND>
<HEAD>NOW Charges Censorship in Ad Refusal by Radio Stations</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Abortion Protests</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RONALD POWERS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The National Organization for Women said Friday
its message favoring abortion rights was refused by more than two
dozen radio stations in five northeastern cities.
   ``It never occurred to us that we wouldn't be able to place paid
ads on a subject that's on everyone's lips. It is the issue of the
day in terms of women's rights,'' Molly Yard, the president of NOW,
said at a news conference.
   NOW budgeted about $40,000 to place the 60-second spot on 35
stations in Boston, New York, Philadelphia, Baltimore and
Washington. Eight stations agreed to carry the spot and 26
declined; one station had not decided, Ms. Yard said.
   The spot was aimed at promoting an April 9 march in Washington
supporting the right to abortion. Ms. Yard said organizers expected
as many as 250,000 people to attend.
   NOW's advertisement was produced to sound like a newscast, with
an announcer setting a scene, followed by clips of President Bush
and Vice President Daniel Quayle voicing their opposition to
abortion.
   In the ad, actress Susan Sarandon concludes with the warning
that ``A woman's right to choose now hangs in the balance.''
   Ms. Yard said the radio stations had refused to run the
advertisement because of its controversial content.
   ``It's like the stupid decision that's made on condoms. They
won't talk about condoms, they won't show them on TV, and now
they're not going to talk about abortion,'' she said.
   However, executives at several radio stations that declined to
accept the advertising spot said they were bothered not by its
content but because of the format.
   ``We won't take anything if they're trying to simulate a
newscast. You can't fake a newscast,'' said Warren Maurer, general
manager of WINS-AM, an all-news station in New York.
   Jeff Messerman, national sales manager for WXKS-FM, a Boston
station playing contemporary hit music, said the station refused to
air the ad because of its newscast format and sound effects.
   ``It has exploding bombs, sirens, just things you don't want to
have on copy. We thought that this was a spot that was going to
cause people to tune out,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
