<FIRST>r a AM-BRF--PoliceLights     03-24 0181</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Police Lights,0184</SECOND>
<HEAD>Woman Raped After Stopping For Fake Police Lights</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WESTERLY, R.I. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A woman who pulled her car over when she
saw a blue light flashing behind her thought she was being stopped
by police, but instead was overpowered and raped by the driver of
an unmarked car, police said.
   Such blue lights cost $6.99 at auto supply stores, police said
this week. It is not illegal to buy them, although their use is
illegal, they said.
   The woman told police she was driving near the Connecticut
border Saturday night when a car behind her flashed its high beams,
then turned on a flashing blue light.
   When she stopped, a man in civilian clothes approached the car,
talked with her, then overpowered and handcuffed her before taking
her to an isolated stretch of road in Connecticut where she was
sexually assaulted, the victim told police.
   Eugene C. Texter III, 27, has been charged with kidnapping and
for violating the terms of his bail on a previous sexual assault
charge. Connecticut State Police were investigating the rape charge.
</TEXT>
