<FIRST>u a AM-MissingBoat 1stLd-Writethru   03-24 0372</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Missing Boat, 1st Ld - Writethru,0379</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fishing Boat Still Missing</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 5 grafs to UPDATE search suspended; picks up 5th
graf pvs: `About an ...; SUBS 8th graf pvs, to conform.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEAN McNAIR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NORFOLK, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Coast Guard suspended its search for a
52-foot sport fishing boat Friday night after almost 24 hours of
battling rough seas and poor visibility with no success, a
spokesman said.
   ``We haven't got any new information,'' Petty Officer 1st Class
Rick Woods said. ``As of about six o'clock, the units that are out
there will finish their search patterns and come back in.''
   Woods said the area had been thoroughly and unsuccessfully
searched by three Coast Guard cutters, two Navy ships and a Coast
Guard helicopter.
   He did not know whether the search would be resumed.
   The Coast Guard received a distress call Thursday night saying
the Blue Goose, with 10 people aboard, was sinking off the Virginia
coast.
   About an hour later, the boat radioed that it was taking on
water about five miles off Virginia Beach and that the occupants
had donned life jackets and were abandoning the vessel. The Coast
Guard advised the people to stay together but received no
acknowledgement of that transmission.
   Driving rain, 50-knot winds and seas of 6 to 8 feet were
reported about the time the distress call was received.
   An all-night search turned up no sign of the boat or its
passengers. Water temperatures were in the 40s, which could cause
hypothermia in anyone who was overboard, said Petty Officer 1st
Class Vernon Covington.
   The Coast Guard searched boat registrations in every East Coast
state and found no record of a vessel named the Blue Goose that
matches the description of the fishing vessel, Petty Officer 1st
Class Rick Barrett said.
   ``If it's not a documented vessel and all we have is the name,
it's hard for us to track down the information,'' he said.
   Coast Guard spokesmen said the distress call sounded legitimate
and they had no reason to believe the call was a hoax.
   ``We don't know that this is a hoax, but there have been hoaxes
before,'' said Petty Officer 2nd Class Steve Blando.
</TEXT>
