<FILEID>AP-NR-03-24-89 2027EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-Meningococcus     03-24 0447</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Meningococcus,0462</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sixth Death In Meningococcus Outbreak</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NICHOLAS K. GERANIOS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>YAKIMA, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Health officials said Friday they will
begin vaccinating up to 4,000 people after an infant became the
sixth person to die in an outbreak of meningococcal disease.
   Yakima County health officials also conferred with the federal
Centers for Disease Control in Atlanta on how to deal with about
400 participants from seven states at a basketball tournament
underway in nearby Wapato.
   Teams at the all-Indian tournament, which began Wednesday, are
from Kansas, Oregon, Washington, Idaho, Montana, California and
Oklahoma.
   Health officials want to ensure they do not carry the disease
back to their states. Options include quarantining participants,
vaccinating them, or sending them home with no treatment, said Dr.
Bob Atwood, county health director.
   Dr. Jay Wenger of CDC said a quarantine was unlikely because the
risk of participants contracting the disease is very low.
   It was a discouraging day for health officials, who on Wednesday
said they felt they were through the worst of the nation's largest
current outbreak of meningococcal disease.
   The meningococcus germ is carried in the nose and throat and
passed through sneezing and other secretions from the nose and
mouth. It is not considered highly contagious.
   In the Yakima outbreak, the germ is causing bacterial
meningitis, an inflammation of the lining of the brain and spinal
cord, and meningococcemia, in which it travels through the blood
stream and attacks organs.
   Adults who become infected usually do not become sick, but can
carry the disease to children. Symptoms are similar to the common
cold, and include fever, nausea, headache and a rash.
   An unidentified infant died Thursday in the latest case, making
it the 18th since Jan. 10. Of the six deaths, four were infants.
The state had only four deaths from meningococcal disease in all of
1988.
   ``This suggests there is a high rate of carriers in the
county,'' Atwood told an emergency meeting of the county health
board.
   That is troubling because the basketball tournament has drawn
large crowds, who have mingled with the out-of-town visitors,
making it impossible to do conventional contact-tracing techniques
to identify those most at risk of exposure, he said.
   As a result, health officials planned to vaccinate everyone
between ages 1 to 25 in the Wapato area on Friday and Saturday, a
total of about 4,000 people, Atwood said.
   The vaccine does not work on people under age 1 and people over
25 who are exposed rarely become ill, Atwood said.
   Most of the deaths in the outbreak have involved Hispanics or
Native Americans, and the common denominator is low-income families
living in crowded conditions, officials said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
