<FIRST>r i AM-Japan-US 1stLd-Writethru   03-24 0345</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-US, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0721,0352</SECOND>
<HEAD>Defense Chief Says FSX Talks Are `Tough'</HEAD>
<UNK>Eds: SUBS 4th graf: `President Bush...' to CORRECT to billion sted
million. Pickup 5th graf pvs: `Tazawa said,...'</UNK>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Japan's defense chief said Friday that a new round
of talks in Washington between Japanese and U.S. officials on the
FSX fighter project started with disagreement.
   ``The contents of the talks were very tough,'' Kichiro Tazawa,
director-general of the Defense Agency, said at a news conference.
   Agency Deputy Director Seiki Nishihiro and U.S. officials,
including Secretary of State James A. Baker III, met Thursday to
discuss the joint development of Japan's next generation jet
fighter plane.
   President Bush said this week he endorsed joint production of
the FSX fighter but with some changes to protect U.S. technology.
His decision followed criticism that the plan amounted to a
giveaway of up to $8 billion worth of American technology.
   Tazawa said, however, that Washington should stick to the terms
of the original agreement signed in November. Under the agreement,
Mitsubishi Heavy Industries Ltd., Japan's major defense contractor,
and U.S. aircraft maker General Dynamics Corp. would develop the
new fighter.
   Nishihiro, scheduled to remain in Washington until Sunday, will
continue to hold meetings with U.S. officials, Tazawa said.
   Japan originally planned to develop the fighter independently
but negotiated a joint development agreement after Washington put
pressure on Tokyo to buy U.S.-built planes.
   American critics, however, have warned that U.S. technology for
the plane could help Japan compete against American companies in
the manufacture of civilian aircraft, a high-technology field in
which Japan now lags but has targeted for development.
   Under the development agreement, reached after several years of
negotiations, Mitsubishi would be responsible for developing the
new fighter by using technology developed domestically and from the
F-16, developed by the St. Louis-based General Dynamics.
   General Dynamics would receive 35 percent to 40 percent of the
contract in the developmental stage.
   Initially, 130 planes would be built, with a possible follow-up
order for about 100 more. Each FSX would cost about $40 million,
Japanese officials say.
</TEXT>
