<FIRST>r a AM-HaitiansIntercepted 1stLd-Writethru a0605 03-24 0346</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Haitians Intercepted, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0605,0353</SECOND>
<HEAD>Haitians Intercepted Just Outside U.S. Territorial Water</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: ADDS 7 grafs to UPDATE with two Haitians taken to hospital,
reax from Haitian community and INS, cutter dispatched to escort refugees
home.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 50-foot boat carrying about 100 Haitians was
intercepted Friday just outside U.S. territorial waters, and the
refugees will be returned to their homeland, the Coast Guard
reported.
   Officers determined that the Haitians' wooden sailboat was
intercepted 3.2 miles from shore, just outside the 3-mile limit,
said Petty Officer Luis Diaz.
   ``Real close,'' Diaz said. ``They did two readings and confirmed
that is the correct position _ perhaps they were just a breath away
from making it into the three miles.''
   If the Haitians had been inside the limit, they would have been
brought ashore for detention and processing, and their claims for
asylum would have been considered by Immigration and Naturalization
Service workers.
   Diaz said the Haitians were spotted early Friday by the crew of
a tanker about three miles east of Fort Lauderdale.
   Medical personnel were sent to the sailboat as a precaution and
the unsuccessful immigrants also were given water, Diaz said. Two
of the would-be immigrants were taken to Memorial Hospital in
Hollywood.
   ``They're suffering from exposure and dehydrated,'' hospital
spokeswoman Linda Hamlin said late Friday afternoon, adding it was
too soon to say if they would be admitted.
   A Coast Guard cutter was dispatched to return the Haitians to
their homeland.
   Leaders of Miami's Haitian community, meanwhile, attacked what
they call a racist immigration policy. While Cubans and Nicaraguans
are received with open arms, they say, Haitians aren't even allowed
into the country.
   ``It's clear they're playing games with the black refugees,''
said Gerard Jean-Juste, director of Miami's Haitian Refugee Center.
``We would like to see something done about it.''
   An INS official denied there was any discrimination in the
interdiction policy.
   ``It's just that more Haitians are coming in boats than any
other ethnic group,'' said INS district director Perry Rivkind.
``There's nothing really one can do.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
