<FIRST>r a AM-TeacherShot     03-24 0451</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Teacher Shot,0468</SECOND>
<HEAD>High-School Teacher Killed in Early-Morning Ambush</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A popular high school teacher and class
adviser was killed Friday by a gunman with a semiautomatic weapon
who shot him three times in the back as he left for school, police
said.
   Detectives sought a student recently expelled from Grant High
School in suburban Van Nuys, but didn't consider him a suspect and
weren't sure if the victim played a role in his expulsion, said
police Lt. Warren Knowles.
   Harold ``Hal'' Arthur, 60, a social studies teacher and senior
class adviser at the school for 20 years, was shot as he put some
papers in the back seat of his car about 6 a.m., Knowles said.
   The killer, who fired six shots from a .22-caliber semiautomatic
gun, apparently was either standing in the street or sitting in a
car in front of Arthur's home in the San Fernando Valley suburb of
Sherman Oaks, the lieutenant said at an afternoon news conference.
   The teacher's wife, Virginia, and one of his two sons ran
outside to find him on the ground, and he was pronounced dead a
short time later at Sherman Oaks Community Hospital.
   Neighbor Hal Gelman, a screenwriter, said he heard the shooting.
   ``I heard this sound like `bap, bap, bap _ like an AK or an
Uzi,'' said neighbor Hal Gelman, referring to an AK-47 and another,
Israeli-made semiautomatic weapon. California legislators have
moved to ban the sales of such weapons since five children were
killed by a gunman in a Stockton schoolyard in January.
   Robbery was tentatively ruled out as a motive.
   ``He simply walked out, started to get into his car and was shot
from behind,'' Knowles said. ``No one approached him to take
anything from him.''
   A 16- or 17-year-old boy who had been expelled from Grant was
being sought at his home and at his new school, North Hollywood
High, where he hasn't been seen since Tuesday.
   ``Some of the students we talked to indicated it would be worth
our while to talk to him. They said he had a grudge against
(Arthur),'' Knowles said.
   Police did not specify whether Arthur had anything to do with
the boy's expulsion.
   As senior class adviser, Arthur helped students with social
activities and was well-liked, said Shel Erlich, spokesman for the
Los Angeles Unified School District.
   Counselors from the district's mental health crisis team rushed
to the school to help calm students, the spokesman said.
   ``Everybody seems to be down,'' Erlich said. ``Some students are
handling it better than others.''
   Gelman, Arthur's neighbor, said the victim used to throw
semester-end parties for students.
   ``Mobs of kids would come,'' Gelman recalled. ``He was very
popular.''
</TEXT>
