<FILEID>AP-NR-03-24-89 2357EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-TwoForks-Reax     03-24 0429</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Two Forks-Reax,0443</SECOND>
<HEAD>Two Forks Decision Provokes Dismay, Praise, Questions</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Two Forks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CARL HILLIARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal order Friday that could sink a $500
million proposed dam and reservoir drew angry charges of
interference from some Colorado officials, but environmentalists
praised it as wise and courageous.
   Denver Mayor Federico Pena and other members of the Denver Water
Board, themain sponsors of the Two Forks Dam, were dismayed after
hearing of the decision by Environmental Protection Agency
Administrator William K. Reilly.
   ``We feel Mr. Reilly has interjected himself in this process
outside the purview of the EPA's own regulations,'' said Denver
Water Board President Monte Pascoe.
   Pascoe said the project ``addressed environmental and other
concerns and has emerged far and away as the biggest long-term
water supply plan for the Denver metropolitan area.''
   The eight-year-old project on the South Platte River southwest
of Denver has been the center of a bitter fight between
environmentalists and Denver area officials who say the region
needs the dam for its future water needs.
   Reilly began procedures tantamount to overruling a construction
permit issued earlier this month by the Corps of Engineers, which
could lead to a veto of the project if compromises are not worked
out.
   Gov. Roy Romer called Reilly's position a ``basic disagreement
between federal agencies about how the decision should be made.''
   ``That disagreement is fertile ground for delay and
indecision,'' the governor said. He said he would prefer to see a
permit for Two Forks issued with ``a 25-year shelf life,'' and
added he would be willing to take action to compensate for damage
to the environment and wildlife.
   Pena said ``the impact of a final rejection of Two Forks, in my
opinion, will have stronger environmental consequences. That is the
message not communicated to the EPA office.''
   U.S. Sen. Tim Wirth and environmentalist organizations, however,
praised Reilly's action.
   ``I think we should view EPA's decision as a commitment by the
Bush administration to conserving one of America's most beautiful
canyons and conserving water resources,'' Wirth said.
   ``But today's decision does not mean that we should stop looking
for ways to provide more water for metropolitan Denver,'' he added.
   Dr. Jay D. Hair, president of the National Wildlife Federation,
headquartered in Washington, D.C., said, ``I commend (the) EPA
administrator for a courageous position. ... It is economically a
bad project and environmentally, it's been a disaster.''
   Audubon Society President Peter A. Berle said the decision was
the first major environmental test for President Bush and he passed
it ``with flying colors.''
</TEXT>
