<FIRST>r a AM-Campbell-Execution     03-24 0271</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Campbell-Execution,0277</SECOND>
<HEAD>High Court Declines to Stay Execution for Triple Slayer</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN WHITE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>OLYMPIA, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The state Supreme Court on Thursday
rejected a triple murderer's plea for a stay of his execution by
injection or hanging.
   The high court said the motion for a stay, based mostly on
Charles Rodman Campbell's absence during jury selection for his 1982
murder trial, was not worthy of further consideration.
   Campbell attorney Robert Gombiner conceded that Campbell had
signed a waiver of his right be present at jury selection, but
argued that ``by court rule a defendant in a capital case can never
waive his right to be present at jury selection.''
   Campbell is scheduled to die at 12:01 a.m. next Thursday for the
1982 knife slayings of Renae Wicklund, 31, her 8-year-old daughter
Shannah and Barbara Hendrickson, 51.
   In a neatly printed brief submitted to the court Wednesday,
Campbell also asserted that ``death by hanging is so psychologically
distressing and frightening to petitioner that the fear of being
hung will force petitioner to violate his religious beliefs against
killing and suicide, ... forcing petitioner to actively take part in
his own demise in order to escape death by hanging.''
   Campbell's lead lawyer Al Lyon said late Thursday he will seek a
stay of execution from U.S. District Court in Seattle within the
next few days, seeking a stay of execution.
   At the time of the murders, Campbell was living at a work release
center, serving a sentence for assault and sodomy. Ms. Wicklund was
the victim in those crimes and testified against Campbell at the
earlier trial.
</TEXT>
