<FIRST>r i AM-Japan-Korea     03-24 0287</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-Korea,0294</SECOND>
<HEAD>Japanese Reported Seized In South Korea In Business Dispute</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A South Korean company has seized a Japanese
machinery company president for the second time in four months in a
business dispute, and his whereabouts are unknown, his company said
Thursday.
   Koji Kohno of the Japanese company Osawa Press Seisakusho said
the firm has received 12 telephone facsimile messages from Namil
Machine Co. in South Korea requesting $3.8 million.
   He said recent messages declared that Osawa Press president Tokuo
Osawa had been beaten, and that one of his fingers would be cut off
and sent to back up demands for payment. The messages also
threatened Osawa's family, Kohno said.
   Japan has asked South Korean authorities to cooperate in the
case, Foreign Ministry spokesman Taizo Watanabe said.
   While it was up to the two companies to settle their business
dispute, he said, ``this kind of illegal action should not accompany
a solution of the case.''
   Osawa Press exported six press machines to Namil last year for
about $837,000, and Osawa went to South Korea in December to offer
technial assistance after Namil complained that the machines were
defective, Kohno said.
   He said Osawa was confined in Namil's villa on Dec. 24 for three
to four days until Korean police and Japanese Embassy staff helped
win his release. Kohno said another Osawa Press employee and the
president of a Japanese trading company also were held three days in
the villa.
   Meanwhile, he said, Namil filed a complaint accusing Osawa of
fraud, and he was not allowed to leave the country. After he had
stayed two months in a hotel, Namil seized him again on Feb. 20 and
his whereabouts now are unknown, Kohno said.
</TEXT>
