<FIRST>r w AM-Bush-Manufacturers 2ndLd-Writethru a0667 03-24 0464</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush-Manufacturers, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0667,470</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Praises Manufacturers, Open Trade</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Adds 2 graf with Bush-dinner</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush told U.S. manufacturers Thursday
he would work to keep international trade open but ``will not
confuse involvement with interference.''
   Speaking to a National Association of Manufacturers luncheon,
Bush praised industry's recent gains in productivity and exporting.
``Nobody is second-guessing American manufacturing any more. Clearly
you all are playing a winning game,'' he said.
   Bush was applauded vigorously when he said he would ``keep on
fighting'' for his proposal to reduce the capital-gains tax rate to
a maximum of 15 percent, about half the current top rate.
   The proposal, part of his fiscal 1990 budget package, has been
cooly received by the Democratic-controlled Congress.
   The president contends that lowering the tax on capital gains _
proceeds from the sale of stock, homes, buildings, real-estate and
other assets _ would spur new business investment and bring as much
as $4.8 billion in new tax revenue to the government for 1990.
   ``This is a case where less means more,'' Bush said.
   He said a lower capital-gains rate would enhance U.S.
competitiveness abroad.
   Bush told the manufacturers, ``Your presence here today
demonstrates that you are fighting to win the international struggle
for continued growth.''
   ``I'm not saying you're going to have to do it alone,'' he added.
``There is a role for government. Sometimes political leadership is
needed _ for example to keep international trade free and fair.
However, I will tell you that this government will not confuse
involvement with interference.''
   Bush sounded again the anti-drug theme he has been stressing in
recent speeches, saying drug and alchohol abuse are cutting into
business productivity.
   ``We're determined to keep drugs out of the workplace,'' Bush
said. He praised a recent Supreme Court ruling on drug-testing,
saying it would give his administration's anti-drug efforts ``a much
better chance of success.''
   The court on Tuesday upheld the constitutionality of drug testing
programs for law enforcement and public safety workers.
   ``Employers can teach their people to recognize the signs of
substance abuse in their co-workers _ and understand how drug abuse
hurts the non-users on the line,'' Bush said.
   Later in the day, the president went for a two-mile jog under
chilly, gray skies at Fort McNair, inviting two reporters and
Republican National Committee Chairman Lee Atwater to join him and a
few aides for the 20-minute run.
   Still later, Bush and his wife Barbara went by motorcade to a
Chinese restaurant in nearby Falls Church, Va., where they dined
with press secretary Marlin Fitzwater and White House photographer
Carol Powers, Fitzwater's finance.
   After the meal, Bush walked around the restaurant shaking hands
with other diners and the entire restaurant erupted in applause.
</TEXT>
