<FIRST>r a AM-Vincennes-Bomb     03-24 0431</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Vincennes-Bomb,0442</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rogers to Give Up Command in Routine Change, Navy Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN DIEGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Navy Capt. Will Rogers III will give up command
of the USS Vincennes in May, a change the Navy called routine and
unrelated to the possible terrorist bombing of a van driven by
Rogers' wife.
   ``This has been in the works for a long time,'' Navy spokesman
Cmdr. David Dillon said Thursday. Rogers became captain of the
guided missile cruiser in April 1987, and a command usually runs
about two years, Dillon said.
   The FBI is investigating whether the March 10 bombing of Sharon
Rogers' van was in retaliation for the Vincennes' mistaken
destruction of an Iranian jetliner in the Persian Gulf last July.
All 290 aboard the plane were killed.
   Mrs. Rogers has been in protected seclusion since the attack,
which left her uninjured. Rogers was in command when the Vincennes
left last week on a training mission off Southern California.
   The new commander of the Vincennes will be Capt. R.B. Lynch,
Dillon said. He said he didn't know what Rogers' next duty
assignment would be.
   However, The (San Diego) Tribune, citing an unidentified Navy
source, said Rogers would take command of a shore installation in
the Point Loma area of San Diego. Rogers is eligibile for promotion
to rear admiral, the source said.
   Meanwhile, it was reported that Mrs. Rogers, who lost her
teaching job at La Jolla Country Day school after the bombing, has
written parents of her former pupils to say she wasn't a security
risk.
   Officials at La Jolla Country Day School announced last week that
she was leaving her teaching job by mutual consent to ensure the
safety of the school's students.
   However, Mrs. Rogers, who says she was fired by the school,
stated in her letter that an in-depth investigation by federal
officials found that ``no evidence exists of a direct or implied
threat against me or the school,'' the Los Angeles Times and the
Tribune reported Thursday.
   That finding, Mrs. Rogers wrote, left her ``prepared to resume a
full classroom schedule'' until administrators notified her last
Thursday ``that my services had been terminated.''
   One school official told the Times that Mrs. Rogers was not
allowed to return to her fourth-grade classroom partly because
administrators feared parents would pull their children out of the
exclusive private school if she remained on the faculty.
   School spokesman Jim Stewart again maintained that Mrs. Rogers
was not fired. ``We're just not renewing her contract,'' he said
Wednesday. ``No matter what kind of furor she expresses, she's not
coming back. Period.''
</TEXT>
