<FIRST>r a AM-BRF--SRPBonus     03-24 0163</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--SRP Bonus,0166</SECOND>
<HEAD>DOE Offers $6.25 Million Bonus For Reactor Restart</HEAD>
<DATELINE>AUGUSTA, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government is offering the new operator
of the Savannah River Plant a bonus of up to $6.25 million for
efficiently restarting the reactors at the nuclear weapons material
plant.
   Westinghouse Savannah River Co., which will assume control of the
Department of Energy plant from Du Pont on April 1, is assured of a
fee of $1.25 million for its first six months.
   The federal government will add a bonus based on a formula which
includes a safe restart, efficient production and safety
improvements, the Augusta Herald reported.
   The plant, in South Carolina across the Savannah River from
Augusta, has been shut down since last summer because of safety
concerns.
   Du Pont operated the plant under a non-profit arrangement. The
company, which gained nuclear expertise at the plant, was reimbursed
for its expenses and will receive a ``profit'' of $1 when it
relinquishes the contract April 1.
