<FIRST>r a AM-GrocerKilled     03-24 0432</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Grocer Killed,0448</SECOND>
<HEAD>Police Recall That Anti-Drug Meeting Preceded Shooting of Crusading
Grocer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grocer Lee Arthur Lawrence's longtime battle against
drug trafficking in his neighborhood provoked vandalism against his
business and home, physical attacks, and finally, authorities
suspect, his slaying.
   Homicide detectives have been working round-the-clock since
Lawrence of West Perrine was killed Monday in a spray of up to 30
bullets in front of his grocery store, Lee's Grocery.
   ``He was a fine man,'' said Sandra Alvarez, a staff member of
Perrine's Community Action Agency, which had Lawrence on its board.
   ``The lack of his leadership will be felt for a long time,'' she
said. ``The entire community is in a state of shock.''
   Late last week, three days before the Monday killing, Metro-Dade
Police Director Fred Taylor met with Lawrence, ministers and other
concerned citizens to discuss how to squelch the rampant drug
problem in West Perrine, south of Miami.
   ``You don't know how bad I feel,'' Taylor said Wednesday. ``They
were going to assist us by identifying some of the individuals. We
just can't live in this kind of society.''
   Detectives Thursday were still looking for two men in their
mid-20s, but had made no arrests. They have yet to establish a
motive, but they believe Lawrence was slain by professional killers.
   His family and neighbors, however, said they think the murder was
arranged by drug dealers.
   Last week, Lawrence filed a complaint with police about a death
threat. A friend had told Lawrence that a drug dealer was
threatening to kill him.
   Taylor said a detective was investigating the threat, and
officers were told to patrol the store.
   ``We can't assign a policeman around the clock to stay with
somebody unless we have some specifics,'' Taylor said. ``I don't
know what we could have done.''
   Lawrence, 51, was widely known in the neighborhood for his
anti-drug stance, visiting schools and organizing residents to fight
against dealers.
   Two years ago, shots were fired into his home and homemade bombs
were tossed into his store. He also was the target of two attacks in
which gunmen fired on him as he entered his house.
   No one was arrested, but police say they suspected drug dealers.
   The night Lawrence died, two men in military camouflage clothes
were lurking around Lee's Grocery, said King Lewis, a witness in the
parking lot.
   Lawrence's daughter, Nita, said her father cooperated with
police, letting them know about suspicious activity, and she talked
of how he stood up to the area's drug dealers.
   ``He let them know they weren't welcome,'' she said.
</TEXT>
