<SECOND>AM-Hostage Anniversary,0250</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.N. Group Marks Anniversary Of British Journalist's Abduction</HEAD>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The wife of kidnapped British journalist
Alec Collett, U.N. officials and fellow journalists appealed
Thursday for information about the hostage on the fourth anniversary
of his abduction in Lebanon.
   A radical Moslem group has claimed that Collett was hanged in
April 1986 in retaliation for the U.S. bombing raid on Libya, and
released a videotape purportedly showing his body hanging from a
scaffold. His body was never found.
   Collett was abducted on March 25, 1985, while on assignment with
the U.N. Relief and Works Agency for Palestinian refugees. A group
linked to Palestinian terrorists claimed responsibility for his
abduction.
   ``We are heading into our fifth year,'' Collett's wife, Elaine,
said Thursday during a service held by the U.N. Correspondents'
Association. ``It must be several lifetimes for Alec. There seems to
be a lack of urgency concerning his whereabouts.
   ``Have any of his fellow journalists let him down? Search your
hearts for solutions to get Alec and his fellow hostages home.''
   U.N. Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar said in a
statement that he and his senior staff were pursuing every
opportunity to obtain information about Collett.
   Walid Mourani, president of the U.N. Correspondents Association,
said his group was doing the same.
   Fifteen foreigners, including nine Americans, are missing in
Lebanon. The longest held is Terry Anderson, chief Middle East
correspondent of The Associated Press, who was kidnapped on March
16, 1985.
