<FIRST>r a AM-LennonFilm     03-24 0577</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lennon Film,0593</SECOND>
<HEAD>Film By Former Beatle To Be Shown In Two Michigan Theaters</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Crisler is cq in 3rd graf</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEOFFREY HAYNES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A film produced by former Beatle John Lennon is
making its debut nearly two decades after it captured Ann Arbor's
counter-culture during a huge 1971 rally to support a jailed
activist.
   Screenings of the film ``Ten for Two,'' have been held up by
Lennon's own reluctance to release it during his lifetime and by
uncertainty over who owns the rights.
   The movie documents a benefit concert held at the University of
Michigan's Crisler Arena for John Sinclair, a radical activist who
was serving a 10-year prison sentence for possession of two
marijuana cigarettes. He was released shortly after the December
1971 concert, having served 2{ years.
   Lennon, who faced his own problems with drug charges in the
United States, apparently was unwilling to release the film that
features radical speakers, folk protest songwriters and fellow rock
musicians such as Stevie Wonder and Bob Seger.
   ``This film was not released because of John Lennon's immigration
problems,'' the film's director, Steve Gephardt, said. ``The
immigration people said if you let this out, (Lennon) might as well
book a boat home.''
   Ownership rights of the film, which runs about 80 minutes, still
haven't been settled, but it will be shown anyway April 1 in Royal
Oak, a Detroit suburb, and April 2 in Ann Arbor.
   ``I don't think there's anything in writing anywhere'' about the
rights, said David Clements of MediaVision, a non-profit film
company based in Hazel Park that's putting on the two showings. He
said there are no current plans for other showings.
   The film apparently has been seen only rarely, at a handful of
private parties and a brief showing in England.
   Lennon and his wife, Yoko Ono, perform three songs in the film,
including one composition Lennon dedicated to Sinclair and one song
Ono said she wrote ``for the women of Ann Arbor.'' Lennon played an
acoustic guitar and Ono played a drum.
   Others appearing in the film are radicals Bobby Seale and Jerry
Rubin, as well as Wonder, Seger, folksinger Phil Ochs and the rock
group Commander Cody and His Lost Planet Airmen.
   Clements said Ono has not responded to queries about the film.
``This is one of the ways to see if she'll cooperate positively to
get it (the film) into public hands,'' Clements said.
   Sinclair, who now edits the Detroit Council of Art's ``City Arts
Quarterly,'' said after seeing the film Wednesday that it depressed
him.
   ``The people you see in this movie are responsible for all the
changes we had during the 1960s and '70s,'' he said.
   Lennon died in 1980, shot to death near his New York City home by
a deranged admirer.
   At the time of Sinclair's arrest, possession of marijuana was a
felony, punishable by up to 10 years in prison. He was arrested at
age 25 in Detroit while living as a poet and revolutionary who
founded the White Panthers. He received the maximum sentence.
   Lobbying efforts to free Sinclair eventually paid off, even
before the concert was held. The day before the concert, the
Michigan Legislature voted to reduce the penalty for possession of
small amounts of marijuana to a misdemeanor, punishable by up to a
year in prison.
   Because he already had served 2{ years, Sinclair was released
from prison three days after the concert.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890324-0198 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-24-89 0155EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-Minister-Cartel     03-24 0550</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Minister-Cartel,0567</SECOND>
<HEAD>Colombian Justice Minister: Drugs Only one of Many Crises</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SANDRA WALEWSKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Colombia's justice minister on Thursday shrugged off
U.S. charges against leaders of the infamous Medellin Cartel, saying
the country faced a much bigger crisis than pursuing reputed cocaine
kingpins.
   ``For the American government, drug trafficking is the biggest
problem,'' said Guillermo Plazas Alcid. ``For us, it is one of many,
including terrorism and subversion.''
   Thirty people, including reputed cartel leaders, were indicted in
Jacksonville on Wednesday, accused of smuggling $1 billion in
cocaine into the United State through the Bahamas and other points.
   Plazas, who had no visible security guards, told a luncheon
gathering of 130 members of the Colombian American Chamber of
Commerce that the South American nation was doing its best to
confront the drug issue, but extraditing cartel leaders for
prosecution in the United States was not an option.
   The extradition treaty between the two countries was invalidated
by Colombia's supreme court after the capture of cartel co-leader
Carlos Lehder Rivas, convicted last year and sentenced to life in
prison for cocaine trafficking to the United States.
   Since then, the extradition issue has been on hold. Asked what
effect Wednesday's sweeping drug-trafficking indictment might have,
Plazas simply replied, ``the extradition treaty can't be applied.''
   Among those indicted was Pablo Escobar Gaviria, an alleged leader
of the cartel accused of plotting the assassination of Colombian
Justice Minister Rodrigo Lara Bonilla in 1984 and the 1986 slaying
of drug informant Barry Seal.
   Plazas discussed for nearly an hour the reform and strengthening
of Colombia's judicial system in response to drug trafficking,
guerrilla activity, common delinquency and the weakening of the
public and private sectors.
   ``If we are not at the edge of the abyss, then we're getting to
the point of almost no return,'' Plazas said. ``This is like a
gigantic nuclear mushroom cloud penetrating the whole society.''
   Plazas said Colombia, as a producing nation, should not bear sole
reponsibility for the drug problem and insisted it was a worldwide
issue that needed to be addressed on that scale.
   ``Colombia is not responsible for drug trafficking _ it is a
victim,'' he said. ``We are all victims.''
   He referred to the United State's swift reaction to tainted
Chilean fruit, saying this country had the power to respond with
equal vigor to drug trafficking.
   U.S. prosecutors said they were confident many of the 30
defendants named in the Jacksonville indictment would eventually
face prosecution. In addition to Escobar, the indictment _ charging
bribery, murder and conspiracy to import 44,000 pounds of cocaine _
named alleged cartel leaders Jose Rodriguez Gacha, Gonzalo Mejia and
brothers Jorge and Fabio Ochoa Vasquez.
   Also indicted was Everette Bannister, an associate of Bahamian
Prime Minister Lynden O. Pindling, who was charged with receiving
bribes to protect cartel smuggling operations in the island nation.
   The Bahamian government Thursday issued a statement strongly
denying Pindling was in any way linked to drug traffickers.
   ``The legal difficulties (of) ... Bannister, a private Bahamian
citizen, have nothing to do with the government of the Bahamas, its
institutions or its people,'' said Margaret McDonald, the Bahamian
ambassador to the United States.
   Others indicted in the Jacksonville case were alleged pilots,
managers of cocaine operations and distributors of the drug.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890324-0199 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-24-89 0158EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-SpottedOwl-Ruling     03-24 0416</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Spotted Owl-Ruling,0427</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judge Extends Ban on Timber Sales for Spotted Owl Pending Trial</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TIM KLASS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal court extended a ban Thursday on U.S.
Forest Service plans to sell nearly 1 billion board feet of ancient
timber from nine national forests in two states where the northern
spotted owl lives.
   Environmentalists hailed the ruling, but a timber industry lawyer
said it could mean the loss of 11,000 to 14,000 jobs in Washington
and Oregon.
   U.S. District Court Judge William S. Dwyer also set a trial for
June 13 on challenges by the Sierra Club Legal Defense Fund and the
Washington Contract Loggers Association to the agency's spotted owl
management plans.
   Wildlife biologists are still trying to determine whether the
owl, which is believed to inhabit only ancient forests, is really
threatened with extinction.
   Roughly 2,400 owls are thought to inhabit the woods of the
Northwest.
   ``It's obvious that once the habitat is destroyed, it cannot be
replaced in any time frame that our generation can deal with,''
Dwyer said. ``That, of course, demonstrates a form of irreparable
harm.''
   If timber interests prevail at trial, ``the trees in question
have been growing for hundreds of years, and they will still be
available for logging,'' he added.
   But he said the prospects that the environmentalists would
prevail were ``sufficiently strong'' to justify a preliminary
injunction, in effect extending by 60 days a temporary restraining
order he issued Friday.
   ``Today's injunction is not just a victory for the ancient
forest-dependent spotted owl but is also important to the increasing
number of people in the recreation, tourism, retirement and fishing
industries whose future livelihood is tied in large part to the
ancient forests' protection,'' said Wendell Wood of the Oregon
Natural Resources Council.
   Mark Rutzick, a lawyer for the loggers, said the 60-day
injunction against sales would mean a one-year delay in actually
logging the more than 18,000 affected acres of spotted owl habitat,
roughly 29 square miles.
   The more than 900,000 board feet of timber to be logged from
those areas amounted to a one-year supply of logs for 20 to 30
mills, Rutzick said.
   Rutzick said that, because of the ruling, ``I think it is very
possible that 20 domestic sawmills in Washington and Oregon ... will
close within the next 12 months.''
   He said that would idle 3,000 to to 4,000 mill workers and 8,000
to 10,000 others in timber-dependent work ranging from shopkeepers
to gasoline station attendants.
</TEXT>
