<FIRST>r i AM-SatanicVerses     03-24 0321</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Satanic Verses,0328</SECOND>
<HEAD>Minister Confident Death Sentence Will Be Carried Out</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iran's interior minister on Thursday
assured Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini that ``the children of Islam''
will implement his decree and kill British writer Salman Rushdie.
   Ali Akbar Mohtashemi, a radical and staunch follower of Khomeini,
spoke at a gathering at Khomeini's residence in the northern Tehran
suburb of Jamaran to mark the birthday of Imam Mahdi _ the so-called
``Hidden Imam'' who Shiite Moslems believe will return as an Islamic
messiah.
   The speech was broadcast on official Tehran Radio, monitored in
Nicosia.
   During the speech, crowds in the background could be heard
chanting: ``You are our soul Khomeini, you are the idol smasher
Khomeini,'' and slogans condemning the United States and Israel.
   Last month Khomeini urged Moslems in a fatwa, or religious edict,
to kill Rushdie for allegedly blaspheming Islam in his novel ``The
Satanic Verses.'' The novel includes a brothel scene in which
prostitutes take the name of Mohammed's wives and suggests that
Mohammed wrote the Koran instead of receiving it from God.
   The 41-year-old author has been in hiding since Khomeini's death
threat Feb. 14.
   ``The oppressors and global arrogance must know that the children
of Islam will carry out the sentence against those who have risen to
battle against Islam, and this mercenary agent will see the
consequences of his deed, and the execution order will be carried
out at the hands of the children of Islam,'' Mohtashemi said.
   Britain and its 11 partners in the Economic Community withdrew
their ambassadors from Tehran to protest Khomeini's death sentence.
Iran later severed relations with Britain, accusing Prime Minister
Margaret Thatcher of conspiring against Islam.
   EEC nations agreed this week to allow each country to decide on
its own if it wanted to send its ambassador back to Iran. Britain,
however, said it will not restore relations with Iran until Khomeini
revokes the death sentence.
</TEXT>
