<DOCNO> AP890324-0203 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-24-89 1331EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a w AM-EmbassyVisaSiege Adv27   03-24 0795</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Embassy Visa Siege, Adv 27,0818</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv27</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Mon AMs March 27 and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Coming to America: Global Tempest Touched Off by Visa Lottery</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: This is being repeated for all needing.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUSANNE M. SCHAFER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   From Senegal to Sicily and Morocco to Malaysia,
throngs of agitated people have besieged U.S. embassies and
consulates in recent weeks _ not in anger, but in eagerness.
   People anxious to gain information about a new program that will
grant 20,000 immigrant visas into the United States in 1991 and 1992
have kept embassy telephones ringing off the hook and snarled
embassy entry ways.
   _ In Cairo, the embassy was forced to shut down its entire
complex and call the local police recently to deal with a crowd of
2,000 people demanding details.
   _ In Bucharest, Romania, people began forming lines at 6 a.m.,
and police finally organized the crowds into groups of 20 persons
for entry into the embassy.
   The rush was touched off late last month when the State
Department announced that citizens from 162 countries will be
eligible for the special visa lottery. Some 20,000 entrants will be
chosen at random by computer, and applicants only have until Friday
to apply.
   Normally, immigrants have to prove they have a close relative in
the United States or a scarce profession in order to enter the
country, said Frances Jones, an official with the State Department's
Consular Affairs office.
   The enthusiastic response is understandable, she says, because
``suddenly, there's an opportunity for anyone to come'' to the
United States _ but only if they meet the other basic requirements
as well, such as good health and no criminal contacts.
   The last lottery, a more restrictive program in 1986, brought
10,000 people into the country; 1.4 million applicants lost out.
   Rep. Howard L. Berman, D-Calif., the prime sponsor of the law
that established the program, said it was designed to ``encourage
diversity'' in the nation's immigration program ``and to give
opportunity to those who have no family contacts to come to
America.''
   ``Immigration is good for America. It is a tremendous source of
economic innovation and growth,'' Berman said.
   It appears there will be no problem attracting applicants. Within
hours of the announcement, U.S. posts abroad were nearly under siege.
   ``The Marine on (weekend) duty in Kuala Lumpur was among the
first to feel the enthusiastic response _ he spent his shift
informing callers they'd have to wait until Monday morning for
information,'' Ms. Jones said the Malaysian embassy reported.
   In the first week, the embassy handed out more than 3,000
information sheets about the program and handled more than 1,000
phone calls. In desperation, the embassy installed a five-minute
telephone recording with information that logged about 100 calls a
day.
   Elsewhere around the world, Ms. Jones said embassies reported
similar situations:
   In Dakar, Senegal, a special telephone hotline was set up, and
the telephone ``has never stopped ringing,'' the embassy reported.
   In Rabat, Morocco, embassy officials put information on bulletin
boards so people waiting in lines could obtain background about the
program. But that didn't stop others from waiting in long lines,
trying to get help with their applications. In Casablanca, the post
handed out 5,000 information sheets in three days.
   In Amman, Jordan, the switchboard operator fielded ``thousands of
calls'' in the days after the program was announced.
   In Dacca, Bangladesh, the embassy reported interest from ``all
segments of society _ from university professors to rickshaw
drivers,'' along with heavy demand for information.
   But the fact that no application form was available appeared to
confuse some, as well as the request that the information required,
such as name, residence and address, be typed ``in the Roman
alphabet'' on a sheet of paper.
   ``More than one application arrived using Roman numerals,'' the
embassy reported.
   The embassy in Dublin, Ireland, reported an ``extraordinary
response'' that ``increased the workload of an already
hard-pressed'' consular unit.
   From the embassy in Suva, Fiji, officials reported being
``besieged'' with telephone calls, requests for information and
letters. More than 1,000 information sheets were handed out.
   ``Tongans, Rotumans, Vanuatuans and others in the South Pacific
are eager to participate,'' in the program, the embassy reported.
Tonga and Vanuatu are independent nations, while Rotuma is an island
grouping that is part of Fiji.
   In contrast, however, the residents of northern Italy and Denmark
seem uninterested in moving to the United States.
   The post in Copenhagen said the announcement did not attract
media attention ``or evoke any great public interest.''
   And even though some 162 requests came to the post in Palermo,
Sicily, ``no inquiries'' were received in the first weeks of the
program in Genoa, Milan, and Rome, Ms. Jones reported.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Mon AMs, March 27</NOTE>
