<FIRST>r f PM-Eastern-Bankruptcy Bjt   03-24 0567</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Eastern-Bankruptcy, Bjt,0586</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eastern Bankruptcy Judge to Appoint Examiner with Broad Powers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARCY GORDON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Embattled Eastern Airlines has been granted its
request for a court-appointed examiner in its bankruptcy
proceedings, but the airline appears to be getting a more powerful
examiner than it wanted.
   In a surprising ruling Thursday, U.S. Bankruptcy Court Judge
Burton Lifland said he would appoint an examiner with unusually
broad powers to oversee strike-bound Eastern during its Chapter 11
reorganization.
   Lifland granted Eastern's request that an examiner be appointed
to review all transactions between Miami-based Eastern and
affiliated airlines. But he decided to give the examiner a broader
mandate than requested by the airline, saying it was in the public's
interest to do so.
   Among other things, the as-yet unnamed examiner would mediate
differences among Eastern employees, creditors and other parties to
achieve a consensus on a bankruptcy reorganization plan, Lifland
said. He described that role as ``banging heads together by an
independent entity.''
   The judge also refused a union request to order Eastern to
release about $24 million in pre-strike paychecks and benefits
frozen when the airline sought protection from creditors on March 9,
five days after the beginning of a strike by its machinists union.
   Eastern's pilots and flight attendants have refused to cross the
machininists' picket lines.
   The unions have asked the bankruptcy court to appoint a trustee
who actually would run the airline during its reorganization,
bumping Texas Air Corp. Chairman Frank Lorenzo from that function.
   An April 7 hearing has been scheduled on the trustee request. But
an attorney for the Air Line Pilots Association indicated the union
might be willing to drop the request, because the powers of the new
examiner would be so sweeping.
   ``It's rather an extraordinary appointment,'' Bruce Simon, who
represented ALPA during Thursday's hearing, told reporters outside
the courtroom. He described the new examiner to be appointed by the
judge as a ``super-mediator'' and a ``super-examiner.''
   Simon said he would be prepared to examine the trustee issue with
Harvey Miller, Eastern's lead bankruptcy attorney. ``We'll look at
the order; we'll make a judgment,'' he said.
   Another participant in the hearing, who asked not to be
identified, also said the scope of the new examiner's mandate was
virtually unprecedented in a bankruptcy proceeding.
   ``We're extremely pleased with the ruling today,'' Eastern
President Phil Bakes said in an interview. ``We wish we had thought
of it,'' he said, referring to the judge's broadening of the
examiner's functions.
   Eastern has said it made the request for an examiner to dispel
arguments by its unions that transactions between Eastern, its
parent Texas Air and its affiliiated acarrier Continental Airlines
were not made in the company's best interests.
   Eastern's unions claim Texas Air has been stripping the airline
of its assets while trying to bolster Continental.
   ``What I'm hearing is a reflection of parochial interests; what
I'm not hearing is the public interest here,'' Lifland told Miller
and Simon after their presentations in front of a packed courtroom.
``The sooner we get into the gut issues here, the better off we
are.''
   Regarding the request to free the paychecks, Lifland said such a
move would be of ``no demonstrable benefit'' to Eastern's estate and
would consume about 10 percent of the company's cash on hand.
   Simon acknowledged that Lifland's decision on the checks was a
setback to Eastern's employees.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
