<FIRST>r f PM-AutoSales Bjt   03-24 0562</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Auto Sales, Bjt,0580</SECOND>
<HEAD>Car, Truck Sales Up 5 Percent in Mid-March</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-Auto Sales-Table</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDERICK STANDISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Car and light truck sales rose 5 percent in
mid-March, but an industry analyst said the improvement doesn't
indicate a turnaround in a slow sales start for 1989.
   The eight U.S.-based auto companies reported Thursday that
vehicles they made sold at an average daily rate of 39,225 during
the March 11-20 period this year, compared with a 37,344-per-day
rate during the same time last year.
   But that didn't impress analyst Ron Glantz of Montgomery
Securities Inc. of San Francisco.
   ``It's very disappointing when you consider that the industry
made the incentives more generous,'' he said.
   During early March, the Big Three automakers, which accounted for
90.3 percent of all the cars sold by the eight companies during the
second 10-day selling period of the month, boosted or extended
existing incentives.
   In mid-March last year, similar incentives were in place.
   ``What I think is happening is that consumers are reacting to
increased interest rates, not automobile rates, though,'' Glantz
said, adding that holders of adjustable rate mortgages may have
recently received notice of higher payments because of increases in
lending rates nationwide.
   Another analyst, Charles Brady of Oppenheimer &amp; Co. of New York,
was more bullish on the industry.
   ``I think a lot of people have been shopping, just kind of
looking for what to buy,'' Brady said. ``Why buy when there's a
chance of snow or rotten weather? Get past Easter Sunday and you
should see sales smooth out at a higher level.''
   ``All you're seeing is that the market is being jerked back and
forth by incentives or lack thereof,'' he said.
   Mid-March sales were bolstered by light trucks, which were
leaving dealer lots in numbers 8.9 percent higher than last year.
Car sales went up 2.8 percent compared with the same period last
year.
   Automakers have been looking for a sales resurgence in March and
April after a sluggish start early this year. Typically, U.S.
consumers head to automobile showrooms during the early spring to
get ready for summertime driving.
   For the year, cars and light trucks are selling at a pace 5.4
percent behind last year's tempo. The automakers sold an average of
34,475 vehicles a day through March 20 this year, compared with a
daily rate of 36,451 during the same period last year.
   Car sales were off 8.2 percent and truck sales were 0.3 percent
lower so far this year than they were during the Jan. 1-March 20
period last year.
   Chrysler Corp. said it sold 16.2 percent fewer cars during
mid-March this year compared with last year, with sales averaging
3,228 a day this year, compared with a 3,850 car-a-day clip last
year.
   Ford Motor Co.'s mid-March car sales were up 6.1 percent this
year and General Motors Corp.'s were 0.2 percent ahead of last
year's sales rate.
   Year-to-date car sales for each of the Big Three were running
behind last year's pace, with Chrysler down 20.7 percent, GM 12.7
percent lower and Ford off 2.1 percent.
   It was a different story for the Big Three on the truck side, as
Ford showed a 10.6 percent increase, Chrysler was up 6.7 percent and
GM's truck sales were 5.5 percent higher in mid-March this year
compared with the same period last year.
</TEXT>
