<FILEID>AP-NR-03-24-89 0315EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Polaroid-Shamrock Bjt   03-24 0401</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Polaroid-Shamrock, Bjt,0415</SECOND>
<HEAD>Delaware Court Frees Polaroid to Buy Back Shares</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DANA KENNEDY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When a Delaware Supreme Court removed all obstacles
to Polaroid Corp.'s buyback of 16 million shares of its common
stock, it apparently dealt a fatal blow to Shamrock Holdings Inc.'s
8-month-old takeover attempt.
   The court on Thursday rejected Shamrock's request for an
extension of a one-week injunction against the buyback plan, an
effort by the instant camera giant to stymie Shamrock's $3.2 billion
takeover bid.
   In response, Shamrock and its affiliates announced plans to
tender to Polaroid all 4.96 million Polaroid shares purchased during
the takeover effort.
   But Michael Sitrick, spokesman for the Burbank, Calif.-based
company, refused to say whether Shamrock would abandon its bid for
Polaroid.
   Earlier this week, another Shamrock spokesman said the company
would not give up its battle for Polaroid even if the court ruled in
favor of the buyback.
   ``It would seem they're on the verge of giving up,'' said Eugene
Glazer, an analyst with Dean Witter Reynolds in New York.
   ``It's somewhat of a fatal shot, almost a shot right to the head
of Shamrock,'' said Alex Henderson, an analyst with Prudential-Bache
Securities in New York. ``Their (Shamrock's sell-back) plan is
symbolically the same thing as throwing in the towel.''
   However, Henderson said, Shamrock is ``unlikely to go away'' and
may still stage a proxy fight although, as a result of the buyback
plan and individual stock ownership, Polaroid will own enough shares
to stop Shamrock.
   Shamrock, controlled by the family of Roy E. Disney, nephew of
the late Walt Disney, planned to wage a proxy fight for control of
Polaroid's board of directors at its as-yet unscheduled annual
meeting.
   ``They could continue to pursue'' a bid, said Glazer, ``but with
those defenses seeming so strong and supported by the Delaware
courts, their ability to get 50 percent of the shares to vote for
them seems very remote.''
   Glazer said the court's endorsement of Polaroid's actions to ward
off a takeover could send a signal to other Delaware-based companies
that defensive strategies will be backed.
   Polaroid has been resisting Shamrock's takeover attempt since
July, when the company made a friendly but unsolicited offer of $40
a share. In January, Shamrock increased the bid to $45.
   Polaroid, based in Cambridge, has approximately 11,000 employees
worldwide and sells instant film packs, cameras, videotapes and
other products.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
