<DOCNO> AP890324-0213 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-24-89 0318EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-IBMOutlook Bjt   03-24 0682</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-IBM Outlook, Bjt,0701</SECOND>
<BYLINE>IBM Denies Slowdown In High Tech Industry</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>By ALAN COOPERMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Top executives of International Business Machines
Corp. tried to allay fears of a high technology slowdown and its
impact on the economy, concerns raised when earnings forecasts were
cut for ``Big Blue'' and Digital Equipment Corp., the nation's
largest computer makers.
   During a meeting of securities analysts Thursday in Boston, the
men who run IBM predicted strong worldwide growth in demand for
computers despite a cooling domestic market.
   They promised to deliver ``kinder, gentler'' computers in the
short term, predicting it would be easier for individuals and more
efficient for companies to use.
   In the long term, they said businesses would find more and more
uses for computers, demanding ever larger amounts of memory capacity
for ``paperless offices'' in which products would be designed
entirely on computers.
   ``Far less than 2 percent of the data that mankind has generated
is coded and stored in any kind of a computer format ... so there is
still tremendous potential for growth,'' said Carl Conti, an IBM
senior vice president.
   IBM Chairman and Chief Executive Officer John F. Akers predicted
the computer industry would continue to grow at two to three times
the rate of the world's economy as a whole.
   But Akers said in an interview after his speech to the 150
analysts that the U.S. budget deficit is a wild card that could
change IBM's hand.
   ``Our financial position as a country is way out of balance,'' he
said. ``It's either going to come into balance, ... or there's going
to continue to be a lot of economic fragility.''
   The stock prices of IBM and its chief competitor, Digital
Equipment, plummeted during the past week when the companies
signaled their earnings in the current quarter would fall below many
analysts' estimates.
   IBM, the industry leader and the most highly capitalized company
in the nation, has blamed its lower earnings forecast on a microchip
manufacturing problem that has slowed delivery of its
top-of-the-line mainframe 3090S computers.
   Production of the chips, which pack up to 2,300 memory circuits
on a fingernail-sized slice of silicon, has proved more difficult
than the company expected. Only 2 or 3 of every 10 chips it turns
out are free of flaws and can be used.
   Digital, the second largest computer maker, said it has seen a
softening of demand for computers in the United States. At the low
end of the market, more and more powerful personal computers and
workstations have cut into sales of the larger and more expensive
minicomputers and mainframes.
   At the meeting Thursday, IBM executives said they have solved the
chip problem and will catch up with the backlog in orders by the end
of the year. They denied that the problem has hurt demand for the
mainframes.
   Because of the manufacturing delays, Wall Street analysts
forecast IBM will earn $10.25 to $10.75 a share this year, down from
previous estimates of $11 to $11.25 per share.
   Several analysts questioned the IBM executives closely about the
company's continuing reliance on sales of computer hardware for
approximately 70 percent of its revenue, while software and computer
services are the fastest growing segments of the market.
   George Conrades, a senior vice president, said IBM realized it
needed to emphasize software development and would begin ``wrapping
our hardware like a burrito'' in software and support services.
   While the IBM executives declined to make specific estimates for
sales or earnings growth this year, they said they expected rapid
increases in the Far East, slower growth in Europe and minor growth
in the United States.
   Akers also said IBM would compete vigorously in the market for
computers that use open, or freely licensed, operating systems based
on Unix, an increasingly popular system developed by American
Telephone &amp; Telegraph Co.
   He said that while IBM faces strong competition from Japanese
computer makers, it is poised to capitalize on heavy demand for
computers in Asia and the construction of computerized manufacturing
facilities by Japanese and Korean companies in the United States.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890324-0214 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-24-89 0320EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-ElectronicTrading     03-24 0598</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Electronic Trading,0617</SECOND>
<HEAD>NYSE Cool To Electronic Stock-Trading Plan</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   New York Stock Exchange officials say they may
look at a 24-hour, electronic stock-trading system being developed
by a competitor, but they appear to be in no hurry to link up with
it.
   ``We're not sure there's interest in that right now,'' said
spokesman Richard Torrenzano. ``We're not sure that there's nough
demand to make the New York Stock Exchange go to 24-hour trading.''
   Nevertheless, Chicago Board Options Exchange President Charles
Henry indicated the New York Stock Exchange may be invited join the
computerized order-matching network for stocks and stock options
being developed by the Options Exchange, the Cincinnati Stock
Exchange and London-based Reuters Holdings PLC.
   ``We certainly have not discussed excluding other exchanges,''
Henry said Thursday in a telephone interview after the project was
announced.
   The network would be similar to electronic trading systems being
developed by Chicago's futures exchanges, theoretically giving
investors around the world 24-hour access to international financial
markets.
   But Torrenzano said the demand for round-the-clock stock trading
is probably limited to only about 100 ``world-class'' stocks such as
IBM and General Motors, some of which are already accessible 24
hours a day because they are listed on overseas exchanges as well on
U.S. boards.
   Officials said they could not estimate a start-up date for the
system, which will require approval from the Securities and Exchange
Commission.
   The Chicago Board Options Exchange owns the majority of
memberships on the Cincinnati Stock Exchange, which lists the 300
largest-volume issues traded on the New York Stock Exchange.
   The Cincinnati exchange is the only fully computerized securities
market in the United States, using a computer to match buy and sell
orders. It averaged 1 million trades per day last year compared with
about 170 million trades per day on the New York Stock Exchange, by
far the nation's largest securities market.
   Henry said the decision to develop an electronic trading system
was a reaction to the increasingly international nature of investing.
   ``Take an IBM,'' he said. ``It's traded by investors in Europe,
in Tokyo, in Singapore, in the United States.''
   ``We're seeing globalization enter into the stock and securities
markets as it has in other markets,'' Henry said. ``We want to be at
the forefront by opening up access to our marketplace.''
   The Chicago Board Options Exchange is the world's largest market
for stock options and stock-index options. A stock option is a right
to buy or sell 100 shares of a given stock at a specified price by a
future date. Stock-index options involve baskets of stocks, such as
those represented by the Standard &amp; Poor's 100 and 500 indexes.
   Investors use stock options to reduce their risks in the stock
market or to speculate on price movements.
   London-based Reuters, a leading vendor of financial information,
would supply the technology for the system through its Instinet
Corp. subsidiary.
   Reuters and the Chicago Mercantile Exchange are developing a
similar system, called Globex, for 24-hour trading of futures
contracts. A future is a binding contract to buy or sell a commodity
or financial instrument at a specified price on a future date.
   Globex is expected to become operational this fall, as is Aurora,
a competing system being developed by the Chicago Board of Trade,
the world's largest futures market.
   Globex already has received commitments from three other futures
exchanges, the New York Mercantile Exchange, the Sydney Futures
Exchange of Australia and the French futures exchange known as
MATIF, to offer some of their products for trading on the system.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890324-0215 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-24-89 0322EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Dow-Sarabond     03-24 0577</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Dow-Sarabond,0599</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dow Sued Over Mortar Additive</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM S. BERGSTROM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Colorado court is trying to determine whether a
mortar additive made by Michigan-based Dow Chemical Co. caused walls
to crumble.
   A bank, hospitals, and now a hotel in Denver are among dozens of
plaintiffs that have sought damages in lawsuits spanning the last
decade stemming from use of the additive, Sarabond. They claim the
substance corrodes metal supports, letting bricks fall or entire
walls sag.
   But Dow says brickwork can deteriorate for many reasons and
argues that its corporate wealth _ $16.68 billion in 1988 revenue _
makes the Midland-based chemical giant an easy ``deep pockets''
target for lawsuits.
   Trial opened Monday in a suit brought by the Executive Tower Inn
in Denver. The hotel is seeking $190 million in actual and punitive
damages from Dow.
   The suit is one of 28 pending cases involving Sarabond, which was
sold by Dow from 1965 to 1976 and used in structures ranging from
hospitals to the Eisenhower Memorial Tunnel in the Rocky Mountains
west of Denver. Additional suits have been settled out of court.
   ``We do remain convinced that Sarabond is not deficient. We are
back in the courtroom this week defending our position,'' Dow
spokeswoman Terri McNeill said.
   Two previous suits have gone to trial and juries found Dow liable
in both, although one is under appeal.
   A 1979 complaint by Central National Bank in Cleveland resulted
in a $28 million damage award and later was settled for $13 million.
   A Johnson Circuit Court jury in Franklin, Ind., on May 3, 1988,
awarded St. Vincent's Hospital in Indianapolis $1.7 million in
actual damages and $5 million in punitive damages. That judgment is
being appealed.
   Meanwhile, new court actions continue to crop up.
   Bronson Methodist Hospital in Kalamazoo filed suit last month,
claiming Sarabond-mortared brickwork on a service-elevator tower
built in the early 1970s was deteriorating. Bronson is asking
damages in excess of $10,000.
   Attorney Bill Dorigan of Minneapolis, who represents the
Executive Tower Inn, Bronson Hospital and other Sarabond plaintiffs,
has said the mortar additive releases chloride similar to road
de-icing salt.
   Metal supports tying the mortared brickwork to the building walls
or frame corrode, bricks or sections of wall crack and loosen, and
in some cases bricks have fallen, Dorigan said.
   He said he knew of no resulting injuries, and structural damage
to buildings has not been involved.
   Dow sold the Sarabond business in 1976 to Masonry Systems
International, and in the early 1980s the product ceased to be
marketed. McNeill said Dow sold the business because Sarabond was
unprofitable.
   Dow maintains the mortar additive did not cause the problems that
led to the lawsuits, McNeill said.
   The company used Sarabond in its own Midland headquarters
buildings as recently as 1981 with no problems, she said.
   Dorigan disputed that, in an interview prior to the Executive
Tower Inn trial. He said he visited the Dow headquarters twice _
after obtaining court orders in two previous lawsuits _ and found
rusted metal and cracked bricks both times.
   Dorigan said more than 20 other suits have been filed that never
came to trial. Dow wouldn't comment on the number of suits settled
or the total amount of the settlements, McNeill said.
   ``There have been settlements over the years,'' she said. ``They
are not an admission of liability. Where we can resolve suits
amicably we do our best to accomplish that.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890324-0216 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-24-89 0750EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-CleanAirRuling     03-24 0570</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Clean Air Ruling,0586</SECOND>
<HEAD>Appeals Court: EPA Can't Evade Acid Rain Question by Inaction</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN M. DOYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal appeals court in Manhattan has ruled
that the U.S. Environmental Protection Agency has to announce what
it's going to do about changing air quality standards _ even if it's
nothing.
   The 2nd U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals, in a 2-to-1 decision, has
ruled that federal district courts can compel the EPA ``to make some
formal decision'' on whether or not to revise air quality standards.
   The decision reversed a lower court ruling that threw out a
lawsuit by seven states and four environmental groups against the
EPA and its administrator, Lee M. Thomas.
   Filed in December 1985, the lawsuit sought to compel Thomas to
update the EPA's ambient air quality standards for sulphur oxides,
which cause acid rain.
   Those sulphur oxide standards, which haven't been revised since
the early 1970s, are used to set legal emission levels for
pollutants the EPA identifies as hazardous.
   While the EPA has revised the criteria for determining air
quality standards, it has taken no public action on the standards
themselves ``neither revising the existing standards nor formally
declining to revise them,'' noted the 2nd Circuit opinion written by
Circuit Judge Ralph K. Winter.
   Judge Ellsworth A. Van Graafeiland concurred but Judge J. Daniel
Mahoney dissented. The ruling was made Wednesday and announced
Thursday.
   The lawsuit was brought by New York, Vermont, Connecticut, New
Hampshire, Massachusetts, Rhode Island and Minnesota as well as the
Environmental Defense Fund, the Natural Resources Council, the
Sierra Club and the National Parks and Conservation Association.
   Last April, U.S. District Judge David N. Edelstein ruled that for
technical reasons he did not have the authority to consider the
lawsuit.
   But the appeals court said that interpretation would leave ``a
bureaucratic twilight zone'' in which EPA action or inaction would
not be subject to court review.
   The 2nd Circuit panel ruled that while it's up to Thomas to
decide what specific changes to make in the air quality standards,
the EPA administrator has a ``duty to make some formal decision'' on
the need to update national air standards.
   The 2nd Circuit noted that shortly after Edelstein's decision,
the EPA announced that it was ``premature and unwise'' to change air
quality standards to address the acid rain problem.
   The appeals court said Edelstein should issue an order directing
the EPA to continue its public decision making process.
   ``This victory could not have come at a better time,'' said New
York Attorney General Robert Abrams in a statement issued by his
office. ``It shows that the EPA has had the power and the duty to
act against acid rain all along, but that it has refused, leading to
needless destruction of forests and waters throughout the
Northeast.''
   Abrams added: ``If the (Bush) administration accepts this
decision without further appeal and updates the standards it will
advance the cause of acid rain reduction.''
   Massachusetts First Assistant Attorney General Gerald Fitzgerald
said in a statement: ``The EPA for too long has taken a no-action
approach to air pollution and acid rain. It is unfortunate that it
takes litigation and a court judgement to force EPA to face up to
its responsibilities under the Clean Air Act. Now that the court has
ruled, we trust EPA will stop pondering the acid rain problem and do
something about it.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
