<FIRST>r f PM-WorldsOfWonder     03-24 0312</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Worlds Of Wonder,0322</SECOND>
<HEAD>Investor To Pay More Than $27 Million To Bail Out Toy Company</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OAKLAND, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Investor Eli Jacobs of New York will pay
$27.6 million to revitalize Worlds of Wonder Inc., according to a
plan of reorganization and disclosure statement filed in U.S.
Bankruptcy Court.
   The documents filed Thursday contain details of a five-year
reorganization of the troubled Fremont toy company, which last month
announced an agreement to sell to investors headed by Jacobs, the
majority stockholder of a group buying the Baltimore Orioles.
   Worlds of Wonder, which began in a trailer in 1985 and saw sales
climb to $300 million with such toys as Lazer Tag and the talking
bear Teddy Ruxpin, filed for protection from creditors under Chapter
11 of bankruptcy laws in December 1987. It owed more than $300
million to creditors.
   According to the reorganization plan, Jacobs has agreed to buy
the company's inventory and assets for $10 million and will pay an
extra $17.6 million for stock and notes.
   Jacobs also will receive licensing rights to the company's
products, with the exception of Worlds of Wonder's Class Acts school
accessories line.
   Worlds of Wonder's major creditor _ the Algemene Bank Nederland
of New York, which is owed $32 million _ will be paid in full, said
Ann Jordan, a WOW lawyer.
   Five other financial institutions are expected to be repaid $30
million of the $78 million they are owed, Jordan said.
   Unsecured creditors, owed a combined $240 million, will be paid a
combined $5 million cash and $1.5 million in preferred stock, Jordan
said.
   Jacobs' partners are Franklyn S. Barry Jr., former president of
Fisher-Price Toys, and David Edleman, president of Sheridan
Companies Inc. of Buffalo. The adequacy of their plan will be
determined at a hearing scheduled for April 10.
   The reorganization proposal also must have the approval of
creditors.
  
</TEXT>
