<FILEID>AP-NR-03-24-89 0803EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-UpjohnMoves     03-24 0266</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Upjohn Moves,0276</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pharmaceutical Company Strengthens Anti-takeover Measures</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KALAMAZOO, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Upjohn Co., unaware of any efforts to
accumulate stock or gain control, nevertheless has strengthened
existing anti-takeover measures, Chairman Theodore Cooper says.
   The pharmaceutical company's board of directors adopted three
changes to a shareholders' rights policy adopted in 1986.
   ``The amendments are intended to reflect developments in case law
and make the plan a more effective deterrent to the abusive takeover
tactics that can be used to deprive shareholders of the full value
of their investment,'' Cooper said Thursday.
   Shareholders now can acquire stock at half-price if any party
acquires 20 percent of Upjohn's outstanding shares. Previously, an
acquirer also had to take other action such as a merger or sale of
assets.
   The market value of Upjohn's outstanding stock totals about $6
billion, meaning an investment of more than $1 billion would be
needed to gain a 20 percent stake.
   Making it easier for current shareholders to obtain additional
stock in the event of a takeover bid would increase the number of
shares outstanding, diluting a would-be acquirer's stake, spokesman
R.D. LaRue said.
   Another amendment would let the board accept Upjohn shares rather
than cash for such transactions _ extending the plan to stockholders
lacking ready cash.
   A third change would let the board carry out the transactions for
up to 30 days after anyone obtained 20 percent or more of the
company's stock, rather than only prior to that time.
   Upjohn, a worldwide manufacturer and marketer of human and animal
health care products and services, had 1988 revenue of $2.75 billion.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
