<FIRST>r f PM-FaultyPacemakers 1stLd-Writethru f0009 03-24 0495</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Faulty Pacemakers, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0009,0507</SECOND>
<HEAD>Company Agrees to Payment for Defective Pacemakers</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: CORRECTS figure in 12th graf, A new, to $700,000 sted $700.
This also moved on general news wires.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAROLYN SKORNECK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A company that admitted selling defective heart
pacemakers has agreed to pay $5 million to settle claims that it
defrauded the government, the Justice Department says.
   The Cordis Corp. in Miami is satisfied with the agreement, said
Chick McDowell, vice president for corporate relations, who noted
that the company already has spent $4 million in legal fees and
associated costs.
   ``What we did is we paid $1 million yesterday with the signing,
and the balance of $4 million will be paid in three equal annual
installments at 7{ percent interest,'' McDowell said Thursday.
   The agreement, announced Thursday by the Justice Department, was
simply to reimburse the government for pacemakers purchased directly
by the Veterans Administration or that were subject to reimbursement
through Medicare and Medicaid programs. It would not provide
payments to anyone who had a faulty pacemaker implanted or the
survivors of anyone who died because of it, said Justice spokeswoman
Amy Brown.
   The Food and Drug Administration has alleged that the devices
could stop without warning, and said that between December 1983 and
October 1985 the company shipped 2,200 pacemakers subject to
potential failure and 6,000 batteries even though it knew they were
subject to corrosion.
   The settlement did not indicate how many pacemakers the
reimbursement covered.
   McDowell said there haven't been any suits brought by those
people who bought the pacemakers themselves or who had them
implanted by the VA.
   Ms. Brown said the settlement would not preclude such individuals
from suing the company.
   John R. Bolton, assistant attorney general in charge of the
department's Civil Division, said the settlement is believed to be
one of the largest Medicare recoveries ever.
   The out-of-court settlemet of civil claims is unconnected with
criminal charges against Cordis, which sold off its pacemaker
business two years ago to Telectronics, an Australian medical device
manufacturer.
   In the criminal case, U.S. District Judge Stanley Marcus in Miami
last October rejected a plea-bargain arrangement between Cordis and
federal prosecutors under which the company would have pleaded
guilty to 23 counts of selling defective pacemakers and would have
paid $123,000 in criminal fines and $141,000 in costs. The judge
said the payment was too low.
   A new agreement is to be presented next week to Marcus, McDowell
said. Under that plan, Cordis would plead guilty to 12 felony and 13
misdemeanor counts and pay the government more than $700,000 in
fines and costs of the investigation, he said.
   The agreement would not affect a separate indictment of four
former Cordis officers, who have all pleaded innocent.
   The company reported net losses of $56.1 million in 1987, but
underwent a major restructuring since selling the pacemaker
operation. Net earnings for 1988 totaled $2.4 million on sales of
$132 million.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
