<FIRST>r f PM-Champion-Cooper     03-24 0495</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Champion-Cooper,0517</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cooper Acquires 83 Percent Of Champion Shares</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MITCH WEISS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOLEDO, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cooper Industries Inc.'s purchase of Champion
Spark Plug Co. probably won't result in immediate changes for the
Toledo manufacturer, an auto analyst says.
   But William Prebe, an independent consultant and formerly Dana
Corp.'s chief economist, said Thursday that some white collar jobs
at Champion's Toledo headquarters are likely to be phased out over
the next year as Houston-based Cooper assumes more control of
Champion.
   ``Cooper will begin to absorb their name into their parts
network. Cooper also will begin to absorb Champion departments into
their operations. After a period of time, they will determine what
they will do with the Toledo operation,'' he said.
   ``But I see some of Champion's management, including department
heads, being let go or assigned new positions,'' he said.
   Cooper announced Thursday that it had purchased 83.2 percent of
Champion common stock, moving it a step closer toward a planned
merger with the spark plug maker.
   When completed, Cooper will have paid $707 million for the 33.6
million outstanding shares of Champion common stock.
   Cooper spokeswoman Ellen Meyers said Thursdsy that the company
bought the shares for $21 a share. Cooper needed 50.1 percent
ownership to take control.
   Champion stock closed at 20], down 1\, in trading on the New York
Stock Exchange Thursday.
   The merger was approved by directors of Cooper and Champion on
Feb. 22.
   ``We're in good shape,'' Ms. Meyers said from the company's
Houston headquarters. ``The merger will go through. The actual legal
merger won't take place until after May 1.''
   After the merger, shares not acquired in the original cash tender
offer will be exchanged for $21 a share in cash, she said.
   The deal, including debt reduction, legal fees and other
considerations, brings the total purchase price to about $800
million, she said.
   The announcement ends nearly two months of speculation and rumors
about a Champion purchase. On Jan. 25, Dana, a Toledo auto parts
firm, offered to buy Champion for $590 million in cash and stock. A
week later, Cooper said it would offer at least $21-a-share cash for
Champion.
   Champion stock has traded above $21 a share on the New York Stock
Exchange, fueling rumors that Cooper would have to up its bid.
   Cooper has not said whether it would move Champion's headquarters
from Toledo to Houston.
   Cooper's tender offer, launched Feb. 23, expired at 12:01 a.m.
Thursday.
   Among the shares tendered were those of Chinook Partners L.P.,
which was established in 1986 by the founding Stranahan family to
maintain a dominant voice in Champion's affairs. It controlled 35
percent of Champion's common Stock.
   Champion is the world's leading manufacturer of spark plugs for
all types of internal combustion engine. It has annual revenue of
about $720 million and employs about 9,200 workers worldwide.
   Cooper, with 1988 revenue of $4.3 billion, makes products for the
electrical, electronic, commercial, industrial, compression and
drilling markets.
</TEXT>
