federal report that compared family incomes from 1973 through 1987.
   According to the study, released this week by the House Ways and
Means Committee, the wealthiest 20 percent of the nation's
households saw, on average, an increase in income over the 15-year
period to $67,416 from $60,299. At the same time, the poorest fifth
experienced a drop to $5,107 from $5,507.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices fell Thursday, wiping out some early gains as talk
on Wall Street intensified about the possibility of a recession in
the not-too-distant future. The Dow Jones industrial average dropped
20.17 points to 2,243.04, extending its loss for the week to 49.10
points.
   The dollar finished higher in uneventful domestic trading. Gold
prices were mostly lower.
   The bond market rose slightly.
   Platinum and silver futures prices fell sharply as the dollar
gained strength. Sugar futures continued a slide; soybeans were
lower while grains were mixed; energy futures advanced; and
livestock and meat futures were mixed.
</TEXT>
