<HEAD>Dollar Mostly Higher In Limited Trading</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Stands for AM-Dollar-Gold</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar moved higher in extremely quiet
domestic trading Friday and rose slightly in limited dealings in
Europe, where most markets were closed for Good Friday.
   Commodities markets were closed worldwide.
   ``Trading was almost nonexistent,'' said Bob Morrissey, a senior
trader at the Bank of Boston's New York office. He said activity had
virtually shut down at about midday.
   ``If anybody had a small position, there was small-position
squaring,'' Morrissey said.
   Earlier in Europe, traders said what little activity existed
fizzled out with the winding down of the Tokyo trading day. Most
leading European financial centers were closed for Good Friday and
will reopen Tuesday.
   In Tokyo, the dollar rose 0.39 Japanese yen to a closing 131.27
yen. Later in Europe, it was quoted at 131.30 yen. In New York, the
dollar traded at 131.48 Japanese yen, up from 131.25 yen late
Thursday.
   In Europe, the British pound fell to $1.7190 from $1.7205 late
Thursday. In New York, sterling declined to $1.7195 from Thursday's
$1.7215.
   Other midday dollar rates in New York, compared with late
Thursday's rates, included: 1.8738 West German marks, up from
1.8715; 1.6275 Swiss francs, up from 1.6264; 6.4000 French francs,
up from 6.3333; 1,377.50 Italian lire, up from 1,376.88, and 1.1905
Canadian dollars, up from 1.1901.
   Other late dollar rates in Europe, compared with late Thursday,
included: 1.8733 West German marks, up from 1.8720; 1.6252 Swiss
francs, down from 1.6260; 6.3350 French francs, up from 6.3315;
2.1138 Dutch guilders, up from 2.1025; 1,376.10 Italian lire, up
from 1,370.12, and 1.1895 Canadian dollars, up from 1.1894.
   Gold and silver bullion markets in New York, London, Zurich and
Hong Kong were closed for the holiday.
