<FIRST>r f BC-Earns-AmericanMedical     03-24 0239</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-American Medical,0249</SECOND>
<HEAD>Profit Down 25 Percent in 2nd Qtr.; Attributed to Sale of Hospitals</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEVERLY HILLS, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   American Medical International Inc.
said Friday its second-quarter profit was 25 percent below levels of
a year ago, primarily because the company sold 36 of its hospitals
to an employee stock plan.
   The health care company said it earned $18.1 million, or 26 cents
a share, in the second quarter, down from $24.1 million, or 30 cents
a share in the second quarter of 1988.
   Sales in the quarter ended Feb. 28 were $678.2 million, down from
$766.1 million a year ago.
   If the previous year's figure was adjusted to remove results from
the hospitals that were sold, the company said, second-quarter sales
would have totaled $611.3 million.
   American Medical owns 55 hospitals and psychiatric treatment
centers in the United States and 20 such facilities overseas.
   The company sold 36 hospitals to EPIC Healthcare, an employee
stock ownership plan, on Sept. 20, 1988.
   First-quarter profits also were depressed by the addition of $13
million to the company's reserve for potential malpractice suits and
$11 million to buy out leases as part of a headquarters
consolidation program.
   In the first six months of this fiscal year, American Medical
earned $18.6 million, or 26 cents a share, down from $63.3 million,
or 76 cents a share a year earlier. Sales were $1.32 billion, down
from $1.51 billion a year earlier.
</TEXT>
