<FIRST>r f AM-Japan-Expo     03-24 0437</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-Expo,0453</SECOND>
<HEAD>Exotic, Futuristic Expositions the Latest Rage in Japan</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELAINE KURTENBACH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Exotic birds, a space camp and azaleas are some of
the attractions tempting travelers this year as cities throughout
Japan join this country's latest fad: the exposition boom.
   On Saturday, the port of Yokohama opens its $775 million
centennial exposition, the Yokohama Exotic Showcase, featuring a
space camp for kids, French and American art collectons and a
high-tech train.
   Yokohama is one of 15 Japanese cities investing millions of
dollars on expositions they hope will attract more Japanese and
foreign visitors and give them a more cosmopolitan image.
   Throughout the spring and summer, Yokohama will be competing for
visitors with the Himeji Shirotopia Exposition 1989 in southern
Japan; Fukuoka's Asian-Pacific Exposition, called Yokatopia;
Yamagata's Omiyage (Souvenir) World and Nagoya's Design Expo '89,
among others.
   The Asian-Pacific Expo in Fukuoka on the southwestern island of
Kyushu is typical of Japanese expositions in that it offers a bit of
something for everyone _ including many attractions only loosely
related to its theme of ``The Quest for New Communication in Our
World.''
   Visitors to the seaside expo site can see Micronesian villages
and exotic Asian birds, watch a three-dimensional movie, ride a
ferris wheel and sample foods from other Asian nations.
   Organizers said they expect more than 6 million visitors to
Yokatopia, which opened March 17 and runs until Sept. 3.
   At Himeji's exposition, which started March 18, visitors can see
a 3-D documentary or wander through a historic commercial
``district'' near the majestic white castle that dominates the city.
   The expositions have the added benefit of giving some cities a
facelift. Fukuoka, for example, has spent millions of dollars to
improve transportation facilities, organizers said.
   Yokohama plans to use revenues from its anticipated 18 million
visitors to help fund a waterfront development project.
   A tally of organizers' estimates shows attendance at expositions
this year could be more than 36 million.
   But the many expositions connected with centennial celebrations
of Japanese cities has raised the risk that some will suffer from
the competition, particularly the smaller ones featuring such
attractions as azalea displays, souvenirs and food.
   Last year, of the 14 expositions staged throughout Japan, at
least two lost a lot of money. The Sapporo World Food Festival on
the northern island of Hokkaido reportedly lost more than $62
million and another festival near the Seto Bridge in southwestern
Japan lost $651,000.
   Expositions aren't cheap. Tickets for this year's events cost
between $9 and $21 for adults and $5 to $10 for students _ prices
that make family visits expensive.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890324-0236 </DOCNO>
