<HEAD>General Motors To Shut Down Linden Production Plant For Week</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LINDEN, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A General Motors Corp. plant in Linden will
be shut down next week to reduce inventories of Chevrolet Corsica
and Beretta cars, affecting about 140 assembly line workers, the
company said Friday.
   ``It's been decided that we need a week to bring our inventory to
what it needs to be,'' GM spokeswoman Nettie Seabrooks said.
   Ward's Automotive Reports, a weekly trade journal, said that as
of Feb. 28, the company had a 103-day supply of the Corsica-Beretta
cars on hand. GM's inventory for new cars was 83 days compared with
the 78 days in the domestic industry, according to Ward's.
   Ms. Seabrooks said the shutdown would not affect the entire work
force because some employees would be training at the plant,
scheduled to resume production April 3.
