<FIRST>r f AM-Polaroid-Shamrock     03-24 0416</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Polaroid-Shamrock,0430</SECOND>
<HEAD>Shamrock May Lose But Still Come Out Richer, Analysts Say</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN COOPERMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Shamrock Holdings Inc. may have lost its battle to
acquire Polaroid Corp., but it is likely to walk away with a $40
million profit before expenses, analysts estimated Friday.
   Polaroid has yet to claim victory, and Shamrock has not conceded
defeat, but Wall Street analysts said the eight-month fight for
control of the instant photography company was essentially over.
   Shamrock, which offered $45 a share for Polaroid stock, was
stymied Thursday by a Delaware court decision clearing the way for
Polaroid to repurchase 16 million shares for $50 each.
   Polaroid spokesman Sam Yanes said stockholders had tendered a
total of 58.6 million shares to the Cambridge-based company by
Thursday's midnight deadline.
   Since that is roughly four times more shares than Polaroid plans
to buy, the company will pro-rate the number of shares it accepts
from each stockholder. Based on preliminary calculations, it
expects to buy 27 percent of the shares tendered by each owner,
Yanes said.
   Shamrock, which amassed 4.95 million Polaroid shares during the
takeover battle, tendered all of its shares, said Michael Sitrick,
a spokesman for the Burbank, Calif.-based radio and television
concern.
   According to filings with the Securities and Exchange
Commission, Shamrock paid an average of about $31 a share for its
stake in Polaroid. By selling 27 percent of its shares back to
Polaroid at $50 each, Shamrock can expect to receive approximately
$67 million.
   The value of Shamrock's remaining shares is uncertain because
many analysts expect Polaroid's stock, which closed Thursday at
$40.25 on the New York Stock Exchange, to slip to $38 or $37 a
share after the buyback, said Alex Henderson, an analyst for
Prudential-Bache Securities Inc.
   Still, Shamrock's remaining 3.6 million Polaroid shares would
conservatively be worth more than $130 million, yielding a profit
of approximately $42 million before legal fees and other expenses.
   Polaroid said the final number of shares tendered under the
buyback offer and the definitive pro-rating formula will be
determined April 4.
   Shamrock still has appeals pending before the Delaware Supreme
Court on Polaroid's employee stock ownership plan and its sale of
$300 million in stock to Corporate Partners, a New York City-based
investment group that supports Polaroid's current management.
   Shamrock has not called off its proxy fight for control over
Polaroid's board of directors, even though tendering its shares
under the buyback plan sharply decreases its chance of winning that
fight.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
