<FIRST>a f BC-WeeklyWallStreet Adv25-26   03-24 0651</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Weekly Wall Street, Adv 25-26,0677</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv25</HEAD>
<HEAD>$adv26</HEAD>
<HEAD>REPEAT FOR ALL NEEDING</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Weekend Editions March 25-26</HEAD>
<HEAD>Hopes Persist For Lower Interest Rates</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHET CURRIER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   While the headlines focus on inflation worries
and tighter credit, some Wall Street analysts are sticking with
their forecasts that interest rates are headed lower soon.
   They contend that the economy sent out signals in February that
it was beginning to slacken, even though the producer price index
of goods traded at the wholesale level jumped 1 percent for the
second straight month.
   And they maintain that more evidence of a slowdown in growth is
coming soon, helping to persuade both bond traders and the Federal
Reserve that further increases in interest rates aren't needed to
restrain inflation.
   On Wednesday the Commerce Department is scheduled to report the
index of leading economic indicators for February.
   Peter Greenbaum at Smith Barney, Harris Upham &amp; Co. projects
that the index, which is designed to detect future swings in the
economy, will post a drop of about 0.5 percent. That would mark the
first decline in five months.
   ``A modest uptrend in inflation rates has taken hold, but the
market may be exaggerating the potential extent of the rise,''
Smith Barney said in its economic commentary for the week ahead.
   ``February economic data have been surprisingly soft. The
market's preoccupation with inflation suggests that this may have
been overlooked.
   ``Will today's inflation fears give way to recession fears over
the next two quarters?''
   Recession fears might be something less than a balm for the
stock market, but they would logically stand to benefit the market
for Treasury bonds.
   If bond traders were expecting the economy to slacken, they
might well bid aggressively for government securities to profit
from any approaching decline in interest rates.
   Joseph Barthel, an analyst at Butcher &amp; Singer Inc., maintains
that ``evidence is mounting that during the second quarter an
important peak in interest rates should occur.''
   Barthel says one significant signal in this direction has been a
decline since last summer in commodity prices, as measured by the
Commodity Research Bureau's futures index.
   Many bond market participants watch commodity price indexes
closely as a guide to what future trends in inflation might look
like.
   Past peaks in interest rates have come about 10 months after the
CRB futures index crested, Barthel says.
   ``About nine months ago we forecasted that the second quarter of
1989 was likely to produce an important low'' for bond prices, he
says.
   ``Although recent inflation data would seem to argue that
interest rates must move higher, we stand by our earlier forecast.''
   Whether the problem was inflation and interest rate worries or
increased talk of a recession, the stock market showed little zip
in the past week, shortened by one trading day in observance of
Good Friday. The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials dropped 49.10
to 2,243.04.
   The New York Stock Exchange composite index fell 2.02 to 162.64;
the NASDAQ composite index for the over-the-counter market dropped
1.25 to 400.94, and the American Stock Exchange market value index
was down 3.49 at 324.87.
   Volume on the Big Board averaged 148.40 million shares a day,
down from 177.28 million the week before.
   Last Monday, Merrill Lynch &amp; Co. made a modest shift from stocks
to cash in its guidelines for the allocation of investors' assets.
   ``Clearly, the pressure is on the Federal Reserve to tighten its
credit policy,'' said Charles Clough, Merrill's chief investment
strategist.
   ``However, we believe that most of the upward pressure on rates
will remain at the short end of the yield curve and that any move
up from here in long-term Treasury bond yields will be limited in
time and degree.
   ``We believe that this rise in long-term rates will prove to be
an opportunity to lock in attractive yields.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Weekend Editions March 25-26</NOTE>
