<FILEID>AP-NR-03-24-89 2032EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a f BC-RJR-Nabisco-Future Adv27   03-24 0923</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-RJR-Nabisco-Future, Adv 27,0951</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv27</HEAD>
<HEAD>For release Monday, March 27</HEAD>
<HEAD>New CEO `Up To Eyeballs' Learning Company; Asset Sales Said Likely</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARC RICE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   With a few days remaining before he begins work
as the new head of RJR Nabisco Inc., Louis V. Gerstner was said to
be absorbed in learning about his new company and analysts
suggested he would take office ready to sell some of the tobacco
and food giant's assets.
   Gerstner, who takes over as chairman and chief executive officer
of the Atlanta-based RJR Nabisco April 3, has not said what his
specific plans are for the company, recently acquired by Kohlberg
Kravis Roberts &amp; Co. for $24.53 billion, the largest debt-financed
takeover in history.
   But analysts say Gerstner, who is leaving as president of
American Express Co. to head RJR Nabisco, probably will decide to
sell some of the company's brands to raise money to help pay off
the debt, including $3 billion in annual interest payments, picked
up by KKR with the acquisition.
   ``I think that's very much the case,'' said Emanuel Goldman, an
industry analyst with PaineWebber Group Inc. in San Francisco.
``That, I think, is in the forefront (to reduce the debt)...to sell
for as much as you can as quickly as you can.''
   Layoffs are possible but not certain, Goldman said. Personnel
moves could come after RJR Nabisco's divestiture _ with the new
owners of whatever divisions are sold making the decisions, he said.
   RJR Reynolds Tobacco USA, a subsidiary, announced last week that
about 700 employees will be offered early retirement enhancements
or cash incentives to leave their jobs voluntarily. But the move to
cut the workforce stemed from the failure of RJR's smokeless
cigarettes, not the KKR takeover.
   Goldman said the RJR Nabisco assets likely for sale _ including
Del Monte Foods and Planters-Life Savers _ are attractive holdings.
   ``Look at the cookies, the crackers, Del Monte, Planters, Life
Savers. This is not so bad. You have the creme de la creme of some
of the business,'' he said.
   ``I don't think they'll know what they'll end up selling until
they see what their actual value is,'' Goldman added.
   KKR has retained Goldman, Sachs &amp; Co., reportedly to study a
possible sale of the RJR Nabisco subsidiary Del Monte.
   On March 13, the day KKR announced his appointment, Gerstner
said his new job was ``the greatest challenge in corporate
America.'' Since then, the native of Long Island, N.Y., has
declined requests for interviews.
   Pauline A. Howes, a spokeswoman for RJR Nabisco in Atlanta,
said, ``For the time being, he's up to his eyeballs in RJR Nabisco
immersion. He's going to take a month or two to get settled and
learn more about the company's operations.''
   Gerstner, at this point, won't publicly reveal his vision for
the company, Ms. Howes said.
   Financial concerns aside, asset sales are considered likely
because the Federal Trade Commission required some as part of the
regulatory approval process for the takeover.
   The FTC, responsible for preventing monopolies by enforcing
antitrust laws, said it would not challenge the takeover if KKR
within a year sells:
   _The Chun King oriental food line of RJR Nabisco or the La Choy
line of Beatrice-Hunt-Wesson Inc., a unit of KKR.
   _The Planters nuts line of RJR Nabisco or the Fisher nuts line
of Beatrice.
   _RJR Nabisco's Del Monte ketchup or Beatrice's Hunt ketchup.
   The commission said unless those units were divested, the
combined market share could result in unfair consumer pricing.
Together, RJR Nabisco and KKR's prior holdings account for
one-eighth of the food sold in U.S. supermarkets.
   Goldman said there is no doubt the FTC directive will be
followed, but he said the specific items named by the government do
not amount to a major portion of the company's business.
   Gerstner replaces the aggressive, flamboyant CEO F. Ross
Johnson, who left RJR Nabisco after losing to KKR in the
high-stakes takeover battle. Gerstner, 47, hugely successful during
his 11 years at American Express, has been described as a
methodical executive unafraid of shaking up a company.
   He reportedly will start at RJR Nabisco with a $2.3 million
annual salary and has received a signing bonus of more than $10
million.
   Lawrence Adelman, a tobacco industry analyst with Dean Witter
Reynolds in New York, said that Gerstner is coming into a company
that already is ``very well run'' and he should not face any
immediate crises.
   ``Kohlberg Kravis Roberts has a lot of experience in the food
area,'' he added. ``It's not new to them, though it's new to him
(Gerstner). I'm sure he'll zero in and try to maximize his
opportunities.''
   Other analysts have said Gerstner's immediate tasks include
giving RJR Nabisco employees a firm sense of direction in the wake
of last year's bruising takeover fight and reversing the company's
loss, over the last few years, of its share of the domestic tobacco
market.
   If RJR Nabisco sells some food lines, tobacco will become even
more important because it will command a larger chunk of the
company's earnings, said John G. Nelson, an industry analyst with
Brown Brothers Harriman in New York. Currently, tobacco accounts
for about two-thirds of RJR Nabisco income.
   Also on the horizon could be a move of the company's
headquarters from Atlanta. A relocation to RJR Nabisco's former
home in Winston-Salem, N.C., has been rumored for months.
   Johnson moved RJR Nabisco from Winston-Salem, its home for more
than 100 years, to suburban Atlanta in 1987.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End adv for Monday, March 27</NOTE>
