<FILEID>AP-NR-03-24-89 2028EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>d f PM-Eastern-FlightAttendant     03-24 0413</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Eastern-Flight Attendant,0427</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eastern Flight Attendant Has Her Own Bankruptcy Plan</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEFAN FATSIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Eastern Airlines flight attendant with 21
years' experience has her own plan to get striking employees back
to work.
   Marsha Atkins of Watkinsville, Ga., is filing a motion asking
U.S. Bankruptcy Court to appoint a supplemental trustee to run the
airline and to allow workers to return immediately at reduced pay.
   The motion, which her attorney husband Samuel Atkins sent to the
court on Thursday, suggests that thousands of striking Eastern
employees want to return to work, as long as it's not for Texas Air
Corp. Chairman Frank Lorenzo.
   ``Even though they're frustrated not working, they'd rather be
frustrated than working for Lorenzo,'' Samuel Atkins said in a
telephone interview Friday.
   Under Atkins' plan, if the court appointed a trustee to run the
airline instead of Lorenzo, who runs Eastern's parent carrier,
workers could return at 75 percent of pre-strike pay. The remaining
25 percent of their pay would accrue until Eastern reorganized
under Chapter 11 of federal bankruptcy laws.
   ``I was sort of frustrated by nothing happening in the case. She
was too,'' Samuel Atkins said. ``Everyone was trying to do
something to help the attorneys and the investment bankers. But no
one wants to do anything for the employees. They want to go back to
work.''
   Eastern's Machinists struck the carrier March 4 and pilots and
flight attendants are honoring the walkout. The airline sought
Chapter 11 protection from creditors on March 9.
   Eastern's pilots and Machinists already have asked Bankruptcy
Judge Burton R. Lifland to appoint a trustee to run the airline's
day-to-day operations, removing company management from that role.
   A clerk for Lifland said Friday that she was unaware of the
Atkins motion.
   Atkins said his wife was filing as a creditor owed $858.21 in
back pay.
   Lifland has scheduled an April 7 hearing on the pilots' trustee
request. Atkins said he hoped to bring a busload of employees from
Georgia to attend the hearing, at which he expects his motion to be
heard.
   Atkins, who lives in a town with a population of 2,000 about 60
miles northeast of Atlanta, admitted that a motion by one employee
was a tiny cry in proceedings dominated by powerful union and
corporate players.
   ``It's highly unusual,'' he said. ``This is an unusual case
anyway. We though it was worth a shot. It was definitely in the
public interest.''
</TEXT>
