<DOCNO> AP890324-0251 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-24-89 0747EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-Polaroid-Siege Adv26 2ndLd-Writethru 03-24 0677</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Polaroid-Siege, Adv 26, 2nd Ld-Writethru,0700</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv26</HEAD>
<HEAD>For release Sunday, March 26</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Polaroid Employees, Takeover Is Fearful Prospect</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 7th, 13th and 18th grafs to change verb tense.</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-Circling the Wagons</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN COOPERMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CAMBRIDGE, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   If it worked for the Chicago Bears,
Polaroid employees figured, it might work for them too.
   So one day earlier this month, booming over the speakers in the
lunchroom at Polaroid's film plant in Norwood, Mass., came the
company's new fight song.
   ``Used to have it all,'' it goes. ``But one man has come. He
wants to break up what we've done. Cut out the heart, and take the
money and run.''
   While that ``one man'' remained nameless in the song, his
identity was no mystery to anyone at the instant-camera giant.
   The clear villain of the piece was Stanley Gold, president of
Shamrock Holdings Inc., the Burbank, Calif., company that launched a
hostile takeover bid for Polaroid last July.
   It appeared this past week the takeover battle might be over.
Unable to defeat Polaroid's defensive strategy in court, Shamrock
said it was selling its stock under a Polaroid share buyback plan.
But Shamrock didn't say it was giving up.
   Although Shamrock is owned by the family of Roy E. Disney, nephew
of the late Walt Disney, it was Gold, a 46-year-old Hollywood
entertainment lawyer turned takeover specialist, who came to
personify the threat to Polaroid workers.
   As the eight-month-old takeover battle became increasingly
bitter, preoccupying top executives and filling the rank-and-file
with apprehension, Polaroid workers united passionately in
opposition to Shamrock and Gold.
   Nearly 6,000 of the company's 8,300 employees in Massachusetts
signed petitions against the takeover. The Employees Committee, a
32-member group elected to represent workers, was solidly behind
Polaroid's current chief executive, I. MacAllister Booth.
   ``Basically, it comes down to this,'' said Committee Chairman
Nicholas R. Pasquarosa. ``We don't want anything to do with Stanley
Gold.''
   Shamrock said the personality of its president is irrelevant.
   ``Making it personal _ that's a public relations maneuver to
obscure the issues,'' said Shamrock spokesman John Grimaldi. ``You
create a straw man so everyone focuses on that instead of on the
poor management of Polaroid.''
   Yet the employee campaign against Gold, if it was one, was so
homespun it belied a Madison Avenue effort.
   The not-exactly-catchy fight song, for example, was recorded by
Carl Saunders, a 40-year-old Polaroid lab technician who ``played a
little guitar in the '60s'' but hasn't done much musically since.
   While he got lots of help from his wife, Cindy, their two
children and friends, Saunders said, Polaroid didn't contribute a
dime.
   What's more, he admitted, he dreamed up the song mainly to give
his 16-year-old daughter, Kerry, a boost toward a singing career.
   ``I just thought it might get her some exposure,'' he said.
   Employee attitudes have been an important element in the battle
for Polaroid, because they were also stockholders, controlling
nearly 14 percent of the company's stock through an employee stock
ownership plan.
   Their attitudes were clear. Throughout its Cambridge headquarters
and manufacturing plants, Polaroid employees wore or hawked $10
T-shirts. They come in a choice of six colors, but all bore the same
message: ``Polaroid Family Says No To Stanley.''
   At the headquarters, four beige brick buildings around a
courtyard called Technology Square, one of the most popular
gathering places was a bulletin board with the latest news Wall
Street takeover battles, including Polaroid's.
   Librarian Richard Gurner, who posted the clippings each day, said
the most sought-after books in the corporate library were also about
high finance, reflecting ``a tremendous thirst'' in employees to
understand what was happening to them.
   Rather than an orchestrated campaign, Gurner believed the anger
toward Gold results from employees' attempts to put the conflict
into comprehensible terms.
   ``We know it's not just one man, because the same thing is
happening to other companies,'' he said. ``But we see our jobs
threatened, the company we have built threatened, and he is the one
we blame.''
   End Adv for Sunday March 26
</TEXT>
