<FILEID>AP-NR-03-24-89 0128EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-FormicaOffer     03-24 0266</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Formica Offer,0281</SECOND>
<HEAD>Formica Corp. Says Its Offered $20 Cash Per Share</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WAYNE, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Formica Corp., facing a bevy of buyout offers,
announced Thursday it received a $256 million bid that tops a $230.4
million tender offer from a management-led group.
   Formica officials declined to identify the company that made the
latest, $20-per-share cash offer, but said Formica's committee of
independent directors instructed Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc. to
begin negotiations with the company.
   Last fall, Malcolm Glazer, a Rochester, N.Y., businessman offered
$20 a share in cash and securities for Formica and was rebuffed.
After the management group announced its offer, Glazer said he was
considering a new bid.
   However it was not known if the latest bid was from Glazer.
   Shearson also is continuing discussions with six other interested
third parties, Formica spokesman Robert Way said.
   The management group, FM Acquisition Corp., has offered $18 a
share for Formica, which manufactures laminated products used in
kitchen countertops, tables and cabinets.
   Formica has said its directors have approved a definitive merger
with FM, but they also told Shearson to see if others might be
interested in bidding.
   Formica stock fell $1 a share to $21 in New York Stock Exchange
composite trading Wednesday.
   Glazer, who owns television stations, nursing homes and real
estate, dropped his bid in November after Formica President Vincent
P. Langone _ who heads the management group _ said the company
wasn't for sale.
   Glazer sold his 1.09 million-share stake in Formica last November
to Chicago-based Great American Realty Inc. It is not known if he
owns any Formica shares.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
